<html>
<head>
<meta http-equiv="Content-Type"
content="text/html; charset=iso-8859-1">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 2.0">
<title>LAWS PERTINENT TO WATER AND WASTEWATER ISSUES </title>
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/images/whttxtr1.jpg"
bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p><strong>VII. LAWS PERTINENT TO WATER AND WASTEWATER ISSUES</strong> <br
wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>
<p>O.C.G.A. Sections 12-5-520 thru 12-5-525 requires the director
to develop river basin plans for specific rivers including the
Chattahoochee, Coosa, Flint and the Ocmulgee. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>
<p>O.C.G.A. Section 12-7 et. seq. requires a comprehensive
statewide soil erosion and sedimentation control program to
protect and conserve air, land, and water resources through the
adoption and implementation of local ordinances and programs
which regulate certain land disturbing activities generally
associated with urban development. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>
<p>House Bill 1788 requires the Board to establish turbidity
standards. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>
<p>Senate Bill 500 (ACT 1042) requires specific sanctions against
Atlanta for failure to meet phosphorus standards, establishes new
phosphorous limits for the Chattahoochee River, establishes
specific schedules and sanctions for CSO's for Atlanta. It also
requires certain assessments of water quality by the director
prior to the issuance of any permits for river basin transfer for
wastewater disposal and allows a 10% reduction in permit capacity
for a permit violation during July 1, 1996 to July 1, 1997. <br
wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>
<p>OC.G.A. Section 43-51 et. seq. requires that all operators of
water treatment, water distribution, wastewater treatment and
wastewater collection facilities obtain a certificate from the
state. It also requires that all analysts that perform tests, as
defined by the Board, in conjunction with the operation with a
water treatment or wastewater treatment plant, obtain a
certificate from the state. This section also delegates
classification of plants to EPD and allows EPD to require
certification in permits which EPD issues. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>
<p>O.C.G.A. Section 1205 et.seq. requires that all direct
discharges of wastewater to a stream or to a land disposal site
obtain a permit from the division; requires permits for certain
indirect dischargers to municipal sewer systems; requires the
division to establish water quality standards, lake water quality
standards, and water use classifications; <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>
<p>House Bill 228 authorizes the department to adopt technical
and procedural rules governing sludge land application systems. <br
wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>
<p>O.C.G.A. Section 12-5-543, the Metropolitan River Protection
Act (MRPA) requires protection of the Chattahoochee River
corridor defined as all land within 2000 feet of the riverbanks
between Buford Dam and Peachtree Creek. It requires the Atlanta
Regional Commission to develop and administer a plan for
protecting the water and land resources of the corridor. <br
wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>
<p>O.C.G.A.Sections 12-5-90 through 12-5-107 (Ground-Water Use
Act of 1972, as amended): requires persons to obtain a permit
from EPD prior to withdrawing, obtaining or using ground waters
in excess of 100,000 gallons per day. Law also requires the
issuance of a permit for ground water withdrawn for farm uses. <br
wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>
<p>O.C.G.A. Section 12-5-31 (Georgia Water Quality Control. Act):
requires persons to obtain a permit from EPD prior to
withdrawing, diverting or impounding surface waters in excess of
100,000 gallons per day on a monthly average. Law also requires
monitoring, recording and reporting of surface water withdrawn by
certain irrigation systems. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>
<p>In 1994, the Georgia General Assembly passed a new lay (Senate
Bill 10) which amended Chapter 5 of Title 12 of O.C.G.A. and
required the Board of Natural Resources to adopt rules and
regulations to the conduct, content and submission of water
conservation plans required by Code Sections 12-5-31 (Surface
Water Withdrawals) and 12-5-96 (Ground Water Withdrawals). <br
wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>
<p>O.C.G.A. Sections 12-5-170 through 12-5-193 (Georgia Safe
Drinking Water Act of 1977, as amended): law defines public water
systems and requires the EPD to regulate the quality of the
public drinking waters; the installation, use and operation of
public water systems; cross-connection control; laboratory
certification; and methods and means for treating and furnishing
water to the public of the state by way of public water systems.
All public water systems are required to obtain a permit to
operate from EPD. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>
<p>O.C.G.A. Sections 8-2-1 through 8-2-3 (Georgia's Water
Conservation Act of 1990, as amended by H.B. No. 605): requires
public water systems to adopt an ordinance requiring the
installation of ultra-low plumbing fixtures in new residential
and commercial construction after July 1, 1992 in order to be
eligible to receive any state funding for water and wastewater
facilities. </p>
</body>
</html>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT17-B32-18</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA093-001005-B013-158</DOCOLDNO>
