<html>

<head>
<title>Water Quality Management Program</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<h1 align=center>Water Quality Management Program</h1>
<p align=center><strong>W. M. Winn III</strong>, Program Manager<br>
#7 Martin Luther King, Jr. Dr S.W., Suite 643<br>
Atlanta, Georgia 30334<br>
Telephone: (404) 656-4905 | Fax: (404) 657-7031<br>
</p>
<hr>
<h3 align=center><a name="goal">GOAL</a></h3>
<p>To conduct intensive surveys and trend monitoring of Georgia's surface waters, conduct water quality modeling and develop 
wasteload allocations, carry out river basin management planning, conduct aquatic toxicity testing, and implement the urban, 
agricultural, and commercial forestry nonpoint source programs as a part of the overall Water Protection Branch nonpoint 
source pollution control program. </p>
<hr>
<h3 align=center><a name="objectives">OBJECTIVES</a></h3>
<ol>
<li>To conduct intensive surveys on streams, lakes, and estuaries. Stream surveys will be conducted to provide specific 
information for mathematical models; impact studies will be conducted to collect information concerning special problem 
areas; document water quality conditions, and investigate nonpoint source problems.</li>
<li>To operate the Georgia trend monitoring network and use the EPA STORET system to manage trend monitoring data.</li>
<li>To build, calibrate, and verify mathematical water quality models and to develop critical period models for wasteload 
allocations and the analysis of other water quality management issues.</li>
<li>To prepare and assign, based on water quality modeling efforts, wasteload allocations as requested for new or 
expanding municipal or industrial facilities, or in response to needs associated with NPDES permit issuance.</li>
<li>To conduct river basin management planning as resources are available in accordance with Senate Bill 637 passed by 
the Georgia General Assembly in 1992.</li>
<li>To conduct acute and chronic toxicity tests on facility effluents to address whole effluent toxicity and to provide 
information for permitting decisions. Also to conduct tests on stream samples in support of intensive surveys.</li>
<li>To coordinate and manage Section 319 Nonpoint Source Pollution Control grant funds (partially matched by Georgia) 
for urban, forestry, agriculture, adopt-a-stream, and education projects.</li>
<li>To overview and support voluntary, non-regulatory nonpoint source control programs conducted by the Georgia Soil 
and Water Conservation Committee (agricultural nonpoint source issues), the Georgia Forestry Commission (forestry 
nonpoint source issues), and develop urban programs for the control of nonpoint source pollutants.</li>
<li>To conduct monitoring of water quality at major public access lakes in Georgia to document water quality conditions 
and trophic status. To increase emphasis as resources are available on assessment of major publicly owned lakes (1000 
acres or greater) and development of standards in accordance with Senate Bill 714 passed in 1990.</li>
<li>To coordinate and manage Section 314 Clean Lakes Grants provided to Georgia by the USEPA. Phase I 
Diagnostic/Feasibility projects are underway on Lakes West Point, Lanier, Allatoona, Walter F. George, and 
Blackshear. Georgia is also conducting a fish tissue evaluation project on major publicly owned lakes using Clean Lakes 
Assessment funds provided by the USEPA and matched in part by the State of Georgia.</li>
<li>To review and update the Georgia Continuing Planning Process (CPP) as appropriate.</li>
<li>To coordinate the review and research on water quality standards issues for the Water Protection Branch.</li>
<li>To support other programs within the Division by providing water quality related environmental data and technical 
assistance for the completion of work described elsewhere in this Implementation Plan. Reviews of proposed water 
effects ratio study plans and reports by industries are examples of this technical assistance.</li>
<li>To refine the data gathering resources within the Division to insure future information needs are met. Computerized data 
collection, desktop geographic mapping systems, and fish tissue assessment procedures are examples of expanded data 
gathering and handling methods developed in recent years.</li>
<li>To examine and develop analytical modeling methods necessary to solve current problems and to address those issues 
anticipated in the future. An example of this will be the work on a dynamic model of the Chattahoochee River from 
Buford Dam to Franklin to be continued in FY 1995.</li>
</ol>
<hr>
