<html>

<head>
<title>Industrial Wastewater Program</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<h1 align=center>Industrial Wastewater Program</h1>
<p align=center><strong>Larry Hedges</strong>, Program Manager<br>
205 Butler Street SE, Suite 1070 East<br>
Atlanta, Georgia 30334<br>
Telephone: (404) 656-4887 | Fax: (404) 657-7379<br>
</p>
<hr>
<h3 align=center><a name="goal">GOAL</a></h3>
<p>To process and issue enforceable NPDES permits to each industrial and federal wastewater discharger in Georgia; to 
determine on a continuing basis whether or not each industrial or federal wastewater discharger is in compliance with its 
NPDES permit; to insure on a continuous basis that violations of State water quality laws, permit limitations, and compliance 
schedules by industrial and federal wastewater dischargers are responded to by the State and resolved between the State and 
the discharger in a timely and appropriate manner through appropriate enforcement actions, including the required upgrading of 
wastewater treatment facilities; to provide for protection of water quality through project reviews, identification of alternatives, 
and special conditions of Section 401 water quality certifications; to implement an effective toxics control program; to place 
increased emphasis on protection of the environment from agricultural practices, concentrated feedlot operations, and trout 
farms; to actively support the Division's antidegradation procedures; to control storm water runoff from industrial activities 
through best management practices and permits for point source dischargers; and to effectively provide environmental 
permitting guidance to potential new industries through participation in the Division's new industry team. </p>
<hr>
<h3 align=center><a name="objectives">OBJECTIVES</a></h3>
<ol>
<li>To issue, reissue, or reopen for reissuance the NPDES permits to industrial and federal dischargers, both new and 
existing, as appropriate, with effluent limitations which provide for achievement of water quality standards, toxics 
control, and U.S. EPA effluent guidelines as they are promulgated.</li>
<li>To issue, reissue, or reopen for reissuance the Land Application System (LAS) permits to industrial and federal 
dischargers, both new and existing, as appropriate. LAS permits will require no discharge of wastewater or 
contaminated storm water runoff to surface waters.</li>
<li>To continue the NPDES storm water program which is based upon issuance of NPDES general permits for point 
source discharges of storm water runoff associated with industrial activity, with emphasis on outreach efforts and 
technical assistance. To implement a strategy to identify the universe of regulated industrial facilities required to have 
NPDES permits for storm water discharges.</li>
<li>To monitor and determine violations of NPDES and LAS permits for industrial and federal dischargers, and perform 
inspections as appropriate to assess compliance with NPDES and LAS permits.</li>
<li>To resolve industrial and federal NPDES and LAS permit violations in an effective and expeditious manner by initiating 
and completing appropriate enforcement actions including letters and Notices of Violations, Consent Orders, 
Administrative Orders, and Directives, based upon available information including but not limited to inspections, 
sampling, and discharge monitoring reports.</li>
<li>To implement the biomonitoring requirements in NPDES permits for industrial and federal discharges, as needed, to 
control toxic pollutants, including priority pollutants as well as ammonia and chlorine. When appropriate, the effluent 
limitations will also consist of chemical-specific numerical limitations for toxic pollutants for State water quality standards 
in effect at the time that permits are issued or reissued.</li>
<li>To closely monitor permits with compliance schedules to insure that the water quality-based effluent limitations for toxic 
pollutants are attained. When appropriate, Orders will be issued with compliance schedules for facilities which have 
demonstrated a good faith effort but have been unable to meet their final discharge limitations for toxics.</li>
<li>To provide coordinated engineering and regulatory reviews of plans for wastewater treatment, wastewater land 
application and sludge disposal to assure that the design alternatives chosen are technically appropriate, well engineered, 
and feasible for implementation.</li>
<li>To provide engineering reviews of plans for industrial pretreatment facilities at POTW's which do not administer their 
own pretreatment programs to assure that the design alternatives chosen are technically appropriate, well engineered, 
and feasible for implementation.</li>
<li>To issue or deny Section 401 water quality certifications as appropriate and to incorporate special conditions in Section 
401 certifications as needed for protection of water quality. To participate in the review of plans and to help identify 
new alternatives or options that protect water quality.</li>
<li>To actively support the Division's antidegradation procedures through the wasteload allocation/permit application 
review/quality assurance process.</li>
<li>To insure the quality and reliability of Discharge Monitoring Report data submitted by industrial and federal dischargers 
through active use of the Discharge Monitoring Report Quality Assurance (DMR QA) Program.</li>
<li>To assure that Discharge Monitoring Report data submitted by all major industrial and federal facilities is entered into 
PCS.</li>
<li>To utilize the Division's data management system for tracking the large number of applicants covered under the NPDES 
general permits for storm water.</li>
</ol>
<hr>
