<hr>

<h3 align="center"><a name="Mission">The Mission of the Water
Protection Branch</a></h3>

<p>The Water protection Branch is committed to protect and
enhance the waters of the State through effective monitoring, allocation,
regulations, and management of water resources, in accordance
with State and Federal legislative mandates.</p>

<p>The Water Protection Branch uses the following <a
name="Principles"><strong>Guiding Principles</strong></a> to
carry out its mission:<br>
</p>

<ul>
    <li>Strives to meet or exceed the statutory goals,
        requirements, and deadlines of the State and Federal
        legislative mandates; </li>
    <li>Utilizes strategic planning and a priority setting
        approach to direct Branch efforts and to facilitate
        efficient, effective, and innovative uses of resources; </li>
    <li>Strives to provide a work environment that challenges
        associates to be participating members of a coordinated
        team effort; </li>
    <li>Be open, flexible, and amenable to change; </li>
    <li>Actively solicit input and participation from interested
        and informed parties; and; </li>
    <li>Foster a cooperative working relationship with US EPA and
        other agencies. </li>
</ul>

<p>The overall <a name="goals"><strong>Goals</strong></a> of the
Water Protection Branch are:<br>
</p>

<ul>
    <li><u>Monitoring</u> - to monitor facilities, discharges,
        and waters of the State to assess compliance with
        applicable laws, rules and permits. </li>
    <li><u>Compliance Assurance</u> - to assess and assure
        compliance with Georgia Water quality laws, rules, and
        permits. </li>
    <li><u>Modeling</u> - to develop water quality models to
        support management decisions. </li>
    <li><u>Watershed Managemen</u>t - to employ a watershed
        management approach to address issues of water quality. </li>
    <li><u>Permitting</u> - to process and issue in a timely
        manner NPDES, LAS, Industrial Pretreatment, and Erosion
        &amp; Sediment Control Permits, Sludge Management Plans,
        and 401 Water Quality Certifications which are
        technically correct, enforceable, and of high quality. </li>
    <li><u>Rules and Regulations</u> - to ensure the Georgia
        Rules and Regulations for Water Quality Control clearly
        and accurately define how State and Federal water quality
        laws will be implemented. </li>
    <li><u>Nonpoint Source</u> - to address nonpoint sources of
        pollution for urban, agricultural, and commercial
        forestry sources. </li>
    <li><u>Funding</u> - to provide funding for publicly owned
        water and wastewater systems. </li>
    <li><u>Engineering</u> - To ensure that wastewater collection
        and treatment systems in Georgia are planned, designed,
        and constructed in accordance with acceptable engineering
        practices and permit requirements. </li>
    <li><u>Planning</u> - To utilize strategic and operational
        planning to achieve long and short-term objectives. </li>
    <li><u>Public involvement</u> - To promote public involvement
        in the activities of the Water Protection Branch. </li>
    <li><u>Data Management</u> - To manage data in an efficient
        and effective manner. </li>
</ul>

<hr>

<h3 align="center"><a name="background">Background</a></h3>

<p>The State of Georgia established an integrated water pollution
control program in 1964 with the passage of the Georgia Water
Quality Control Act. The 1964 Act created a Water Quality Control
Board and a Division for Water Quality Control with the authority
to investigate water pollution problems and take action to insure
documented problems were cleaned up. The Division for Water
Quality Control became the cornerstone of the Georgia
Environmental Protection Division (EPD) which was created in
1972.</p>

<p>The Water Protection Branch of the EPD has maintained the
integrated approach to water quality and manages specific aspects
of water pollution control including; stream, lake and estuarine
monitoring; water quality modeling; river basin management
planning; establishing water quality standards; nonpoint source
management; administration of the federal construction grants and
State revolving loan process for funding municipal water
pollution control plant construction; the permitting, compliance
and enforcement program for municipal and industrial.</p>

<p>We are fortunate in Georgia to have a good supply of clean
water. Programs implemented by local governments, industry, farmers,
foresters, and individuals have helped to control water
pollution. Improvements in wastewater treatment by local governments
and industry have made a significant contribution to improving
water quality in our rivers and streams over the past twenty
years. <pr> However, many significant water quality challenges
remain, including the difficulty of controlling stormwater runoff
from urban and agricultural lands. Another issue of concern is
soil erosion and subsequent sedimentation which occurs whenever
we disturb the earth and fail to properly implement effective
erosion/sediment control measures.</p>

<p>We must also face the challenge of conducting long-term
planning to protect our water resources and to project future
water supply needs in order to promote plans and conservation
practices to provide clean water for all future uses. </p>

<p>The Water Protection Branch uses an annual program plan or
Fiscal Year Clean Water Implementation Plan which is designed to
detail goals and objectives for the fiscal year. The fiscal year
Clean Water Implementation Plan is drafted in June, provided to
the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency and the public for
review, and implemented at the beginning of the federal fiscal
year on October 1. </p>

<hr>

<h3 align="center"><a name="LAuthority">Legal Authority</a></h3>

<p>The Georgia Water Quality Control Act, as amended, and the
rules and regulations promulgated thereunder provide adequate authority
to establish and maintain a comprehensive State water protection
program.</p>

<p>During the past twenty years it has been adequately
demonstrated that the Georgia Water Quality Control Act and the adopted
rules and regulations provide strong and effective legal
authority for the State program.</p>

<p>The Georgia Water Quality Control Act, as amended, provides
legal authority comparable to Section 504 of the federal Clean
Water Act as amended. Contingency plans are available to
implement the &quot;emergency authority&quot; of the State Act on
a case by case basis as needed. This meets the requirements of
Section 106 of the federal Clean Water Act as amended.</p>

<hr>

<h3 align="center"><a name="RBMP">Georgia River Basin Management
Planning</a></h3>

<p>Georgia has adopted a river basin management planning (RBMP)
approach to watershed protection as defined in State law (O.C.G.A.
12-5-520) passed by the Georgia General Assembly in 1992. The law
designated the Chattahoochee, Flint, Coosa, and Oconee Rivers as
the first basins to be addressed. The law requires each plan
include a description of the basin or watershed, identification
of local governments in each basin, land use inventories, and a
description of plan goals which may include providing
environmental education, improving water quality, reducing
pollution at the source, improving aquatic habitat,
reestablishing native species of fish, restoring and protecting
wildlife habitat, and providing recreational benefits. A description
of the strategies and measures necessary to accomplish the goals
is also to be a part of each management plan. The law also
requires a seven person local advisory committee be appointed to
provide advice and council to GAEPD during the plan development.</p>

<p>A watershed protection approach will provide a tool for the
assessment and prioritization of water resource issues, development
of solutions, and opportunities for targeted, cooperative actions
to reduce pollution and enhance aquatic habitat. The watershed
approach will provide opportunities for participation by many
stakeholders, and the solutions implemented will draw on the
combined experiences and resources of many stakeholders.</p>

<p><strong>Summary</strong></p>

<p>RBMP represents a new approach to water resources management
for the State of Georgia that focuses on the watershed, rather
than state-wide program specific approaches. It is not a new
regulatory program, but rather a new way of applying existing
regulatory programs. Water supply and surface/groundwater quality
issues will be addressed in an integrated manner. Stakeholder
involvement will be emphasized throughout the planning and
implementation process.</p>

<p>Partnerships will be developed to share plan development and
implementation opportunities. Similar watershed protection approaches
are becoming a national initiative of varying scales ranging from
small individual watersheds to large interstate watersheds.</p>

<hr>

<h3 align="center"><a name="organization">Organization</a></h3>

<p>The Water Protection Branch of the Environmental Protection
Division is responsible for developing and maintaining a comprehensive
water quality control program for the State of Georgia. This
includes implementation of the Division water quality policies,
requirements of the Georgia Water Quality Control Act, as
amended, and the federal Clean Water Act, as amended, and
achievement of the established water quality control goals.</p>

<p>The Water Protection Branch consists of the <a href="wqmp.htm">Water
Quality Management Program</a>, <a href="wmep.htm">Municipal
Engineering Program</a>, <a href="wmpp.htm">Municipal Permitting
Program</a>, <a href="wiwp.htm">Industrial Wastewater Program</a>,
and support from the Laboratory Operations Program and Regional
Offices. The titles of the respective programs are indicative of
their primary functions. </p>

<hr>

<p align="center">[<a href="#top">Go to Top of this Page</a>] [<a
href="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/epd/index.htm">Go to Home Page
of EPD</a>] </p>

