<html>

<head>
<title>General Q&amp;A for Scrap Tire Management</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<h2 align=center>General Q &amp; A <br>
for Scrap Tire Management<br>
</h2>
<h4><u>$1.00 Per Tire Fees Issues</u></h4>
<p><strong>Question</strong>: What is the purpose of the tire fee? </p>
<p><strong>Answer</strong>: The fee will be used by the Environmental Protection Division to create grants and<br>
reimbursements to cities and counties, authorities, state agencies or the Market Development<br>
Council for:<br>
(1) The clean up of tire dumps<br>
(2) The development and implementation of solid waste enforcement programs for the<br>
abatement of illegal dumping of scrap tires<br>
(3) Implementation of innovative technologies for the recycling and reuse of scrap tires<br>
(4) Educational and other efforts to promote waste reduction, recycling, and recycling market<br>
development. </p>
<hr align=left width=50%>
<p><strong>Question</strong>: Is the $1.00 fee to be imposed on tires sold to local governments? </p>
<p><strong>Answer</strong>: Yes. City, county, state and federal governments are not exempt from the fee. <br>
</p>
<hr align=left width=50%>
<p><strong>Question</strong>: Will the tire dealer (wholesaler or retailer) who sells large quantities of tires to large<br>
companies for the companies' own use be required to impose the $1.00 per tire sold fee? </p>
<p><strong>Answer</strong>: Yes, if the dealer is located in Georgia. No, if the company purchases the tires and are 
pickup outside of Georgia <br>
</p>
<hr align=left width=50%>
<p><strong>Question</strong>: Retail dealer A sells several tires to Retailer B; which dealer is responsible to impose the 
$1.00 fee? <br>
<br>
<strong>Answer</strong>: Retailer B is responsible to collect the fee (the dealer who sells the tires to the ultimate<br>
consumer must collect the fee). </p>
<hr align=left width=50%>
<p><strong>Question</strong>: Is a used tire dealer required to impose the $1.00 fee on the resale of used tires? </p>
<p><strong>Answer</strong>: No. The $1.00 fee is to be imposed only on the sale of new replacement tires.<br>
<br>
</p>
<hr align=left width=50%>
<p><strong>Question</strong>: Will a retail dealer be allowed to add an additional charge to his invoices for disposal of 
the scrap tires? </p>
<p><strong>Answer</strong>: Yes. The $1.00 requirement is not a disposal fee. It is considered a tire management fee.<br>
<br>
</p>
<hr align=left width=50%>
<p><strong>Question</strong>: What tires are excluded from the $1.00 fee? </p>
<p><strong>Answer</strong>: <br>
(a) Farm equipment other than trucks<br>
(b) Tires with a rim size of less than 12&quot;<br>
(c) Any device moved exclusively by human power <br>
</p>
<hr align=left width=50%>
<p><strong>Question</strong>: Will the $1.00 fee be imposed on an aircraft tire dealer, located in another state, who 
sells tires to an individual or to an airline located in Georgia?<br>
<br>
<strong>Answer</strong>: Yes. If the tires are delivered in Georgia, the fee must be imposed.<br>
</p>
<hr align=left width=50%>
<p><strong>Question</strong>: Is the distributor/wholesaler responsible to collect the $1.00 fee? </p>
<p><strong>Answer</strong>: The distributor/wholesaler is responsible to collect the fee only from those retail dealers 
who do not have a valid Generator I.D. number </p>
<hr align=left width=50%>
<p><strong>Question</strong>: A tire manufacturer located in Ohio sells tires to the maintenance shop of a utility 
company through a local distributor. Who, if anyone, remits the $1.00 fee?<br>
<br>
<strong>Answer</strong>: The $1.00 fee must be imposed by the dealer or distributor who is located in Georgia<br>
<br>
</p>
<hr align=left width=50%>
<p><strong>Question</strong>: Can distributors and retail dealers deduct a &quot;handling&quot; fee for collecting and reporting 
the $1.00 fees? </p>
<p><strong>Answer</strong>: Yes. Both distributors and retail dealers may deduct 3% of the first $3000 of the total 
amount of all fees collected and reported, and an additional .5% of that portion exceeding $3000 in 
fees collected and reported only if the fees and reports are not delinquent. </p>
<hr align=left width=50%>
<p><strong>Question: </strong>Will the $1.00 fee be imposed on tires sold to manufacturers of automobiles, boat 
trailers, sway cars, mobile homes, and similar manufacturers? </p>
<p><strong>Answer</strong>: No. The fee is to be imposed only on new replacement tires. </p>
<hr align=left width=50%>
<p><strong>Question</strong>: Is the $1.00 fee to be imposed only on passenger tires? </p>
<p><strong>Answer</strong>: No; the fee is to be imposed on a variety of new replacement tires including tires for cars, 
trucks, motorbikes, aircraft, heavy equipment, ATV's, boat trailers and others. </p>
<hr align=left>
<h4><u>Carriers/Permits Issues</u></h4>
<p><strong>Question</strong>: Will a retail dealer, hauling its own scrap tires, be required to have a Carrier Permit? </p>
<p><strong>Answer</strong>: No. </p>
<hr align=left width=50%>
<p><strong>Question</strong>: How is the Manifest used if a Carrier picks up 100 tires, salvages 20 tires for reuse, 
then transports the remaining 80 tires to processors or landfills, etc.? </p>
<p><strong>Answer</strong>: <br>
(a) Carrier becomes a processor during the sorting operation, and must be approved by EPD. 
(b)Carrier must initiate a second set of Manifests for the 80 scrap tires. The twenty (20) tires<br>
for reuse will not be manifested. <br>
</p>
<hr align=left width=50%>
<p><strong>Question</strong>: Will Carrier Permits be permanent or renewable? </p>
<p><strong>Answer</strong>: Permits will be permanent as long as financial assurance (Bond or Letter of Credit) is 
valid. </p>
<hr align=left width=50%>
<p><strong>Question</strong>: Is there a fee for obtaining a Carrier Permit?<br>
<br>
<strong>Answer</strong>: No; however, a $5000.00 or $10,000.00 Bond or Letter of Credit is required and the 
insurance companies and banks usually charge an initial fee plus annual renewable fees. </p>
<hr align=left width=50%>
<p><strong>Question</strong>: Will scrap tire carriers based in other states be required to have Carrier Permits? </p>
<p><strong>Answer</strong>: Yes; whether they transport scrap tires into or out of Georgia<br>
</p>
<hr align=left>
<p><u>Generators/ID#'s Issues</u><br>
<br>
<strong>Question</strong>: Will city, county, and state vehicle maintenance shops be required to have ID Numbers 
and Carrier Permits? </p>
<p><strong>Answer</strong>: All governmental agencies must have a Generator ID Number if they generate scrap tires. <br>
They will not be required to have Carrier Permits in order to transport scrap tires. </p>
<hr align=left width=50%>
<p><strong>Question</strong> : What is required of companies who have their own vehicle maintenance shops and 
generate scrap tires? </p>
<p><strong>Answer</strong>: <br>
(a) Company must have ID Number as a Generator and manifest the tires to an approved state<br>
processing or disposal facility.<br>
(b) Company will not be required to have a Carrier Permit to transport its own company-generated 
scrap tires.<br>
</p>
<hr align=left width=50%>
<p><strong>Question</strong>: Will a large retail dealer chain be required to have an ID Number for each of its stores? </p>
<p><strong>Answer</strong>: Yes. ID Numbers are site specific, therefore, each store location must have its own ID#. </p>
<hr align=left>
<h4><u>Manifests Issues</u></h4>
<p><strong>Question</strong>: Will retail dealers be required to submit copies of scrap tire shipment manifests to the<br>
Environmental Protection Division? </p>
<p><strong>Answer</strong>: No. Copies of completed manifests should be maintained for three years by dealers, 
carriers, and processors, users or disposers. EPD inspectors may from time to time review these<br>
manifest files as part of the tracking system. </p>
<hr align=left width=50%>
<p><strong>Question</strong>: Is a scrap tire Generator required to manifest used tires and retreadable casings? </p>
<p><strong>Answer</strong>: Used tires and casings do not have to be manifested if they are pre-sorted prior to 
transport. If the tires are not pre-sorted, all must be manifested.<br>
</p>
<hr align=left>
<h4><u>General Issues</u></h4>
<p><strong>Question</strong>: Which tire handlers have to keep records? </p>
<p><strong>Answer</strong>: Retail dealers, generators, carriers, end users, processors and disposers must keep 
accurate records. </p>
<hr align=left width=50%>
<p><strong>Question</strong>: Who is required to report to the Environmental Protection Division (EPD)? </p>
<p><strong>Answer</strong>: <br>
(a) Carriers must report annually the number and disposition of scrap tires.<br>
(b) Retail dealers must remit $1.00 for each new tire sold on a quarterly basis.<br>
(c) Processors must report quarterly the number of scrap tires processed.</p>
<hr align=left width=50%>
<p><strong>Question</strong>: How do used tire dealers fit into the Scrap Tire law? </p>
<p><strong>Answer</strong><br>
(a) When mixed tires (scrap, used and recyclable casings) are picked up from the original 
generator, the used tire dealer must sign the Manifest as both the Carrier and the state-approved 
Tire Processor.<br>
<br>
(b) Used tire dealers who pick up tires, sort them, then transport scrap tires must have:<br>
1. ID# as a Generator/Processor of scrap tires<br>
2. Carrier Permit as a transporter of the scrap tires<br>
3. Initiate a second Manifest for the scrap tires that are sorted from recyclable casings and<br>
reusable tires (which are not considered scrap tires) </p>
<hr align=left width=50%>
<p><strong>Question</strong>: Is a tire Retreader required to have ID#'s or Permits? </p>
<p><strong>Answer</strong>: <br>
(a) If only retreadable casings are transported to the retreader, Permits will not be required.<br>
(b) If a Retreader picks up scrap tires, salvages the casings, then transports <br>
rejects to a landfill or processor, he will be required to have a Scrap Tire Carrier Permit, be an<br>
approved state processor, and must initiate another manifest as a Generator. </p>
<hr align=left width=50%>
<p><strong>Question</strong>: Will EPD provide lists of approved scrap tire carriers, processors, and disposers? </p>
<p><strong>Answer</strong>: Yes; EPD will periodically provide updated lists of all three handlers. </p>
<hr align=left width=50%>
<p><strong>Question</strong>: Will grants and loans for implementing innovative technologies for recycling be available 
to individuals or companies? </p>
<p><strong>Answer</strong>: No. </p>
<hr align=left width=50%>
<p><strong>Question</strong>: How many tires can be stored at various facilities? </p>
<p><strong>Answer</strong>: Different storage limits have been placed on scrap tire handling facilities as follows: <br>
1. Solid Waste Disposal sites - number to be approved by EPD<br>
2. Retail Tire Dealer - 3000 scrap tires<br>
3. Tire Retreader - 1500 scrap tires<br>
4. Auto Salvage Yard - 500 scrap tires<br>
5. Scrap Tire Sorter - 3000 mixed tires prior to sorting and 3000 scrap tires stored prior to<br>
transport<br>
6. Scrap Tire Processor - number to be approved by EPD </p>
<p>Revised 03/94<br>
</p>
</body>

</html>
</DOC>
