<h1>Georgia Coastal Management Program</h1>

<p> </p>

<h2>Ecological Services Section</h2>

<p> <em>Program Managager: Kathryn Zagzebski</em> Email: <a
href="mailto:kaz@dnrcrd.dnr.state.ga.us">
kaz@dnrcrd.dnr.state.ga.us </a></p>

<p> Phone: (912)264-7218</p>

<p> <img src="art/suntan.gif"></p>

<p> &127;</p>

<h3>Mission Statement:</h3>

<p> It is the mission of the Georgia Coastal Management Program
to balance economic development in Georgia's coastal areas with
preservation of natural, environmental, historic, archaeological,
and recreational resources for the benefit of Georgia's present
and future generations.</p>

<p> </p>

<h3>Georgia's Coast:</h3>

<p> Georgia has a beautiful coastal area with extensive marshes
and attractive beaches. Economic growth has been healthy and
Georgia's coast is a popular place to live, work, and visit. This
popularity, however, affects coastal resources and the overall
quality of life on the coast. Some of the activities in the
coastal area are not compatible. Conflicts and resource
limitations are already affecting coastal communities. Coastal
issues need to be addressed through a comprehensive management
program that considers all aspects of the coastal uses and
issues. Issues that are important to Georgia's coast include:
water supply limitations, identification of historic sites,
impacts to endangered species, beach erosion and hazard problems,
water quality degradation, declining fishery populations,
increased population growth, dredging and spoil disposal, lack of
beach access, and need for energy planning. As Georgia grows in
population, these issues will become more pressing.</p>

<p> </p>

<h3>History:</h3>

<p> In September 1992, Governor Zell Miller directed the Georgia
Department of Natural Resources Coastal Resources Division
(DNR-CRD) to develop a coastal management plan utilizing funding
available from the National Oceanic and Atmospheric
Administration, Office of Ocean and Coastal Resource Management
(NOAA-OCRM). Before the plan was written, the DNR-CRD conducted a
thorough review of Georgia's existing laws and regulations and
concluded that Georgia could receive federal approval for a
coastal management plan based on existing authorities. Moreover,
DNR-CRD committed to developing a plan that would not result in
additional government bureaucracy. </p>

<p> </p>

<h3>Public Participation:</h3>

<p> To assist DNR-CRD in creating a coastal management plan,
Governor Miller appointed a 27-person Coastal Zone Advisory
Committee comprised of citizens from the coastal counties of
Georgia. Through the Coastal Zone Advisory Committee, nine public
task forces were organized to make policy recommendations to
DNR-CRD. Altogether, over 200 citizens were directly involved in
the development of the plan. An additional 1,428+ citizens
reviewed the plan and provided comment at public meetings,
hearings, and presentations. Public involvement has been and
continues to be crucial in the process of developing a coastal
management plan.</p>

<p> </p>

<h3>The Plan:</h3>

<p> The Georgia Coastal Management Program establishes a network
among agencies handling coastal issues, presents a comprehensive
framework for managing coastal resources, and promotes open
communication among the various parties with coastal interests.
Based on recommendations submitted to DNR-CRD by the citizen task
forces and the Coastal Zone Advisory Committee, the plan document
describes the significant assets of Georgia's coast, identifies
the problems and issues Georgia faces as its coastal region
continues to develop and grow, and provides the management
framework for resolving those issues. </p>

<p> </p>

<h3>Federal Approval:</h3>

<p> The federal Coastal Zone Management Act of 1972 created a
voluntary program for states to develop and administer coastal
management programs. This Act set broad guidelines for state
programs and the criteria for approval. Individual states were
given the responsibility of identifying priority issues for their
respective coasts and implementing their program using state laws
and regulations. General concerns such as resources that affect
national defense and interstate transport must be addressed to
ensure that the management plan does not unduly hamper these
activities. The federal Coastal Zone Management Program provides
participating states with significant benefits, including federal
consistency, funding, and technical assistance.</p>

<p> </p>

<h3>Current Activity:</h3>

<p> The issue of whether or not to pursue a federally-approved
coastal management program is currently up before a state
legislative study committee. The committee will meet Monday,
September 16, and Tuesday, September 17, to learn about the
proposed program, the benefits of federal approval for Georgia,
and the steps that would be necessary to enact a
federally-approvable coastal management program. This meeting is
open to the public. For more information, contact the Georgia
Coastal Management Program.</p>

<p> <img src="art/lemming_windsurfer.gif"></p>

