<h1>Operations Management Program</h1>

<p> </p>

<h2>Ecological Services Section</h2>
<em>

<p>Program Manager: Phillip Flournoy</em> </p>

<p> Email: <a href="mailto:phillip@dnrcrd.dnr.state.ga.us">
phillip@dnrcrd.dnr.state.ga.us </a></p>

<p> Phone: (912)264-7218</p>

<p> <img src="/CRD/art/lockness.gif"></p>

<p> The primary responsibility of the Operations Management
Program of the Ecological Services Section is the formulation of
Section operational objectives, the identificaiton and
procurement of objective funding sources, and the accomplishment
of those objectives through effective and efficient processes. In
periods of fiscal austerity, the function of the Operations
Management Program is particularly significant, since needed
improvement level projects must often be funded through sources
other than the State. Chief among the functions of the Operations
Management program is the identification and procurement of
alternative program funding sources. During the 1996 fiscal year,
the Operations Management Program procured five federally funded
projects totalling approximately $800,000. These federally funded
projects alllow the Coastal Resources Division to conduct
research, devise resources management plans, and acquire critical
habitat that would not be possible with state funding.
Applications are now in progress for six additional projects
totalling more than $1,000,000. </p>

<p> The Operations Management Program provides coordination,
supervision, and field assistance to federally funded and branch
projects not associated with other Programs. Current activities
include the implementation of a statewide Wetlands Training
Project for DNR law enforcement personnel, educators, and
officials of local government and development of a Joint General
Permit between the Georgia DNR and the U.S. Army Corps of
Engineers. Projects scheduled to commence in Fiscal Year 1996
include implementation of a partnership effort with The Nature
Conservancy to conduct an Altamaha River Watershed Demonstration
Project leading to increased protection of that ecosystem;
implementaiton of a Coastal Sediment Monitoring Project in
cooperation with the Skidaway Institute of Oceanography; and
continuation of the statewide Wetlands Training Initiative. </p>

<p> The Operations Management Program ensures continuous quality
emprovement in the Ecological Services Section by providing
on-going support to all section projects and activities. The
Operations Management Program provides on-going inservice
training and facilitates Section initiatives such as Strategic
Planning Efforts. The program provides budgetary planning,
oversight and control. The Program coordinates activities between
the Ecological Services Section and other Division programs such
as procurement and accounting. The Program also administers
Section accounting, purchasing, and inventory control processes.
In addition, the Program provides recruitment and other personnel
related services to the Section. </p>

<p> <img src="/CRD/art/surfer.gif"></p>

