<h1>Altamaha River Watershed Project</h1>

<p> </p>

<h2>Ecological Services Section</h2>

<p> <em>Janet Zimmerman, Marine Biologist</em></p>

<p> Email: <a href="mailto:janet@dnrcrd.dnr.state.ga.us">
janet@dnrcrd.dnr.state.ga.us </a></p>

<p> Phone: (912)264-7218 or (912)437-3066</p>

<p> <img src="art/blue_bar.gif"></p>

<p> The Altamah system drains 19,400 km2 (7,760 mi2) of piedmont
terrain and 28,800 km2 (11,520 mi2) of coastal plain, making it
the largest drainage area east of the Mississippi River basin.
Undammed below the fall line, the Altamaha is unique among
watersheds in the eastern United States. The lower Altamaha
watershed, along the Altamaha River proper, boasta the highest
number of rare plants, animals, and natural community occurences
in Georgia. The lower Altamaha watershed also contains the
largest contiguos riparian corridor in the state, with floodplain
over 17 km wide in some areas. Nevertheless, somae areas are
logged to the riverbank, and multiple wetlands and other natural
communities are at risk. The relatively small number of
landowners in the lower Altamaha watershed, some of whom own
large tracts of land, offers great opportunity for protection of
wetlands via direct landowner negotiation.</p>

<p> The Watershed Protection Approach Demonstration Project
focuses on the lower Altamaha River watershed ecosystem and
expands efforts of the Georgia Department of natural Resources,
Coastal Resources Division, in cooperation with The Nature
Conservancy of Georgia, in protecting and preserving tidal and
nontidal wetland ecosystems throughout the state. The project
inventories and analyzes wetlnad and water quality data of the
Altamaha River via digitization and analysis of landcover, land
ownership, ecological significance, point source pollution, and
water quality layers on a Geographic Information System (GIS).
The project also classifies and ranks priority wetlands, provides
information which can be used by local decsionmakers, and is
working to design a wetlands protection protection strategy for
the watershed from the confluence to the ocean. In addition,
individualized maps and packets for landowners identifying
reources, expalianing the valua of those resources, and
describing protection options are being developed through the
project. The closing stage of the project will outline
contributions and applicability of the demostration project
methodology to other watersheds in Georgia and in the nation.</p>

<p> In this effort to manage Georgia's natural resources in a
sustainable manner, the following project objectives have been
identified:</p>

<p> 1) Develop a GIS database encompassing the Altamaha River
Watershed, including already collected data, landownership,
current management, landcover, and pollution sources for analysis
and use in coordinated planning, protection, and restoration
efforts. </p>

<p> 2) Conduct a landcover classification to be used for
watershed analysis, utilizing satellite imagery, field surveys,
and of the methodology developed by TNC in its national pilot
project. </p>

<p> 3) Analyze threats to the wetland resources, including
sources of stresses. </p>

<p> 4) Determine wetland protection priorities, through
correlation of areas of highest conservation interest and
concern, areas facing the greatest threats, and opportunities
based on landownership, land use, and regulatory jurisdiction. </p>

<p> 5) Develop a comprehensive system-wide protection plan for
the Altamaha River Watershed. This plan will:</p>

<p> a) identify and rank priority wetlands;</p>

<p> b) outline goals to protect priority wetlands;</p>

<p> c) survey existing conservation programs and regulations for
effectiveness;</p>

<p> d) develop wetland protection and management strategies;</p>

<p> e) identify potential restoration sites; </p>

<p> f) develop site conservation plans (tract-based) for high
priority wetlands, including a framework for acquisition,
conservation easements, management, and addressing cumulative
impacts and incremental loss;</p>

<p> g) summarize data analysis and report recommendations for use
by local governments, state and federal agencies, and regional
development centers.</p>

<p> </p>

<p> 6) Produce maps and reports to facilitate meetings with
landowners and managers of high priority protection sites; </p>

<p> 7) Conduct meetings with private landowners of priority
wetlands, to discuss the uniqueness and importance of resources
under their ownership and appropriate management options, and to
identify and implement conservation strategies of their choice.</p>

<p> <img src="art/blue_bar.gif"></p>

