<body>

<h1>Marina Pumpout Project</h1>

<p> </p>

<h2>Ecological Service Section</h2>
<em>

<p>Brad Williams: Technical Assistant</em></p>

<p> e-mail: <a href="mailto:brad@dnrcrd.dnr.state.ga.us">brad@dnrcrd.dnr.state.ga.us</a></p>

<p> Phone: (912)264-7218</p>

<p> <img src="art/suntan.gif"> </p>

<h3>Grant Program Development</h3>

<p> The purpose of this component shall be to plan and establish
a state grant program which will create criteria and processes
for awarding funds for the installation and renovation of pumpout
and/or dump stations in the six Georgia coastal counties. Current
data, including the 1995 Coastal Marina Survey will be analyzed
to determine areas in which the greatest needs exist. Target
areas will be identified according to boating density, number and
availability of pumpout or dump facilities, and habitat
considerations such as proximity to shellfish harvesting sites,
primary nursery areas, and water quality. </p>

<p> Based upon the analysis of survey data, marina facilities in
targeted, critical locations will be identified. Criteria for
awarding funds will be established. These elemental criteria will
include boating density, adequacy of facility, and availability
of other proximal pumpout or dump stations. Other priority
considerations may include installation of pumpout or dump
stations at fuel docks and other service areas which attract both
transient and local boaters, marinas and service facilities
catering to large numbers of transient boaters, marinas with wet
slips which cater to boats greater than 26 feet (pumpouts) or
less than 26 feet (dump stations), and marinas open to the
general public. A standardized funding application form will be
developed and completed for each facility requesting funding. </p>

<p> </p>

<h3>Pumpout/Dump Station Construction</h3>

<p> The purpose of this component shall be to implement the state
grant program from which funds will be awarded for the
installation and renovation of pumpout and/or dump stations in
the six Georgia coastal counties. Upon receipt of applications,
the Division will review proposed projects and grant awards based
upon prioritization of needs utilizing established criteria.
Prior to the close of the contract, pumpout or dump stations
installed or renovated will be inspected for proper installation
and operation. Based upon preliminary information generated by
the 1995 Coastal Marina Survey, three major construction projects
and five minor construction projects in coastal Georgia will be
completed during this funding period. </p>

<p> </p>

<h3>Public Information and Education</h3>

<p> The purpose of this component is to develop and implement a
coast-wide public education and information program designed to
build awareness of the problems associated with boat sewage and
encourage the use of pumpout and dump station facilities. The
component will also advertise the grant program and provide
information on the application process and selection criteria.
Working with private and public sector organizations, a directed
public education and information process will be developed. The
coast-wide outreach strategy will include development,
publication, and distribution of informational brochures and
materials aimed at the boating public and marine related
industry; development of a mobile display for use at boat shows
and other functions; development, publication, and distribution
of a boat sewage fact sheet; and inclusion of articles in the
public media and Departmental and Divisional newsletters and
other publications.</p>

<p> <img src="art/lemming_windsurfer.gif"></p>

<p> <a href="index.htm"> Back to the CRD Homepage</a></p>

<p> </p>
</body>
