<body>

<h1> Offshore Bottom Mapping Project</h1>

<h2> Outer Continental Shelf Program</h2>

<h3> Henry Ansley, Program Leader</h3>

<p><img src="art/blue_marble.gif"></p>

<p> </p>

<h2>Offshore Bottom Survey</h2>

<p>Reef fish constitute one of the South Atlantic's most
important recreational and commercial offshore fisheries. A
primary factor affecting the distribution and extent of this
fishery is the occurrence of natural reefs, known off Georgia as
&quot;hardbottoms&quot; or &quot;live bottoms&quot;. North of
Florida, live bottoms reefs are scattered and are largely less
than 3' in relief, possibly subject to periodic inundation by
sand; off Georgia, the occurrence of live bottom on the adjacent
continental shelf is estimated at only 3-5% of the total area and
typically is found well offshore, beyond safe range of most
smaller boats. Without resources to effectively search for
additional nearshore opportunities, Georgia's offshore anglers
and divers heavily utilize the state's artificial reefs and known
live bottom areas and wrecks closer to shore. As a result,
fishing pressure has become concentrated and associated reef
fisheries have radically declined.</p>

<p> Management of the important South Atlantic reef fisheries in
large part relies on protection of the live bottoms throughout
the region. Without locational information, fisheries managers
lack the basic data needed to monitor reef fisheries and respond
to potential impacts associated with new gear types and offshore
mineral exploration.</p>

<p> In order to distribute fishing pressure, live bottoms,
wrecks, and other structures offering potential fishing
opportunities need to be defined and made available. Location of
these areas will better enable fisheries managers to monitor the
region's offshore reef fisheries and its habitat, as well as
enable improved response to overfishing and other potential
impacts.</p>

<p> <img src="art/blue_bar.gif"></p>

<p> <a href="index.htm">Back to the CRD Homepage</a></p>

<p> </p>
</body>
