<body>

<h1> Access Enhancement </h1>

<h2> Recreational Fisheries Program</h2>

<h3> John Pafford, Program Leader</h3>

<p><img src="art/blue_marble.gif"></p>

<p> Increased marine-based recreational activity is associated
with Georgia's expanding coastal population. Consequently, one of
the primary goals of DNR's strategic planning initiatives is to
improve coastal fishing by improving existing boating and
non-boating access as well as construction of additional access.
Construction of fixed and floating docks at existing boat ramps
sites is needed coastwide to serve non-boating anglers, as well
as the boating public. Ramps with floating docks greatly enhance
the boat launching activities by improving safety and reducing
the risk of boat, trailer, and vehicle damage. Many of Georgia's
coastal boat ramps need repairs to enable adequate access at low
tide. In addition, new ramps are needed due to growing coastal
populations and increasing tourism.</p>

<p> Georgia's 100-mile coast includes more than 2,400 miles of
tidal creeks and rivers; 8,000 square miles of continental shelf;
374,000 acres of tidal marsh; and 184,000 acres of tidal waters.
Residents and tourist alike seek shore-based access to these
saltwater resources for fishing, crabbing, and castnetting.
Because of limited time most coastal residents and visitors have
to fish, they depend on easy access. In addition, lower income
families are largely dependent on non-boating angling access.</p>

<p> Despite this demand and the magnitude of the resources,
shore-based access is limited since most creeks and rivers are
typically separated from high ground by large expanses of
saltmarsh. Further, most suitable high ground adjacent to
saltwater creeks and rivers is privately owned (and highly
valued). For these reasons, public piers are critically needed
coastwide to allow citizens reasonable access to common property
resources.</p>

<p> The benefits of improved angler access and marine
recreational fishing in general are well documented. In the past
10 years, the number of participants in Georgia's marine
recreational fishery has significantly increased with
approximately a half million anglers participating during 1994.
Boat registrations in Georgia have increased 33% since 1981. In
the six coastal counties there is one boat registered for every
15 people as compared to one in 24 statewide. The total economic
impact of saltwater recreational fishing is estimated at more
than $250 million annually. Adequate boating and non-boating
access results in quality fishing trips which translates into
economic benefits to the local coastal communities and the state
overall.</p>

<p> <img src="art/green.gif"><a href="ramp.htm"> Boat Ramp
Construction</a></p>

<p> <img src="art/green.gif"><a href="pier.htm"> Fishing Pier
Construction</a></p>

<p> <img src="art/blue_bar.gif"></p>

<p> <a href="index.htm">Back to the CRD Homepage</a></p>

<p> </p>
</body>
