<h1> Inshore Sportfish Monitoring </h1>

<h2> Recreational Fisheries Program</h2>

<h3> John Pafford, Program Leader</h3>

<p><img src="art/blue_marble.gif"></p>

<p> Georgia enjoys a good reputation among saltwater anglers.
Regional estimates indicate that Georgia's anglers, on the
average, land more spotted seatrout than those in South Carolina,
North Carolina, and Northeast Florida combined. This is due, in
part, to effective management of the State's marine fishery
resources. Georgia's coastal population has increased 12% in the
past decade with angling effort reaching unprecedented levels.
Only through progressive fishery management based on
comprehensive and accurate information will quality saltwater
fishing opportunities be perpetuated.</p>

<p> Including stock assessement and life history studies,
research and fishery-independent surveys provide information on
exploitation rates, annual survival, movement, growth, age
composition, reproductive biology, stock structure, and general
health of fish populations. Presently, this information is only
being collected for spotted seatrout and red drum in two of
Georgia's ten estuarine systems per year. </p>

<p> <img src="art/green.gif"><a href="life.htm"> Sportfish Life
History Research </a></p>

<p> <img src="art/green.gif"><a href="marfin.htm"> MARFIN Red
Drum Tagging Project</a></p>

<p> <img src="art/blue_bar.gif"></p>

<p> <a href="index.htm">Back to the CRD Homepage</a></p>

<p> </p>
</body>
