<body>

<h1> Angler Education</h1>

<h2> Recreational Fisheries Program</h2>

<h3> Spud Woodward, Project Leader</h3>

<p><img src="art/blue_marble.gif"></p>

<p> </p>

<h2>Angler Education</h2>

<p>Coastal Georgia is blessed with abundant and diverse estuarine
and marine fishery resources. Georgia's 100-mile coastline
includes more than 2,400 miles of tidal creeks and rivers; 8,000
square miles of continental shelf; 374,000 acres of tidal marsh;
and 184,000 acres of tidal waters. This environment serves as
habitat to a myriad of marine and estuarine finfish, crustaceans,
shellfish, marine mammals, and sea turtles that are of
recreational, commercial, and nonconsumptive importance to
Georgians and visitors to the state's six coastal counties.</p>

<p> Rapid population and urbanization of Georgia's coastal area
has led to the deterioration of estuarine/marine habitats and
stressed those natural resources dependent on them. Increased
fishing pressure has also stressed numerous marine and estuarine
living resources. The public must be educated about the value and
need for protecting essential fishery habitats from developmental
encroachments and the damaging effects of pollution. Education
about conservation of sportfish resources is another important
element in a public marine education program. A conservation
ethic needs to be instilled in the citizenry, young and old, to
maintain the quality of our marine and estuarine resources for
present and future generations.</p>

<p> Major objectives of a Marine Education Program for the next
five years are: l) promoting and enhancing the public's
understanding of and appreciation for marine resources and
environments; 2) implementing long-term educational strategies
targeting youth and adults and pertaining to marine sportfish
conservation, restoration, and utilization; 3) cultivating a
stewardship ethic for common property resources among marine
resource users; and 4) generating more responsible marine
fishermen through training in the understanding of marine
resource management techniques.</p>

<p> </p>

<h2>Sportfish Research Video</h2>

<p>A key to conserving the State's marine resources for current
and future generations is the education of Georgia's populace.
Georgia's coastal region and associated living resources and
ecosystems are a treasure yet to be discovered and enjoyed by
much of its citizenry. Implementation of a comprehensive marine
education program targeting youth and adults would educate
Georgians about the state's valuable, unique living coastal,
marine, and estuarine resources and habitats, as well as the need
to conserve these valuable resources and the management
techniques required to accomplish this.</p>

<p> Coastal Resources Division plans to develop a video on
Georgia sportfish research and management to promote better
understanding of how fisheries information is gathered, life
histories of selected sportfish species, and regulatory
approaches to management of sportfish species. This will help
generate a populace (youth and adults) with a greater
appreciation of the marine environment, fishery resources,
conservation principles and ethics, and the knowledge necessary
to advocate management of their resource for the present and the
future. </p>

<p> <img src="art/blue_bar.gif"></p>

<p> <a href="index.htm">Back to the CRD Homepage</a></p>

<p> </p>
</body>
