<body>

<h1>Fishing Pier Construction </h1>

<h2> Recreational Fisheries Program</h2>

<h3> John Pafford, Program Leader</h3>

<p><img src="art/blue_marble.gif"></p>

<p> Shoreside access to fishable marine and estuarine waters is
extremely limited in coastal Georgia. Despite vast acreage of
saltwaters, most creeks and rivers are separated from high ground
by large expanses of saltmarsh. There is a paucity of public deep
water access available to the non-boating public. High ground
areas suitable for construction of public fishing piers is
extremely limited in coastal Georgia. What little high ground
property is available is typically too costly to develop for
public saltwater access. The number of sites suitable for
development of non-boating fishing access is expected to decrease
while costs and public demand for providing this needed access
are expected to increase. It is imperative that DNR address
increasing non-boating access needs to meet the demand of a
growing population as well as coastal tourism. The need is
particularly acute in the northern portion of Georgia's coast.
Currently, using federal Sportfish Restoration funds and
state/local government support, DNR is constructing public
fishing piers in Chatham County.</p>

<p> </p>

<pre>
              Recommended Sites for Fishing Pier Construction
                          (not in priority order)

        Site                                             County

Thunderbolt/Wilmington R.  			        Chatham
Kilkenny Creek/Richmond Hill WMA  			 Bryan
Halfmoon Bluff/Timmons R.          			Liberty
Scrubby Bluff/St. Marys R.         			Camden
Overlook Park						Glynn	
</pre>

<p><img src="art/blue_bar.gif"></p>

