<body>

<h1>FEDERAL AID IN SPORT FISH RESTORATION</h1>

<p> Did you know that each time you buy fishing equipment or fuel
for your boat, you are also helping to enhance sport fish
restoration? Many anglers do not realize that sporting goods
manufacturers pay a tax on items they produce. This tax is used
to purchase sites for boating access and improve boating and
fishing dock facilities. It is also used for research,
enhancement, and artificial reefs.</p>

<p> This User Pays, User Benefits funding approach began in 1937
with the Federal Aid in Wildlife Restoration Act. This Act
established excise taxes on outdoor sports equipment, with
proceeds going toward wildlife enhancement. In 1950, Congress
enacted the Sport Fish Restoration Act, sponsored by U.S. Rep.
John Dingell, Sr., of Michigan and Sen. Edwin Johnson, of
Colorado. The law, which became known as the
&quot;Dingell-Johnson Act&quot;, applies a 10 percent
manufacturer's excise tax on fishing rods, reels, creels, lures,
and flies. Tax revenues are transferred to the U.S. Fish and
Wildlife Service, which in turn distributes them to the states
for recreational sportfishing enhancement projects.</p>

<p> Each state's share is based 60 percent on its number of paid
licensed sport fishermen and 40 percent on its land and water
area. No state may receive more than 5 percent or less than 1
percent of each year's total collection.</p>

<p> In 1984, Sen. Malcolm Wallop of Wyoming and Rep. John Breaux
of Louisiana sponsored the Wallop-Breaux Amendment to the Sport
Fish Restoration Act, extending the tax to tackle boxes, sonar
fish finders, motorboat fuels, electric motors, and other
equipment not included in the earlier laws.</p>

<p> The Wallop-Breaux Amendment requires at least 12.5 percent of
all restoration money be spent on boating access to public waters
and requires Georgia and other coastal states to fund marine
recreational fisheries projects proportionate to the ratio of
freshwater to saltwater anglers. In addition, the amendment
requires that states continue to fund fisheries at their historic
levels and not substitute federal funds for those previously
supplied by the states.</p>

<p> In Georgia, Federal Aid in Sport Fish Restoration funds have
attributed to the construction of 14 offshore and 11 inshore
artificial reefs, 6 non-boating fishing docks, 4 boat ramps, and
2 floating dock facilities. Also, funds were used to conduct
numerous research and survey projects including life history
studies on important marine sport fish, sport fish monitoring,
exploitation and stock structure, recreational sport fish
landings, hooking mortality, and others. Basically, these
projects were financed by the boater and/or angler and were
designed for their benefit by providing better access and better
fisheries management.</p>

<p> <img src="art/blue_bar.gif"></p>

<p> <a href="index.htm">Back to the CRD Homepage</a></p>

<p> </p>
</body>
