<body>

<h1>Environmental Monitoring</h1>

<p> </p>

<h2>Ecological Services Section</h2>

<p> </p>

<h3>Dr. Stuart Stevens, Section Chief</h3>

<p>Email: <a href="mailto:stuart@dnrcrd.dnr.state.ga.us">
stuart@dnrcrd.dnr.state.ga.us </a></p>

<p> Phone: (912)264-7218</p>

<p> <img src="art/lemming_swimmer.gif"></p>

<p> <strong>Shellfish Sanitation</strong></p>

<p> As mandated by state law (O.C.G.A. 27-4-197) the Department
of Natural Resources cooperates with the Department of
Agriculture to administer and operate a Shellfish Sanitation
Program sufficient to be certified by the US Food and Drug
Administration. The Department of Agriculture has the
responsibility for certification of handling facilities for
interstate shipments of shellfish in Georgia, which is included
in Part II of the National Shellfish Sanitation Program (NSSP)
Manual of Operations. The DNR has responsibility for
classification and patrol of shellfish growing areas which
incorporates Part I of the NSSP Manual of Operations. The
Environmental Health Program (EHP) composes Sanitary Surveys for
the four growing areas in Georgia. </p>

<p> The EHP's efforts in shellfish sanitation represent the
foundation for the assurance of public health protection of
consumers of molluscan shellfish produced and harvested
commercially or recreational in Georgia. During each month the
EHP monitors shellfish growing waters and performs water quality
analyses using the Program's certified water quality laboratory.
The EHP also conducts extensive shoreline reconnaissance to
identify and evaluate all actual or potential pollution sources
that may affect the sanitary quality of a shellfish growing area.
Annually, water quality monitoring results and shoreline
reconnaissance data are incorporated into revisions and
comprehensive updates of these sanitary survey reports. The EHP
is evaluated each year by the US Food and Drug Administration to
measure compliance with NSSP requirements and is recognized as
having one of the strongest sanitation programs in the country. </p>

<p> The EHP also coordinates annual FDA evaluations of the patrol
element of DNR's Shellfish Sanitation Program by cooperating with
the Wildlife Resources Division, Law Enforcement Section. The
Georgia Shellfish Patrol Policy document, which is also a
requirement of the NSSP, is composed by the EHP and updated
annually or more frequently as required. The EHP manager is also
actively involved in the Interstate Shellfish Sanitation
Conference (ISSC) and Gulf and South Atlantic States Shellfish
Conference (GSASSC) each year. The ISSC is the annual forum for
development of national and international shellfish sanitation
policies for incorporation into the NSSP. The GSASSC is a
regional conference important for representation of regional
shellfish sanitation and shellfish resource management interests. </p>

<p> In addition to providing public health protection, the DNR's
shellfish sanitation program has historically played a
significant role in regulating the ever increasing demand for
coastal development in Georgia. &quot;Approved&quot; and
&quot;Restricted&quot; shellfish growing areas represent an
existing use under Section 404(b) of the Clean Water Act which
provides the DNR an avenue for input in the federal permitting
process to limit the environmental impacts associated with
various activities on the coast.</p>

<p> </p>

<hr>
<strong>

<p>Resource Management</strong></p>

<p> The EHP also has a limited resource management function
through permitting of commercial harvest of shellfish production
in Georgia. The EHP issues Master Collecting Permits and
individual harvest permits to commercial industry members in the
state. The Environmental Health Program also administers leases
for exclusive rights to commercial harvest of shellfish resources
on state owned estuarine properties. There are currently three
state commercial shellfish leases which generate $2,275 in annual
fees which are returned to the program. Information regarding
entry into Georgia's shellfish industry is routinely distributed
to interested individual. The EH also manages approximately
20,000 acres of Public Recreational Shellfish Harvest Areas in
the six coastal counties. The EHP maintains approximately 100
signs identifying these areas and distributes charts marking the
locations to the general public upon request. As an added measure
of public health protection, the EHP also posts approximately 400
signs which identify locations unsafe for shellfish harvesting. </p>

<p> <img src="art/surfer.gif"></p>

