<h1>Habitat Management Program</h1>

<p> </p>

<h2>Ecological Services Section</h2>

<p> <em>Program Manager: Terry West</em></p>

<p> E-mail <a href="mailto:terry@dnrcrd.dnr.state.ga.us">terry@dnrcrd.dnr.state.ga.us</a></p>

<p> <img src="art/island.gif"></p>

<p> The Habitat Management Program was established in July, 1994
as part of a reorganization of the Ecological Services Section.
The Program's function is to administer the mandated regulatory
responsibilities of the Coastal Resources Division: Coastal
Marshlands Protection Act (CMPA), Shore Protection Act (SPA), and
Revocable License Program. Staffing consists of a Program
Manager, two Permit Coordinators, and a clerical position to
administer the legally mandated authorities for the entire
coastal area: 100 miles of ocean-front beaches, 2344 linear miles
of coastline, and about 700,000 acres of marshlands and
waterbottoms. </p>

<p> Under the authority of these laws, the Habitat Management
Program conducts inspections to determine jurisdiction lines,
collect information, advise applicants and investigate
violations. Based on the recommendations of the staff, the
Coastal Marshlands Protection and Shore Protection Committees
issue or deny permits. </p>

<p> The Ecological Services Section is particularly concerned
with permitting projects that serve public interests on the
barrier islands. Examples of projects that require permits are
marinas, boat ramps, boardwalks and beach access crossovers which
protect the sensitive sand dune systems. </p>

<p> Accomplishment of these directives requires staff
coordination with federal, state, and local agencies;
consultation and negotiations with project applicants;
investigation of unauthorized and illegal activities;
determination of jurisdictional areas; and compliance inspections
of permitted projects. </p>

<p> The regulatory functions of the Ecological Services Section
have proven highly successful for a quarter of a century and are
recognized nationwide for this success. The General Assembly, in
legislating the CMPA and SPA, recognized the significant and
varied benefits of maintaining these fragile coastal habitats.
Sustainable populations of many species of marine life and
wildlife are dependent upon these habitats. Georgia's coastal
marshlands and beaches also provide recreation, serve as buffers
from natural storms, help control erosion and flooding, and
filter and disseminate pollutants. These habitats are therefore
vitally linked to the economy of not only the coastal area, but
to the entire state. </p>

<p> Due to the complexity of coastal geography and escalating
demands on the available resources due to population growth, the
management of our coastal habitats has become increasingly
complicated and controversial. Private property rights, public
access, water rights, economic growth versus resource protection,
and excessive governmental bureaucracy are but some of the
regulatory process issues at the forefront of the political arena
today. The regulatory functions of the Ecological Services
Section have for years been recognized for their flexibility to
balance development and conservation of vital estuarine habitat
areas. A primary goal of the Habitat Management Program is to
provide fair and equitable administration of the regulatory
functions while continually seeking to improve the efficiency of
service to the citizens of Georgia. </p>

<p> The Program has initiated changes in the past two years which
have aided attainment of this goal. In August 1994, the Program
assumed the revocable license program and marina waterbottom
leasing responsibilities from the DNR Real Estate Unit in
Atlanta. The Habitat Management Program's administration of the
revocable license authorities has received praise from the Corps
of Engineers, local governments, and citizens for reducing time
and providing efficient service to applicants. Several
administrative procedure changes were incorporated into the
revocable license process which reduced staff time and paperwork,
including the consolidation of five previous application forms
into one. The staff also meshed the revocable license process
with the CMPA and SPA processes, thus eliminating paperwork in a
step in the permitting process for applicants. With regard to the
marina waterbottoms leasing responsibilities, the provisions of
which are of the Coastal Marshlands Protection Act, the staff
performed an initial analysis of the required procedures. This
analysis revealed a prime example of governmental bureaucracy -
duplicative efforts by different agencies, unnecessary paperwork,
unnecessary time delays in processing, and unnecessary costs to
applicants. The staff proposed legislative changes which were
approved by the 1995 General Assembly, signed by the Governor,
and took effect July 1, 1995. These changes not only simplify the
entire process and reduce processing time, but also provide the
lease fee proceeds to be retained by the Program instead of going
onto the general fund. </p>

<p> <img src="art/island.gif"></p>

