<h1>Section 401 Assumption Project</h1>

<p> </p>

<h2>Ecological Services Section</h2>
<em>

<p>Victor Pyle, III: Technical Assistant</em></p>

<p> e-mail: <a href="mailto:vic@dnrcrd.dnr.state.ga.us">
vic@dnrcrd.dnr.state.ga.us </a></p>

<p> Phone: (912)264-7218</p>

<p> <img src="art/surfer.gif"></p>

<p> </p>

<h3>EPA-funded State Wetlands Protection Grant Program, 7/1/96 -
6/30/99</h3>

<p> This grant seeks funding for a three-year program to continue
and expand the efforts of the Georgia Department of Natural
Resources, Coastal Resources Division to develop strategies for
the protection and preservation of existing tidal and non-tidal
wetland ecosystems within the six coastal counties. This effort
can serve as a model for enhanced wetland protection in the
inland portions of the State of Georgia as well as other states.
The proposed program is comprised of two primary developmental
components:</p>

<p> 1) Process development, transfer and assumption of the
Section 401 Water Quality Certification Program from the Georgia
Department of Natural Resources Environmental Protection Division
to Coastal Resources Division in the six Georgia coastal
counties; and</p>

<p> 2) Process development, transfer and assumption of the
Regional General Permit for private, single-family, recreational
docks from the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers to the Coastal
Resources Division within the GCMP area, incorporating current
Revocable License authrity. </p>

<p> The proposed project is consistent with the objectives of the
U.S. Environmental Protection Agency. The project will provide
the following wetlands protection and benefits:</p>

<p> 1. The project will improve and enhance State statutory
authority, regulations, and policies in regards to wetlands. The
Section 404 program will benefit from DNR/DRC assumption of 401
and dock GP and investigation of other NWP/GP/RP/ assumption
opportunities. Development of a GIS compatible electronic permit
tracking database system for compliance assessment, monitoring,
and enforcement will also improve the process. </p>

<p> 2. The project will improve State and Federal agency
coordination by integrating review processes between agencies and
eliminating duplicative programs to achieve more comprehensive
habitat protection. The proposal will involve coordination with a
variety of State (Environmental Protection Division, Coastal
Resources Division, etc.) and Federal (Corps of Engineers, EPA,
USFWS, NMFS, etc.) agencies to improve protection of wetland
resources. Compliance, monitoring, and enforcement will be more
efficient and coordinated as a result. The development process
will encourage the formal formulation and adoption of protocols,
rules, and guidelines for 401 certifications and conditions. </p>

<p> 3. The proposal will encourage consistency with the 404(b)(1)
guidelines. </p>

<p> 4. The proposal will enhance permit tracking, which will be
valuable in encouraging more vigorous compliance, monitoring, and
enforcement efforts, especially to newly-trained DNR conservation
rangers who will identify and report wetland violations. </p>

<p> 5. The proposal will identify and combine various programs,
resources, and recommendations into a strategy that could be
extended throughout the entire State of Georgia. </p>

<p> The proposed project accomplished the above stated benefits
through a collaborative effort between the Georgia Department of
Natural Resources, Coastal Resources Division; the Georgia
Department of Natural Resources, Environmental Protection
Division; and the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers, Savannah District
in an effort to improve and streamline protection of wetlands in
the State of Georgia. </p>

<p> <img src="art/island.gif"></p>

<p> <a href="index.htm">Back to the CRD Homepage</a></p>

<p> </p>
