<h1>Wetlands Education Project</h1>

<p> </p>

<h2>Ecological Services Section</h2>
<em>

<p>Kelie Cochran: Technical Assistant </em></p>

<p> e-mail: <a href="mailto:kelie@dnrcrd.dnr.state.ga.us">
kelie@dnrcrd.dnr.state.ga.us </a></p>

<p> Phone: (912)264-7218</p>

<p> <img src="/CRD/art/lemming_swimmer.gif"></p>

<p> </p>

<h3>EPA State Wetlands Protection Grant Program 7/1/94 - 6/30/96</h3>

<p> Thiis grant project improves state wetlands management
functions through the development of an in-service training
program which meets two designated goals. First, the in-service
training program enhances the capabilities of Georgia Department
of Natural Resources conservation officers to recognize and
report violations of federal and state regulatory laws and
permits designed to prevent the loss and degradation of wetlands
caused by erosion and sedimentaiton and non-point source
pollution. This project also &quot;trains-the- trainer&quot; by
providing Georgia's conservation officers with a wetlands
training program, including lesson plans, audio visuals,and
printed support materials, which they disseminate throughout the
state via presentations to various civic, school, and sportsmens'
groups. </p>

<p> An additional goal of the in-service training program is to
enhance understanding of the ecological value of wetlands and
wetlands protection of local government officials, educators, and
teachers in coastal counties by providing training and printed
support materials. In addition, this project enabled the
digitization and conversion of existing National Wetlands
Inventory maps of the six Georgia coastal counties for use in
Geographic Information Systems (GIS). Utilizing the GIS aids
State and local governments in identifying wetlands; documenting
wetland alteration and conversion; and assist in conservation,
protection, and managment decision making. This project is
carried out through the Coastal Resources Division of the
Department of Natural Resources which is the sponsor of the
project and the primary contractor with EPA. The Coastal
Resources Division has sub-contracted portions of the project to
the Coastal Georgia Regional Development Center and to the United
States Fish and Wildlife Service National Wetlands Inventory.</p>

<p> <img src="/CRD/art/suntan.gif"></p>

<p> <a href="/CRD/index.htm">Back to the CRD Homepage </a> </p>

