<body>

<h1> Outer Continental Shelf Program </h1>

<h2> Marine Fisheries Section</h2>

<h3> Henry Ansley, Program Leader</h3>

<p>Email: <a href="mailto:henry@dnrcrd.dnr.state.ga.us">
henry@dnrcrd.dnr.state.ga.us </a></p>

<p> Phone: (912)264-7218</p>

<p> <img src="art/blue_marble.gif"></p>

<p> The Outer Continental Shelf Program is comprised of five
associates (biologist, two wildlife/marine technicians, and two
research vessel crew). Program associates perform activities in
two primary areas: offshore research and surveys and offshore
recreational fisheries enhancement. Research and surveys
encompass an ongoing offshore bottom survey and life history
studies of offshore reef fishes important to Georgia. Enhancement
efforts entail artificial reef construction and maintenance. The
offshore bottom survey documents offshore bottom habitat
supporting recreational fishing opportunities and disseminates
this information through periodic publication of an updated, free
Georgia Offshore Fishing Guide. Survey results are imperative for
regional management decisions focused at protecting essential
reef fish habitat. The OCS Program's study of gag grouper is
providing critical information to state and federal fishery
managers on gag reproductive behavior/movement in order to avert
overfishing, possible stock collapse, or unnecessarily
restrictive regulatory measures impacting Georgia anglers. Among
the most popular of gamefish with Georgia anglers, gag grouper is
one of several reef fish species for which CRD has management
authority through O.C.G.A. 27-4-130.1 and Board of Natural
Resources Rules 391-2-4.</p>

<p> Offshore artificial reef development and maintenance
constitute the foundation of the OCS Program's recreational
fishing enhancement activities. Thirteen artificial reefs located
5 - 23 nm offshore have been constructed to provide safely
accessible offshore angling opportunities for Georgia anglers, as
well as to provide fisheries habitat necessary to enhance
valuable offshore fisheries. The OCS Program maintains thirteen
buoys to mark the offshore artificial reefs. These typically
large systems permitted through the U. S. Coast Guard not only
assist anglers in locating and utilizing the reefs but also
function as important navigational aids. The fishing
opportunities associated with artificial reefs translate into
direct economic benefits realized by businesses, coastal
communities and government. Direct expenditures by saltwater
fishermen in Georgia are estimated at $53.4 million annually,
with the total impact of Georgia's marine recreational fishing
industry estimated at $250 million annually.</p>

<p> While there is no mandate to construct artificial reefs, once
constructed, the State assumes short and long term responsibility
for each site under COE Regional Permit No. RP0036. There is no
mandate to buoy a reef once the site/obstruction has been
charted; however, while buoyed under USCG permit, there is an
obligation to maintain the aid.</p>

<p> The OCS Program maintains responsibility for the Georgia
Saltwater Gamefish Records Program. This activity recognizes
outstanding saltwater sportfish catches, promotes ethical angling
practices, provides data on saltwater species, and provides
anglers with a popular records program. The OCS Program Leader
represents Georgia on the SEAMAP -South Atlantic Board, which
establishes policy for this cooperative state/federal
fishery-independent data collection program targeting marine
fisheries resources of regional importance. Other miscellaneous
responsibilities of OCS Program associates include Altamaha
houseboat removal, recycling, and public relations cruises (which
will likely increase in FY96 with the new offshore R/V). Program
activities are supported by both State and non-competitive
Federal grant-in-aid funding sources.</p>

<p> <img src="art/green.gif"><a href="offreef.htm"> Artificial
Reef Development and Maintenance</a></p>

<p> <img src="art/green.gif"><a href="bott.htm"> Offshore Bottom
Mapping</a></p>

<p> <img src="art/green.gif"><a href="snap.htm"> Offshore Finfish
Monitoring</a></p>

<p> <img src="art/green.gif"><a href="swr.htm"> Saltwater
Gamefish Records</a></p>

