<body>

<h1> Recreational Fisheries Program </h1>

<h2> Marine Fisheries Section </h2>

<h3> John Pafford, Program Leader</h3>

<p>Email: <a href="mailto:pafford@dnrcrd.dnr.state.ga.us">
pafford@dnrcrd.dnr.state.ga.us </a></p>

<p> Phone: (912)264-7218</p>

<p> <img src="art/blue_marble.gif"></p>

<p> The Marine Recreational Fisheries Program is comprised of
nine associates (four biologists and five hourly wage
technicians) who conduct research and surveys, and monitor stock
status of recreationally important saltwater sportfish.
Additionally, this unit is actively enhancing inshore marine
recreational fishing through boating and non-boating access
development and improvement, and inshore artificial reef
construction.</p>

<p> Four studies constitute the fishery independent research and
monitoring of Georgia's inshore sportfisheries: spotted seatrout
assessment, assessment of red drum exploitation and stock
structure, biotelemetry of young adult red drum, and assessment
of sub-adult red drum in the South Atlantic Bight. Because of
their status as Georgia's most popular inshore sportfish,
estuarine populations of spotted seatrout and red drum are
intensively monitored to determine exploitation and survival
rates as well as stock structure. Additional research emphasis is
attempting to better ascertain these parameters for immature red
drum, so as to improve the accuracy of stock assessments which
are the foundation for state, interstate and federal management
of this species. An ultrasonic tracking study which is
determining the spatial and temporal distribution of young adult
red drum in the spawning stock will conclude this fall. This
extensive fishery independent research provides scientific
information for state, interstate, and federal management of
these important sciaenids mandated pursuant to O.C.G.A.
27-4-130.1, Board of Natural Resources Rules 391-2-4, P.L.
94-265, and P.L. 103-206.</p>

<p> With increased saltwater angling consequent with Georgia's
expanding coastal populations, proactive management and quality
fishing experiences are essential for the resources and our
constituency (i.e. customers). Inshore marine recreational
fisheries enhancement activities entail access development for
boating and non-boating anglers, and improved fishing
opportunities through development of inshore artificial reefs.
The Recreational Fisheries Program is improving coastal fishing
for boating and non-boating anglers by constructing fixed and
floating docks at existing boat ramp sites coastwide.
Deteriorating ramps are targeted for repairs. Program associates
are contracting a cost effective conversion of an existing
shoreside structure into a public pier. Boating access
enhancement is mandated under the Federal Aid in Sportfish
Restoration Program (mandadatory 12.5% expenditure of State's
federal SFR funding). Boating access activities coupled with the
other non-mandatory development activities are extremely
beneficial economically ($250 million annually) to the local
coastal communities and the state overall.</p>

<p> Recreational Fisheries Program associates are engaged in a
number of exclusively State supported marine education
activities, including expansion of CRH Nature Trail resources,
hosting the annual parent-child fishing derby, and field
demonstrations and presentations to numerous school groups, civic
and conservation associations. Associates assist in the
collection of finfish samples for LCP-related contaminants
analyses (LCP is a superfund site located in the coastal zone of
Brunswick). A Program biologist performs law enforcement duties
in a pilot effort to expand coastal enforcement capabilities.
Recreational Fisheries Program associates actively liaison with
sportfishing clubs, and conservation organizations, academia, law
enforcement, and other state and federal agencies in their
research and management endeavors. Program biologists represent
the agency on six state/federal ASMFC and SAFMC work groups,
technical committees, and task forces, three of which are
associated with interstate and federal fishery management
programs, and as such, are federally supported. This involvement
is in fulfillment of agency obligations through the ACFCMA and
the Council Liaison Grant. Recreational Fisheries Program
activities are supported by both state and Federal funding
sources; Federal funds are both competitive and non-competitive
grant sources.</p>

<p> <img src="art/green.gif"><a href="inreef.htm">Artificial Reef
Development and Maintenance</a></p>

