<head>
<title>Commercial Fisheries Program Homepage </title>
</head>

<body>

<h1> Commercial Fisheries Program </h1>

<h2> Marine Fisheries Section </h2>

<h3> Jim Music, Program Leader</h3>

<p>Email: <a href="mailto:music@dnrcrd.dnr.state.ga.us">
music@dnrcrd.dnr.state.ga.us </a></p>

<p> Phone: (912)264-7218</p>

<p> <img src="art/blue_marble.gif"></p>

<p> The Commercial Fisheries Program is comprised of 12
associates (three biologists, senior lab technician, three
research vessel crew, five hourly wage technicians) who are
actively engaged in research, monitoring and surveys associated
with management of Georgia's $25 million (dockside) crustacean
fisheries. Crustacean management involves ongoing monitoring of
shrimp and blue crab stocks utilizing a variety of gear aboard
CRD's Research Vessel ANNA and smaller craft to provide data for
season and area management decisions mandated pursuant to
O.C.G.A. Title 27. Shrimp trawl bycatch is currently being
analyzed during CRD's fishery independent crustacean assessment
study as well as during commercial food shrimping operations in
nearshore waters. Bycatch data are integral to enhanced finfish
stock assessments and necessary for evaluating and documenting
compliance with bycatch reduction essential to effective
interstate marine fishery resource conservation and mandatory
pursuant to the Atlantic Coastal Fisheries Cooperative Management
Act of 1993.</p>

<p> Program professionals collaborate with Wildlife Resources
Division and National Marine Fisheries Service associates to
effect management strategies to minimize the interaction of
commercial trawl and gill net fisheries with endangered and
threatened species. The Commercial Fisheries Program is also
responsible for periodic collection of seafood samples from the
Purvis Creek/Turtle River closure area for contaminants analyses.</p>

<p> In conducting its activities, the Commercial Fisheries
Program manages for optimum yield, stock conservation, and
maintaining or restoring essential habitat quality. Achievement
of these goals is based on a foundation of management-oriented
research, monitoring and modeling, real-time decision making,
policy formulation, and development of legislative and regulatory
initiatives and recommendations to authorities responsible for
habitat quality and function. Program associates actively liaison
with citizens advisory groups, academia, conservation
organizations, law enforcement, and other state and federal
agencies in their research and management endeavors. Commercial
Fisheries Program biologists represent the agency on nine
interagency, state/federal, ASMFC, and SAFMC works groups,
technical committees, and task forces.</p>

<p> Commercial Fisheries Program associates also conduct numerous
public relations activities (e.g. 10 - 20 demonstration trawls)
for VIP's, agency and elected officials, conservation and service
organizations, and school groups throughout the year. Commercial
Fisheries Program activities are supported by both Federal and
State funding sources; Federal funds are both competitive and
non-competitive grant sources. </p>

<p> <img src="art/green.gif"><a href="crab.htm"> Shrimp and Crab
Stock Assessment</a></p>

<p> <img src="art/green.gif"><a href="bycatch.htm"> Shrimp Trawl
Bycatch Characterization</a></p>

<p> <img src="art/green.gif"><a href="crust.htm"> 1995 Annual
Crustacean Report</a></p>

<p> <img src="art/blue_bar.gif"></p>

