<body>

<h2>GEORGIA'S SPOTTED SEATROUT</h2>

<p>Contact: Nick Nicholson <a
href="mailto:nick@dnrcrd.dnr.state.ga.us">
nick@dnrcrd.dnr.state.ga.us</a></p>

<p> Phone:(912)264-7218</p>

<p> <img src="art/blue_marble.gif"></p>

<p> Spotted seatrout, a member of the Sciaenidae or drum family,
is the most targeted inshore sportfish species in Georgia. Known
as the drum family for their ability to make drumming sounds with
their air bladder, this group also includes red drum, black drum,
spot, weakfish and croaker. Spotted seatrout is identified as
having sharp canines, silvery body, with numerous distinct dark
spots on the upper side of its body, including the dorsal and
caudal fins. It occurs from Massachusetts to the Yucatan
peninsula.</p>

<p> Spotted seatrout reach sexual maturity at two years of age
with young fish spawning approximately 100,000 eggs while older
fish may spawn as many as 1,000,000. Spotted seatrout have a
protracted spring and summer spawning period which peaks in
Georgia during May. Spawning occurs primarily in the sounds along
the beaches. The eggs are buoyant and when hatched, the larval
fish are transported into the estuarine nursery areas by wind and
tidal currents.</p>

<p> Spotted seatrout are a schooling species and are
opportunistic carnivores whose feeding habits vary with size.
Juvenile trout feed initially on zooplankton, then primarily on
small crustaceans. Medium sized trout feed on shrimp and small
fish. Large fish (16+ inches) feed almost exclusively on other
fish (mullet, menhaden, etc.).</p>

<p> Tagging studies have shown that spotted seatrout are almost
estuarine specific and very few individuals exhibit movement
outside their natal estuary. Spotted seatrout prefer fringe areas
adjacent to banks, points, jetties and sand bars. In the spring
and summer, they can be located in their spawning areas near or
along beaches. As fall sets in and temperature drops, they move
into the lower sound where there is an abundance of prey. As
winter sets in they move further up the estuary into the upper
rivers and creeks, again, where there is a sufficient food
supply. With the onset of harsh weather, trout often move into
the deeper holes and channels where there is some protection from
the rapid temperature changes occurring in their usual fringe
habitat.</p>

<p> While large spotted seatrout are tolerant of extremes in
temperature and salinity, juvenile fish are susceptible to sudden
changes. Severe cold snaps and hurricanes can have a disastrous
effect, reducing the number of fish available to anglers the
following year(s). Regulations concerning the take of spotted
seatrout consist of a minimum size limit of 12 inches, and a
creel limit of 25 fish per person per day. This allows the
species to spawn at least once before harvest, thereby reducing
recovery time from severe climatic events. With a rapidly growing
coastal population, there is some concern over the stability of
our seatrout populations. It has been suggested to increase the
minimum size limit to 14 inches. This would allow the species to
spawn two or three times before reaching harvestable size,
ensuring a more stable population and rapid recovery from severe
climatic events. It would impact anglers the first year
implemented as there would be a one-year lag time for the year
class to reach harvestable size.</p>

<p> Recreational harvest of spotted seatrout in Georgia averages
over 475,000 fish per year. For the future of sportfish, we hope
all anglers will voluntarily comply with sportfishing
regulations. Conservation today will mean fishing opportunities
tomorrow.</p>

<p> <img src="art/blue_bar.gif"></p>

<p> <a href="index.htm">Back to the CRD Homepage</a></p>

<p> </p>
</body>
</html>
</DOC>
