<body>

<h1>Georgia's Red Drum</h1>

<p>Contact: Spud Woodward </p>

<p> Phone:(912)264-7218</p>

<p> <img src="art/blue_marble.gif"></p>

<p> Red drum (Sciaenops ocellatus), locally referred to as
channel or spottail bass, ranges from Laguna Madre, Mexico in the
Gulf of Mexico to Massachusetts in the Atlantic Ocean. Red drum
is one of 22 members of the family Sciaenidae found along the
Atlantic and Gulf coast of the United States. This group is
commonly known as the drum or croaker family since many of its
members, including red drum, produce drumming sounds by vibrating
their swim (air) bladders with special muscles. Adult red drum
are elongate, silvery red fish with a distinguishing black spot
at the base of the caudal (tail) fin above the lateral line.
However, young red drum may occasionally have numerous spots on
their sides.</p>

<p> Red drum are eurythermal, occurring over a temperature range
of 36-92oF, although they usually move into deeper water during
extremes. Small red drum less than 6-8 inches in length are more
susceptible to the effects of winter cold waves than larger
juveniles and adults. High red drum mortality during freezes
occurs with the ability to decimate large portions of juvenile
year classes.</p>

<p> Primarily found in estuarine and ocean waters, red drum are
somewhat catadromous meaning they may be found in freshwater but
must return to saltwater to spawn. After maturation, adult red
drum spend less time in the estuaries and more time in the ocean.
Red drum typically reach maturity at age four when approximately
32 inches in length and may live more than forty years.</p>

<p> Spawning normally occurs from July through October and takes
place primarily at major river inlets such as the Altamaha River.
Red drum are dioecious (i.e., distinct males and females) and
fertilization occurs externally. Red drummay spawn several times
throughout the spawning season. Spawning ocurs at night in
estuarine waters exhibiting optimum incubation salinities of
25-35 ppt below which the eggs would sink and above which the
eggs would clump together (Note: Salinity of freshwater is zero
and offshore ocean salinity is typically 35-36 parts per thousand
salt). In addition, optimum spawning occurs at temperatures of
72-86oF. Red drum eggs and larvae are carried through tidal and
current movement into estuarine systems. Increased spawning
activity is associated with new and full moon periods during the
spawning season.</p>

<p> Red drum larvae and young juveniles move into the mid and
upper portions of the estuary and generally remain in these areas
until Spring when approximately 8-10 months of age (6-10 inches
in length). In Spring, the young juveniles disperse throughout
the estuarine system and may be found occasionally in near
offshore waters. Juveniles and subadults typically remain in
estuarine waters for 3-5 years until reaching maturity (28-32
inches in length). </p>

<p> Red drum is a popular saltwater sportfish throughout the
southeastern United States and has been subject to increasing
pressure from a growing marine recreational fishery in Georgia.
Results from recreational fisheries surveys conducted by the
National Marine Fisheries Service and the Georgia Department of
Natural Resources (DNR) indicate approximately two million red
drum have been caught by Georgia anglers in the past ten years.
During this same period, the number of saltwater fishing trips in
Georgia increased twofold. Research studies conducted by DNR
indicate that since the 1970's, Georgia's red drum population has
experienced a dramatic decrease in the number of young red drum
surviving to maturity. The bulk of the adult population consists
of red drum 15-25 years of age; very few adults less than 12
years of age exist. As these older adult red drum die off,
inadequate numbers of young adults exist to maintain the adult
population, possibly resulting in drastic declines in red drum
reproduction and numbers of young produced. </p>

<p> <img src="art/blue_bar.gif"></p>

<p> <a href="index.htm">Back to the CRD Homepage</a></p>

<p> </p>
</body>
