<body>

<h1> Offshore Artificial Reef Development </h1>

<h2> Outer Continental Shelf Program</h2>

<h3> Henry Ansley, Program Leader</h3>

<p><img src="art/blue_marble.gif"></p>

<p> <img src="art/green.gif"><a href="reefs.htm"> Georgia
Artificial Reef Guide</a></p>

<p> </p>

<hr>

<h2>Artificial Reef Development/Maintenance</h2>

<p> Continuing coastal development and growth has not only placed
more pressure on Georgia's marine fisheries, but also has created
a demand for increased angling opportunities. Direct expenditures
by saltwater fishermen in Georgia have been estimated at $53.4
million annually. With the number of anglers doubling since 1981,
the total impact of Georgia's marine recreational fishing
industry is now estimated at $250 million annually.</p>

<p> Georgia's continental shelf is characterized by mostly barren
sand bottom. Within this 4,000 square miles of ocean floor, only
an estimated 5% offers habitat for offshore gamefish. Creation of
manmade, or artificial, reefs is a proven management technique
that can significantly enhance the size and availability of fish
populations, as well as improve their accessibility to fishermen.
In 1970, the state of Georgia began a program designed to create
closer, safer offshore recreational fishing opportunities and
additional fisheries habitat. In further attempts to make the
offshore artificial more safely accessible to small vessels,
nearshore reef construction on six permitted sites 5-8 nm
offshore and adjacent to marked channels was initiated in 1989.
By 1996, construction had begun on five of the nearshore sites;
combined with the artificial reefs developed further offshore,
the number of offshore artifical reefs currently now totals 13
artificail reefs located 5- 23 miles offshore. Materials utilized
to construct the reefs include surplus vessels, tires, concrete,
and designed fishery enhancement units. Each reef is marked by a
state-maintained buoy.</p>

<p> In addition to providing additional recreational
opportunities and increasing fisheries habitat, properly
constructed artificial reefs also provide significant economic
benefits. Current estimates indicate that the thirteen offshore
artificial reefs constructed by DNR may generate an $5-7 million
annually, a significant return on a total construction investment
of approximately $1.5 million (federal &amp; state) over 26
years. For these reasons, a primary DNR goal is improvement and
expansion of coastal fishing opportunities through the
construction of a series of offshore, nearshore, and inshore
artificial reefs.</p>

<p> <em>Offshore/Nearshore Artificial Reef Development</em></p>

<p> Although only an estimated 15%-20% of the state's marine
recreational fishery in terms of total participants, Georgia's
offshore recreational fishery's economic impact is
disproportionately high. This fishery continues to expand due to
coastal development, the increased affordability of larger
boats/electronics, and the creation of an offshore artificial
reef system. This expansion, however, has also generated demands
for additional and more accessible opportunities similar to those
provided by Georgia's existing offshore and nearshore artificial
reefs.</p>

<p> Georgia's offshore artificial reef development program has
relied almost entirely on the availability of &quot;materials of
opportunity&quot;, such as donated/surplused vessels and scrap
concrete. Annual funding for the program has also been erratic
and insufficient. Both factors hinder the long-term planning
needed to conduct an effective offshore/nearshore artificial reef
development program coastwide.</p>

<p> In order to address the increasing demands of Georgia's
offshore recreational fishery, existing nearshore and offshore
artificial reefs need to be expanded and additional sites need to
be developed. Suitable materials of opportunity need to be
located and, if possible, barge/tug accessible staging sites must
be located for these materials. Construction components may have
to be designed and constructed, incorporating a variety of
materials. While staging/pre-placement preparations may be
conducted throughout the year, actual deployment operations
should occur, if possible, during the summer months to take
advantage of seasonally better weather/sea conditions.</p>

<p> <em>Offshore/Nearshore Artificial Reef Maintenance</em></p>

<p> Despite the availability and sophistication of today's
navigational electronics, Georgia anglers still rely and utilize
buoys placed and maintained by the state at the offshore
artificial reefs. Consisting of comparatively large buoy systems
to offer better visibility and resistance to dragging caused by
vessels illegally tying to the buoys, placement costs are
typically higher. Ongoing and emergency maintenance is required
throughout the year to ensure system integrity. Adequate
materials must be stockpiled to enable rapid replacement of buoys
lost to ship collisions, hurricanes, and other causes. Scoping
meetings conducted in 1996 regarding continued funding for
buoying of the offshore artificial reefs revealed strong support
in continuing buoying.</p>

<p> Permitted through the United States Coast Guard, the
state-maintained buoys help anglers locate and utilize the
offshore artificial reefs, as well as enhance safety by providing
important navigational backups. This is especially true for
smaller, less-equipped vessels, novice fishermen, and visitors.
The markers also provide visual delineation of the reef sites for
large vessels and, since many of the reefs are Special Management
Zones (SMZ), aid in enforcement efforts. Activities such as fish
trapping and trawling are prohibited on artificial reefs
designated as SMZ's</p>

<p> <img src="art/ship.gif"></p>

<p> <a href="index.htm">Back to the CRD Homepage</a></p>

<p> </p>
</body>
