<h1> Offshore Finfish Monitoring Project </h1>

<h2> Outer Continental Shelf Program</h2>

<h3> Henry Ansley, Program Leader</h3>

<p><img src="art/blue_marble.gif"></p>

<p> Georgia's offshore marine recreational fishery encompasses an
array of finfish targeted by anglers, divers, and other user
groups. Of primary importance are the coastal pelagic
(&quot;mackerel&quot;) and snapper/grouper fisheries associated
with the offshore artificial and natural reefs. Less prominent
fisheries occurring offshore of Georgia include billfishes,
tunas, and sharks, as well as species more typically associated
with inshore fisheries, such as bluefish, red/black drum, and
sheepshead.</p>

<p> Offshore recreational landings data for Georgia are limited.
An independent, shelfwide assessment effort for Georgia is not
feasible. Regional charter surveys and habitat assessment efforts
are also limited and are not available for the nearshore/offshore
reefs frequented by fishermen. As a result, fisheries managers
must make decisions largely based on extremely limited or
incomplete data.</p>

<p> More offshore assessment data are needed to strengthen
existing stock assessments and formulate appropriate management
strategies. Ongoing regional assessment and surveys should be
suppplemented by DNR wherever possible. A limited finfish
monitoring program focusing on selected reefs could also provide
useful background on trends in relative abundances of offshore
finfish. </p>

<p> </p>

<h2>Stock Assessement / Life History</h2>

<p> <em>Snapper/Grouper</em></p>

<p> The South Atlantic Snapper/Grouper Fishery management unit is
made up of 73 finfish species, encompassing snappers, groupers,
porgies, sea basses, triggerfishes, jacks, and others. According
to the South Atlantic Fishery Management Council (SAFMC), at
least 13 species are presently overfished, approximately 14
additional species are thought to be overfished, and more species
are expected to experience overfishing in the near future.
Included are several important gamefish popular with Georgia's
offshore anglers, such as gag/scamp groupers, red/vermilion
snappers, red porgy, greater amberjack, gray triggerfish, and
black sea bass. </p>

<p> Despite the existence of highly developed fisheries,
surprisingly little is known about the life histories of the
species making up the snapper/grouper complex. Baseline
information describing movement, spawning/aggregating behavior,
age structure, exploitation, and similar data is lacking. As
stated by the SAFMC (1991): &quot;Adequate management has been
hindered by lack of current and accurate biological, statistical,
social, and economic information. Data necessary to document
growth and/or recruitment overfishing...are very limited.&quot;
With only limited information, fisheries managers have
implemented creel and minimum size limits; harvest of some
species is now illegal. Future management measures now being
considered include, trip limits, limited entry, additional creel
limits and further seasonal/area closures and quotas.</p>

<p> Basic information on the snapper/grouper fishery off Georgia
is critically needed by South Atlantic management agencies. In
light of the scope of the work and the distribution of the
fishery, cooperative regional assessment and research efforts
constitute the most practical and cost-effective approach needed
to address this problem. Where possible, Georgia facilitates and
supplements South Atlantic research efforts, focusing on species
important to the state's offshore anglers, including gag, scamp,
red snapper, greater amberjack, black sea bass, and red porgy. </p>

<p> Working with South Carolina DNR and other regional agencies,
the Outer Continental Shelf Program is currently focusing on gag
movement and spawning aggregations, which are extremely
susceptible to overfishing. This study hopes to help determine
whether gag movement, possibly in response to spawning, is
inshore-offshore, southward/northward, or a combination of the
two.</p>

<p> <img src="art/blue_bar.gif"></p>

<p> <a href="index.htm">Back to the CRD Homepage</a></p>

<p> </p>
</body>
