<body>

<h1> Inshore Artificial Reef Development </h1>

<h2> Recreational Fisheries Program</h2>
<em>

<p>John Pafford, Project Leader</em></p>

<p> Email: <a href="mailto:pafford@dnrcrd.dnr.state.ga.us">
pafford@dnrcrd.dnr.state.ga.us </a></p>

<p> Phone: (912)264-7218</p>

<p> <img src="art/blue_marble.gif"></p>

<p> Inshore, popular gamefish are heavily targeted on well known
&quot;drops&quot;, primarily consisting of naturally occurring
oyster mounds and similarly encrusted structures that offer
habitat; however, these areas are limited throughout Georgia's
estuaries and are distant to many anglers. Further, many areas
offer only expanses of sand or mud bottom that will not support
oyster mound development due to the lack of needed hard
substrate.</p>

<p> Early experimentation in the late 1960's with inshore
artificial reef construction in Georgia was erratic until a more
recent program utilizing fabricated PVC/concrete structures was
initiated in the late 1980's. To date, four subtidal and seven
intertidal inshore reefs have been successfully constructed in
Georgia's estuaries, with the construction of an eighth reef
underway. The boundary of each reef is marked by corner pilings
and signs maintained by the state.</p>

<p> </p>

<h2>Inshore Artificial Reef Development/Maintenance</h2>

<p> As the trend for population expansion in coastal Georgia
continues, a greater number of people are taking advantage of the
waterways and natural resources Georgia has to offer. Boat
registrations in Georgia have increased 33% over the last ten
years. In the six coastal counties there is one registered boat
for every 15 people as compared to one in 24 residents statewide.
Creel and other fishery-dependent surveys indicate that this
increase means even greater fishing pressure on Georgia's inshore
marine recreational fisheries, the largest of the state's coastal
fisheries in terms of participants.</p>

<p> In an effort to disperse the fishing pressure and improve
fish stocks, inshore artificial reefs are needed to create more
habitat. Experimental reefs in St. Simons and Wassaw Sound have
demonstrated that inshore artificial reefs consisting of selected
materials and properly designed/sited are effective in creating
needed habitat. Presently restricted to two estuarine systems,
development of a coastwide system of small inshore artificial
reefs will help address the increasing angling pressure on
Georgia's inshore marine fisheries.</p>

<p> Georgia's inshore reefs are sited in shallow waters often
adjacent to navigational channels. The United States Coast Guard
requires clear designation of the reef sites. To accomplish this,
pilings marked with warning signs are placed at the periphery to
mark the boundaries of the inshore artificial reefs. Placement
and ongoing maintenance of additional systems will be necessary
with increased inshore artificial reef development.</p>

<p> <img src="art/blue_bar.gif"></p>

<p> <a href="index.htm">Back to the CRD Homepage</a></p>

<p> </p>
</body>
