<h1>Georgia Saltwater Finfish Regulations</h1>

<pre>
	               Open      Daily Creel         Possession		Minimum   
Species 	       Season    Limit               Limit           	Size(inches)

Blue Marlin*	   	All year  	1              1             	86 FL
White Marlin*  		All year  	1              1            	62 FL
Sailfish*      		All year  	1              1              	57 FL
Tarpon*        		3/16-11/30 	1              1              	40 FL
Amberjack      		3/16-12/31     	3              3              	28 FL
Cobia          		3/16/11/30   	2              2              	33 FL
Dolphin        		All year  	15             15             	18 FL
King mackerel  		All year  	3              3              	20 FL
Spanish mackerel    	3/16-11/30     10             10             	12 FL
Sheepshead          	All year  	25             25             	8 FL
Atlantic sturgeon  	2/15-4/15 	5              5              	75 FL
Bluefish       		3/16-11/30     15             15             	12 FL
Black sea bass 		All year  	no limit       no limit       	8 TL
Gag grouper         	All year  	5              5              	20 TL
Red drum       		All year  	5              5              	14 TL
                         (none greater than 27 inches TL)
Red snapper         	All year  	2              2              	20 TL
Spotted seatrout    	All year  	25             25             	12 TL
Striped bass        	All year  	2              2              	22 TL
</pre>

<p> NOTE: An asterisk denotes gamefish status or no sale status.
The letter FL denote fork length and TL denotes total length. For
billfishes, length is measured from the tip of the lower jaw to
fork of tail. </p>

<p> </p>

<hr>

<h2>MEASURING SALTWATER FISH</h2>

<p> Length, creel, and seasonal limits are being used to manage
saltwater finfish in coastal Georgia. Many anglers, particularly
novices, find these harvest regulations somewhat confusing. For
instance, in freshwater, anglers measure most fish using a total
length method. However, in saltwater, fish are measured using a
variety of techniques. A spotted seatrout, which has a deeply
forked and rigid tail, is measured using the fork length
technique. A billfish, such as a sailfish, is also measured using
the fork length technique; however, the measurement is taken from
the tip of the lower jaw to the fork of the tail. In many cases
finfish which have rigid forked tails will suffer damage to their
tails during transport from offshore fishing grounds.
Consequently, if all saltwater fish were measured using the
method, the angler might find themselves in a situation where the
fish they caught was legal, but when that same fish was measured
by a wildlife officer at the dock it would not be the same
length. Therefore, fishery managers have formulated length
regulations based on specific characteristics of the different
saltwater fish.</p>

<p> <img src="art/blue_bar.gif"></p>

<p> <a href="index.htm">Back to the CRD Homepage</a></p>

<p> </p>
</body>
