<body>

<h1>GEORGIA CRUSTACEAN REPORT</h1>

<h2>Commercial Fisheries Program</h2>

<p><img src="art/blue_marble.gif"></p>

<p> Georgia's 1995 calendar year was a very good one for the
shrimp fishery with a record harvest of roughly 7 million pounds
of penaeid shrimp worth approximately 26 million dollars. The
spring roe white shrimp season (April through June) produced 1.7
million pounds and was only 75 thousand pounds below the 1991
record year. Summer brown shrimp landings equaled the 887
thousand pound average since 1957. Fall white shrimp landings
also got off to a good start with the first million pound
September since 1979, and the third highest September ever,
including years when Georgia's sounds were open. October
landings, too, were good with 872 thousand pounds, which was also
the highest since 1979. November landings (355,227 lbs) were 40%
below the historic average since 1957, but December landings
(706,160 lbs) were 36% above average. Based on inshore abundance
and size, the 1995 season was extended beyond 31 December to
allow continued harvest. However, the cold weather in early
January moved vast quantities of small shrimp out on the beaches
and prompted the season closure on 10 January 1996. In summary,
the 1995 shrimp harvest produced the all time record for Georgia
shrimpers, but market prices ran about a dollar per pound less
for the catch.</p>

<p> Season highlights included a 30 day area closure of waters
near the Altamaha River mouth during the entire month of August
to prevent the harvest of small shrimp on the beaches. This area
was also closed during the 10 day season extension in January. On
January 24, Georgia's Board of Natural Resources adopted a
Bycatch Reduction Device (BRD) Rule requiring BRD's in shrimp
trawls, effective on the season opening on 1 June 1996. During
the season the National Marine Fisheries Service implemented its
Sea Turtle Emergency Response Plan (ERP) on two different
occasions, requiring the use of top-ejecting hard TED's in shrimp
trawls (the latter restrictions under the ERP did allow use of
bottom shooting hard TED's). Georgia's and the other South
Atlantic states' bycatch reduction plans to insure compliance
with the mandatory 50% bycatch reduction requirement of the ASMFC
Weakfish Management Plan were approved by the Weakfish Management
Board. These plans require the use of BRD's. The Georgia
Legislature passed a quantity limit of 48 quarts (heads-on or 30
quarts heads-off) per person or per boat for castnet caught
shrimp, effective February 7, 1996. This legislation was the
result of strong concerns about the development of a substantial
new inshore commercial fishery as well as the rapid increase in
the number of Florida castnetters, primarily in Camden County,
coming to Georgia as a result of Florida's 5 gallon limit for
castnetters. Finally, per the concerns of commercial food
shrimpers regarding the high turtle strandings and documented
cases of crab traps fouling TED's during the early weeks of the
shrimp season, DNR is working with both industries to try to
resolve this problem, partially through a gear recycling program
for the old traps, and partially through educating the crab
industry of this potential gear conflict.</p>

<p> Georgia's crab industry appears to have been on the rebound
for several years now with reported landings for 1995 increasing
to 9.3 million pounds equaling the long term average since 1956,
and the highest annual harvest since 1984. During the past year
much concern was expressed that there would be a surge of new
crab license sales as a result of Florida's Net Ban Referendum
and the subsequent need for those displaced small boat fishermen
having to diversify to other fisheries, e.g. Georgia's
unrestricted crab fishery. Legislation to establish a &quot;crab
license&quot; and to implement a moratorium on new license sales
until July 1997 was passed in 1995 to prevent additional
exploitation of this fishery and to allow time to develop some
form of limited access to this fishery. The new law requires a
commercial &quot;crab license&quot; to deploy more than six crab
traps, but, in turn, allows the recreational community to use
this commercial gear to harvest no more than a bushel of crabs
per person without being licensed.</p>

<p> In February 1995, the Board of Natural Resources passed a
Rule requiring that all crab traps have a minimum of two escape
rings with a minimum opening of 2 3/8 inches inside diameter to
be installed on the vertical sides of the traps. There has been
much concern regarding the impacts of this ring rule on
peeler/soft crab production, but sales this year actually
increased substantially over the previous year. A special Blue
Crab Issues Subcommittee is meeting at this time to discuss the
crab ring rule, spatial competition between crab/whelk trawlers
and crab trappers in nearshore ocean waters as well as discussing
the aforementioned gear conflicts and the general effect of
abandoned crab traps on TED's. There is also some interest being
expressed about protection of sponge crabs through a harvest
prohibition.</p>

<p> <img src="art/blue_bar.gif"></p>

