<body>

<h1> Boat Ramp Construction</h1>

<h2> Recreational Fisheries Program</h2>

<h3> John Pafford, Program Leader</h3>

<p><img src="art/blue_marble.gif"></p>

<p> </p>

<h2>Floating Dock Construction at Existing Boat Ramps</h2>

<p> One of DNR's primary strategic initiatives is to improve
coastal fishing for boating anglers by constructing
fixed/floating docks at existing boat ramp sites. Considering
Georgia's 6 to 8 foot tidal amplitude, ramps with floating docks
greatly enhance boat launching by improving angler safety and
reducing boat damage. Floating docks also provide much needed
access for Georgia's non-boating public.</p>

<p> Of the 34 public boat ramps in Georgia's tidal waters, very
few are equipped with a fixed/floating dock. DNR has identified
24 of these existing ramps in need of fixed/floating dock
improvements. Public boat ramps proposed for construction of
floating dock facilities for FY-97 through FY-99 include:</p>

<p> </p>

<pre>

          Boat Ramp Sites Needing Fixed/Floating Dock Enhancement
                          (not in priority order)

     Ramp Site                     County

Kings Ferry/Ogeechee River         Chatham
F.W. Spencer Park/Wilmington R.    Chatham
Tybee Island/Tybee Creek           Chatham
Thunderbolt/Wilmington River       Chatham
Salt Creek/Hwy 17                  Chatham
Demeries Creek/Hwy 144             Bryan
Richmond Hill WMA                  Bryan
Liberty Co. Regional Park          Liberty
South Newport River/Hwy 17         Liberty
Sapelo River/HWY 17                McIntosh
Belleville/Sapelo River            McIntosh
Shellman Bluff/White Chimney Creek McIntosh
Upper Turtle River/Hwy 99          Glynn
Cedar Creek/Hwy 50                 Glynn
St. Simons Island/Harrington       Glynn
Turtle River/Hwy 303               Glynn
Blythe Island/Turtle River         Glynn
Jekyll Island/Jekyll Creek         Glynn
South Brunswick River/Hwy 303      Glynn
Little Satilla River/Hwy 17        Camden
White Oak Creek/Hwy 17             Camden
Dark Entry Creek/Hwy 40            Camden
St. Marys Bridge/Hwy 17            Camden
</pre>

<h2>Boat Ramp Repair</h2>

<p> Boating access in coastal Georgia is relatively limited
overall and is woefully inadequate in some coastal counties and
population centers to meet the demands of ever-increasing
marine-based recreation. Over half of the existing public boat
ramps accessing saltwaters are in need of some degree of repair.
DNR has identified 20 boat ramps that exhibit various degrees of
deterioration, ranging from cracking and separation to extreme
erosion that prevents boat launching at low tide.</p>

<p> Many of the coastal boat ramps need repairs. Erosion from
tidal currents has resulted in dangerous drop offs at the base of
some ramps, resulting in the collapse of the lower portion of the
ramp and even loss of vehicles and trailers. Presently, DNR owns
or controls 11 public boat ramps in Georgia's saltwaters with the
remaining 23 belonging to local city or county governments.
During FY-97, efforts will be directed to surveying these coastal
ramps to identify existing conditions, set priorities, formulate
specific recommendations for repairs, and determine the most
appropriate approach for repairs.</p>

<p> </p>

<pre>

                    Boat Ramps Recommended for Repairs 
                        (priority to be determined)
 
Ramp Site                          County

Houlihan Bridge/Savannah River     Chatham
Bell's Landing                     Chatham
