<body>

<h1>Socio-Economic Angler Survey</h1>

<p> </p>

<h2>Clark Evans, Project Leader</h2>

<p> Email: <a href="mailto:clark@dnrcrd.dnr.state.ga.us">
clark@dnrcrd.dnr.state.ga.us </a></p>

<p> Phone: (912)264-7218</p>

<p> <img src="art/blue_marble.gif"></p>

<p> Efforts to determine the economic value of Georgia's marine
recreational fishery have, to date, been limited. The most recent
economic survey was produced by the Sport Fishing Institute
utilizing data obtained from the National Survey of Fishing,
Hunting, and Wildlife-Associated Recreation. As the marine
portion of the National Survey in Georgia was based on a sample
size of less than 30 individuals who saltwater fished, results
from the SFI study yielded extrapolated values that are
questionable in regards to their scope and accuracy.</p>

<p> Baseline economic data related to the marine recreational
fishery allow for the accurate determination of the economic
impacts of the fishery to the state. Additionally, this
information is essential to the determination of the economic
impacts of regulations on the fishing public.</p>

<p> Marine recreational fisheries also have value in attributes
which are less tangible or are not immediately quantifiable.
These attributes can be measured in terms of demographics,
attitudes, motivations, satisfactions, fishing behaviors,
participation rates, and management preferences. It has been
asserted that fishery managers must consider human benefits and
angler experiences as tangible elements which can be quantified
or modified. Without this key information managers lack the
ability to effectively predict the impacts of regulatory actions
on the affected user group or to determine angler acceptance of
management measures. </p>

<p> In 1990, CRD attempted to document the attitudes of Georgia
resident saltwater anglers about present and future management
issues. The study methodology employed a single survey instrument
and provided a &quot;snap shot&quot; of angler attitudes and
opinions as they were at the time of the survey. A primary
conclusion of the report noted the need to undertake additional
survey work to determine socio-economic characteristics,
demographics, and management preferences of Georgia saltwater
anglers.</p>

<p> Angler motivations, satisfactions, participation rates,
management preferences, attitudes and opinions can change over
time. A problematic aspect of investigating these factors is that
a single survey instrument will provide only a static indication
of what are essentially dynamic attributes. In an ongoing study
of Texas saltwater anglers, Texas A&amp;M University has employed
a longitudinal panel study design. A subgroup of anglers have
been surveyed twice a year since 1989. This design allows for the
identification of changes in fishing participation and management
preferences over time.</p>

<p> The ultimate success of any fisheries management policy is
dependent on the modification of human behavior, voluntary or
enforced. Therefore, managers must understand the human component
of the management equation which is essential to understanding
and implementing effective regulatory measures. An increased
understanding of the human dimension of the marine recreational
fishery is absolutely essential in the development of a
foundation for advocacy and long-term support. </p>

<p> GOALS &amp; OBJECTIVE:</p>

<p> 1) To achieve a better understanding of the socio-economic
aspects of the Georgia marine recreational fishery for purposes
of incorporation into a responsive management strategy.</p>

<p> EXPECTED RESULTS &amp; BENEFITS:</p>

<p> Information regarding the value of Georgia's marine
recreational fishery will enhance agency ability in assessing the
cost/benefit of State expenditures which is essential to the
budgeting process. Data specific to the economic expenditures of
the angler population will allow for the determination of
economic impacts of management measures. Attitudinal,
participation, motivation, satisfaction, and management
preference data will more clearly define the angler population
and will provide an indication of the acceptance of current or
proposed management measures. Additionally, gathering these data
over a period of years, via a subgroup, will provide a continuous
feedback mechanism through which long-term support and advocacy
will be fostered. </p>

<p> APPROACH:</p>

<p> Feasibility Study (FY 97): Year one of the study will be
devoted to determining the appropriate methodologies and
associated costs for statewide survey of Georgia saltwater
anglers and subsequent sub-sample surveys (Job 1). A review of
the relevant human dimensions literature will be conducted to
gather applicable research theory, survey methods, sample size
considerations, and to refine project goals and objectives.
Practical information will be gathered via interviews with state
agency and university researchers having experience with similar
surveys. Information collected from the literature review and
interviews will then be incorporated into a project methodology
specific to application in Georgia. </p>

<p> Statewide Survey (FY 98): A statewide survey of saltwater
anglers will be developed and administered to Georgia saltwater
anglers in year two (Job 2). Questions will focus on
demographics, expenditures, participation, and other issues of
importance. Survey data will be collected, reduced, and analyzed
to produce a final report containing baseline economic data,
participation rates, and demographics. This information will be
supplied to the state legislature, state fisheries managers,
citizens advisory committees, federal fisheries managers,
interstate fisheries management commissions, and the public.</p>

<p> Panel Survey I (FY 99): During year three, a representative
sub-sample, or panel, of Georgia saltwater anglers will be
developed based on the demographics of responses to the statewide
survey (Job 3). Surveys will be developed and administered twice
yearly. Questions will focus on expenditures, attitudes,
motivations, satisfactions, and management preferences for actual
and proposed measures. Survey data will be collected, reduced,
analyzed, and reported semi-annually. This information will be
made available to the state legislature, state fisheries
managers, citizens advisory committees, federal fisheries
managers, interstate fisheries management commissions, and the
public. Additionally, the panel of anglers will receive,
semi-annually, a 2-4 page synopsis of the results of each survey.</p>

<p> Panel Survey II (FY 00): Two surveys will be developed and
administered to the panel of saltwater anglers in year four (Job
4). Again, questions will focus on expenditures, attitudes,
motivations, satisfactions, and management preferences for actual
and proposed measures. Survey data will be collected, reduced,
analyzed, and reported bi-annually. This information will be made
available to the state legislature, state fisheries managers,
citizens advisory committees, federal fisheries managers,
interstate fisheries management commissions, and the public.
Additionally, the panel of anglers will receive, semi-annually, a
2-4 page synopsis of the results of each survey. </p>

<p> <img src="art/blue_bar.gif"></p>

