<head>
<title>Fisheries Management Home Page</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body background="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/images/whttxtr1.jpg" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p>[ <a href="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/index.htm">Home</a> | <a href="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/news.htm">What's New</a> | <a href="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/toc.htm">TOC</a> | <a href="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/feedback.htm">Feedback</a> | <a href="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/search.htm">Search</a> ]</p>
<h2><img src="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/images/wrd.gif" align=left hspace=0 width=100 height=100>Fisheries Management Home Page</h2>
<p>The Fisheries Section manages, protects, and encourages the wise use of the freshwater fishery resources in 
Georgia. The section operates 10 public fishing areas for public fishing and conducts research and sampling of 
the fish populations in over one-half million acres of impoundments, 4,000 miles of trout streams and 12,000 
miles of warmwater streams. The section operates two trout hatcheries and seven warmwater fish hatcheries for stocking fish 
into public waters and private ponds. The section investigates fish kills in public waters, develops and maintains boating access 
facilities, produces aquatic education materials and information about fishing and fishing opportunities, evaluates the impacts of 
development projects on aquatic resources, controls aquatic weeds, and teaches youth to fish. The section also assists private 
pond owners in managing their ponds.</p>
<hr>
<p>Richard M. Gennings, Chief<br>
DNR--Wildlife Resources Division<br>
Fisheries Management Section<br>
2070 U.S. Hwy. 278, S.E.<br>
Social Circle, GA 30279<br>
(770) 918-6406<br>
<br>
More about the Fisheries Section<br>
Mission Statement<br>
Fisheries Offices--Phone numbers and locations of fisheries offices, public fishing areas, and hatcheries<br>
Aquaculture Program--find out about the growing aquaculture industry in Georgia and what permits and licenses are required 
to raise and/or sell fish, mussels, etc<br>
Aquatic Education Program-- materials available to educators that want to teach youth and adults about aquatic resources<br>
Aquatic Weed Program--how to control aquatic weeds in your pond or lake and how aquatic weeds can be beneficial<br>
Boating Access--where to launch a boat<br>
Fish Hatcheries &amp; Stocking--information on fish hatcheries and stocking program<br>
Fish Kill Reporting &amp; Investigations--what to do if you see dead or dying fish<br>
Fishing and its benefits to Georgia-- interesting facts about fishing and its economic impacts<br>
Fishing Licenses--what licenses you need before you go fishing and how to purchase them<br>
Fishing Opportunities--learn about the abundance of freshwater fishing opportunities available, read fishing predictions, hear 
the latest lake updates, or find a new place to fish<br>
Fishing Regulations--1996-97 freshwater and saltwater fishing regulations<br>
Guidelines for Eating Fish from Georgia Waters--learn about the health benefits and risks of eating fish taken from public 
waters and steps you can take to reduce your risks<br>
Management of Public Waters--learn what type of research and survey activities are done, and why, to best manage 
Georgia&#146;s diverse freshwater fishery resources<br>
Private Pond Owners--services to help pond owners manage ponds and fish populations<br>
Public Fishing Areas-- great fishing areas run by the Wildlife Resources Division<br>
Sport Fish Restoration Program--how anglers and boaters contribute to conserving aquatic resources<br>
Turn In Poachers Program- report poaching and other wildlife-related violations<br>
