<head>
<title>F.Y.I. (For Your Information)</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/images/whttxtr1.jpg"
bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p><font size="6"><strong><u>P</u></strong></font><font size="5"><strong><u>RESERVATION</u></strong></font><font
size="6"><strong><u> I</u></strong></font><font size="5"><strong><u>NFORMATION</u></strong></font></p>
<p><font size="4">This months preservation news...</font></p>
<p><font size="5"><strong><u>October, 1996</u></strong></font><br>
</p>
<p><font size="4"><u>A Celebration of Southern Places</u></font><br>
<em>Theme for 1997 Conference </em></p>
<p>The 1997 historic preservation conference, jointly sponsored
by the Historic Preservation Division and the Georgia Trust for
Historic Preservation will be held Sunday through Wednesday,
November 2 - 7, 1997, at the Classic Center in Athens. The state
conference will be held in conjunction with the southeastern
State Historic Preservation Offices annual meeting, which is
being held in Georgia for the first time since 1986. </p>
<p>The theme of the conference is A Celebration of Southern
Places. The keynote speaker will be Dr. Bill Ferris, director of
the Center for the Study of Southern Culture at the University of
Mississippi in Oxford, and editor of The Southern Register, the
Center&#146;s quarterly newsletter, which celebrates the South
through a study of its history, culture, and arts.Dr.
Ferris&#146; keynote has been underwritten by the Athens-based
rock group R.E.M. Long-time supporters of preservation, R.E.M. is
the first sponsor of the 1997 conference. As in past years, HPD
and the Georgia Trust will be soliciting additional sponsorships
for <br>
underwriting conference expenses. </p>
<p>The goal of the 1997 conference will be to highlight the
unique qualities of southern heritage and resources, and to
celebrate the many people, places, and traditions that make up
the culture of the South. The conference program will also be a
vehicle for teaching, and will introduce ideas, concepts and
techniques in preservation practices that are on the cutting edge
of preservation activity. </p>
<p>If you are interested in a conference sponsorship, or if you
have program ideas, contact Carole Moore, conference coordinator,
at 404-651-5268. </p>
<p><font size="4">Program Notes </font></p>
<p><font size="4">Civil War Commission</font><br>
The Georgia Trust has given the HPD a &#147;Certificate of
Merit&#148; for the Resaca Preservation Plan, developed by the
Jaeger Company, with an HPD grant. As a part of the recent
American Battlefield Protection Program meeting in Chattanooga
participants visited the Resaca battlefield and were given an
overview of future plans. </p>
<p><font size="4">Environmental Review</font><br>
The HPD is planning a one-day training conference for DNR
employees on December 13 at the Forsyth Training Facility. The
purpose of this training session is to assist DNR associates in
interpreting Section 106 and GEPA regulations on state-owned
lands. </p>
<p><font size="4">Planning</font><br>
HPD staff is assisting the Georgia Downtown Development Authority
in two training workshops: the first was held in Athens on
September 28, and the second will be held on Jekyll Island on
October 16. Contact Bruce Green of the Office of Downtown
Development at 404-658-0472 if you are interested in their
training programs. </p>
<p><font size="4">National Register</font><br>
The HPD held the fall National Register Review Board Meeting in
Chattanooga on September 19 and presented 17 nominations. All
were accepted by the Review Board and will be finalized and sent
to the NPS for review and approval. </p>
<p><font size="4">Technical Assistance <br>
</font>The next technical presentation of the Architectural
Conservation Forum will be held at noon on October 24. The topic
of the Forum will be &#147;Historic Landscapes: Charleston
Gardens&#148; presented by Jim Cothran of Robert &amp; Company.
It will be held in the fifth floor conference room of the HPD
offices in the Healey Building. Contact Tracey Rutherford at HPD
for further information. </p>
<p>On November 20, HPD will offer a tax incentives workshop for
preservation consultants, regional planners, and Main Street
managers. The workshop will offer a comprehensive look at the tax
program format, National Register eligibility, and architectural
review questions. Call Mary Ann Eaddy for further information. </p>
<p><font size="4">Staff Notes<br>
</font>Ken Thomas has been appointed to the Board of the Center
for the Study of Georgia History. </p>
<p>Pratt Cassity and Lisa Vogel of the Office of Preservation
Services have co-authored an article for Historic Preservation
Forum, the 1996 summer issue. The article &#147;The Buck Stops .
. . Where?&#148; discusses use of local historic preservation
regulations in the Harry S. Truman Heritage District in
Independence, Missouri. Historic preservation guidelines for <br>
the district were first designated by the City Council in 1974. </p>
<p>Michael Miller recently participated in an affordable housing
workshop sponsored by the National Park Service. The workshop
brought together professionals from a number of state offices
which had successfully used the tax act program in promoting
affordable housing projects. Each discussed their state&#146;s
projects, and the way in which the Secretary <br>
of the Interior&#146;s Standards for Rehabilitation were
implemented in successful and unsuccessful projects. The NPS hope
to use this information in future Interpreting the Standards
Bulletins. </p>
<p><font size="4">Who to Call in HPD</font><br>
Questions? Who do you call? <br>
<br>
For information on how to list a property on the <strong>Georgia
and National Register</strong>, to inquire about an <strong>already
listed property</strong> or to receive information on the <strong>State
Review Board Agenda</strong>:<br>
Lee Webb 651-5911<br>
Leslie Sharp 651-6782<br>
<br>
For questions on the <strong>Georgia Survey Program</strong>:<br>
Kenneth Gibbs 651-6432<br>
<br>
For questions or advice with the <strong>American With
Disabilities Act, the Investment Tax Credit, or technical and
architectural information:</strong><br>
Mary Ann Eaddy 651-5181<br>
Marty Goldsmith 651-5567<br>
Angie Edwards 651-5566<br>
Michael Miller 651-5287<br>
<br>
For questions on the Georgia Heritage 2000 grant program or the
Historic Preservation Fund grant program:<br>
Daryl Barksdale 651-5181<br>
<br>
For general questions regarding <strong>transportation and
planning issues</strong>:<br>
