<br>
To receive <strong>HPD publications</strong>:<br>
Karen Luehrs 651-5280<br>
Carole Moore 651-5268<br>
<br>
For information about the <strong>CLG Program</strong>:<br>
Pratt Cassity 706-542-4731 </p>
<p><br>
<font size="4">Conferences </font></p>
<p>The National Trust for Historic Preservation&#146;s 50th
National Preservation Conference, Preserving Community: City,
Suburb and Countryside, will be held October 16 - 20 in Chicago.
The conference is being held in conjunction with
Restoration/Chicago, October 18 - 20, at the Chicago Navy Pier.
For further information, contact the National Trust at 1-<br>
800-944-NTHP. </p>
<p>The Popular Culture Association in the South will celebrate
their 25th anniversary meeting in Savannah October 17 - 20. The
conference will cover wide-ranging issues on popular culture and
American cultural studies. Contact Diane Calhoun-French,
Jefferson Community College, Louisville, Kentucky. </p>
<p>The 1996 Lovable Communities Conference, sponsored by the
South Carolina Downtown Development Association, will be held in
Charleston on October 21 - 26. The goal of the conference will be
to explore the ideas, celebrate the attitude, develop the place
and feed the need existing beyond livable communities. For
further information, contact the South Carolina </p>
<p>Downtown Development Authority, PO Box 11637, Columbus, South
Carolina 29211. Phone 803-256-3560. </p>
<p>The Georgia Main Street Association will be holding its annual
conference October 20 - 22, in Cartersville. The theme of the
conference is Tourism: It&#146;s in the Bag!. The four point
approach of the Main Street Program: Design, Organization,
Promotion, and Economic Restructuring are all linked to tourism.
The keynote speaker will be Don Rypkema, principal of the Real
Estate Service Group in Washington D.C. For further information,
contact the Georgia Main Street Association, c/o A. Arnold,
Treasurer, Three Wall Street, Cartersville, Georgia 30120. Phone
770-386-6458. </p>
<p>The American Institute of Architects and The American
Institute for Conservation of Historic and Artistic Works are
jointly sponsoring a conference titled: Architects and
Conservators: Preserving the Past and Building the Future, in
Alexandria and Natchitoches, Louisiana on October 31 - November
3. The goal of the conference will be to examine the role and
impact of the architect and conservator on historic preservation
projects. The conference will be cosponsored by the National
Center for Preservation Technology and Training. For further
information, contact the American Institute of Architects
Historic <br>
Resources Committee, 202-626-7518. </p>
<p>Stalking the Wild Cottage: Florida Vernacular Architecture and
how it came to Seaside is the title of a workshop co-sponsored by
The Seaside Institute and CUBE, at Seaside, Florida, November 1 -
2. This basic workshop develops an understanding of
&#147;community making&#148; within the context of Seaside,
designed by the renowned town planners Elizabeth <br>
Plater-Zybeck and Andres Duany. For further information, contact
CUBE at 913-262-0691. The 38th Annual Seminar for Historical
Administration at Colonial Williamsburg will take place November
3 - 23. The goal of the seminar is to develop and strengthen
leadership within the historical organization and museum
community, and is cosponsored by the Colonial Williamsburg
Foundation, the American Association of Museums, the American
Association for State and Local History, and the National Trust
for Historic Preservation. For further information contact Peggy
McDonald Howells, The Colonial Williamsburg Foundation,
804-220-7211. </p>
<p>Playing for Keeps: An International Town Meeting, a conference
sponsored by the Smithsonian Institution, will take place
November 16 - 19 in Washington, D.C. The conference will
celebrate SOS! results and consider next steps for action.
Sculptor Luis Jimenez is the keynote speaker. For further
information, contact SOS! Town Meeting, National Institute for
the Conservation of Cultural Property, 3299 K Street, NW,
Washington, DC 20007-4415. </p>
<p>Capitalize on Collections Care: A Fund-Raising Workshop is
scheduled for Atlanta on November 19. Sponsored by SOLINET, this
workshop is designed for librarians, archivists and museum
professionals responsible for incorporating collections care into
their fundraising activities. Contact Lauren Fallon, SOLINET,
404-892-0843 for further information. </p>
<p><font size="4">Bulletin Board</font><br>
<br>
The History Computerization Project of the Regional History
Center of the University of Southern California and the Los
Angeles City Historical Society is building a history information
network for the exchange of information between historians,
librarians, archivists, museum curators, preservation groups, and
historical societies. The project employs the History DataBase
Program and is used for both cataloging and research with all
types of historical materials. The Project&#146;s home page on
the Internet gives you information on using the free History
Database tutorial and links to historical resources at <br>
libraries, archives, museums and organizations around the world.
Visit the project at: <a
href="http://www.history.la.ca.us/history">http://www.history.la.ca.us/history</a>. </p>
<p>Traveling Exhibits on folk arts and Southern culture are
available through the Southern Arts Federation planned with small
and mid-sized communities in mind; each exhibit is available for
rental for one to three months at a reasonable cost. Exhibit
topics include: African American Gardens and Yards, Cajun Music
&amp; Zydeco, Georgia Clay: Pottery, Sacred Space: The
Mississippi Delta, and others. For information, contact Exhibits
Coordinator Evelyn Garlington at 404-874-7244. </p>
<p>The Atlanta Accessibility Guide, a comprehensive guide to the
accessibility of many Atlanta buildings and attractions, has been
recently published by the Shepherd Center and the American
Society of Interior Designers - Georgia Chapter. It is available
from the Shepherd Center at 404-350-7473 or the ASID office at
404-231-3938. There is a charge of $2 each for more than three
copies. </p>
<p><font size="4"><strong>The National Historic Preservation Act
was passed by Congress in October, 1966, making it </strong></font><font
color="#FF0000"><font size="4"><strong>thirty years old</strong></font></font><font
size="4"><strong> this month. </strong></font></p>
<p><br>
</p>
