<body>
<p><br>
<br>
<br>
<em><u>CHAPTER ONE</u></em><br>
<br>
<font size=5>Vision, Mission and Goals</font><br>
</p>
<hr>
<p><br>
A Vision for Historic Preservation in Georgia<br>
<br>
Georgia will be a better place tomorrow than it is today, providing quality communities in which<br>
to live, work, learn and recreate. Historic places will be widely valued as irreplaceable resources<br>
that contribute to our heritage, our economy, our neighborhoods, and our sense of who we are as<br>
Georgians. Communities and the State will plan for growth and change that respects and includes<br>
our historic places. Communities will possess the knowledge, the legal and financial tools, and<br>
the authority to decide how preservation and new development will relate to one another. There<br>
will still be distinctions between city and suburbs, developing areas and countryside. All<br>
Georgians will possess a greater understanding and appreciation of our shared heritage in all its<br>
variations. People and organizations throughout Georgia will work in partnership to preserve and<br>
use historic places. Georgia's communities, economy, environment and people will be better<br>
because of the preservation of historic resources.<br>
<br>
<em><strong><u>MISSION STATEMENT</u></strong></em><br>
<br>
The Historic Preservation Division's mission is to promote the preservation and use of historic<br>
places for a better Georgia.<br>
<br>
<em><strong><u>GOALS FOR PRESERVATION IN GEORGIA</u></strong></em><br>
<br>
1. Achieve widespread public awareness and involvement in historic preservation in Georgia.<br>
<br>
2. Gather information about all historic resources in Georgia, and make the information<br>
accessible for planning, advocacy and educational purposes.<br>
<br>
3. Secure financial and legal tools sufficient to preserve the significant historic resources in<br>
Georgia.<br>
<br>
4. Strengthen and expand the coordinated network of historic preservation organizations<br>
throughout the state.<br>
<br>
5. Protect and use Georgia's historic places so that they may exist into the future.<br>
<br>
These five goals represent the consensus of preservationists and other community and state<br>
leaders who helped create this plan. These goals will guide the Historic Preservation Division's<br>
actions, funding priorities, and policies through the year 2000. They are listed in order of priority<br>
and in the order in which preservation activity must take place--at the statewide level and at the<br>
local level--for historic places to truly be protected, preserved, used and appreciated. This plan is<br>
directed toward accomplishing the five goals, in order to make the Vision a reality in Georgia's<br>
future.<br>
</p>
