<body>
<p>CHAPTER TWO<br>
<br>
<font size=4><em><strong><u>Historic Resources in Georgia</u></strong></em></font><br>
</p>
<hr>
<p><br>
Georgia was founded in 1733 as one of the thirteen original American colonies. For the next<br>
two-and-a-half centuries, its history was shaped largely by the activities and interactions of three<br>
peoples: Euro-Americans intent on creating a &quot;New World&quot; in America, African-Americans<br>
largely caught up in the creation of this new world, and American Indians who ultimately were<br>
dispossessed of it. For two centuries prior to English colonization, the Spanish with their African<br>
servants and slaves explored and settled what would later become Georgia. This<br>
African-European presence was itself preceded by thousands of years of American Indian<br>
occupation. <br>
<br>
The 10,000-year history of what we now know as Georgia has left its mark all across the state. <br>
Not only in metropolitan areas, where the signs of development are everywhere, but also in the<br>
most remote mountain valleys, along apparently undeveloped rivers and streams, across vast<br>
stretches of field and forest, deep in seemingly inaccessible swamps, and along coastal marshes<br>
and islands--there is hardly an acre of land in Georgia untouched by the past. <br>
<br>
The evidence of history takes the form of buildings and structures, historic and archeological sites,<br>
historic landscapes and traditional cultural properties, and historic districts. These are Georgia's<br>
historic properties. They provide a window into our past, and a foundation on which to build a<br>
vision for our future. Preserving these historic properties is what historic preservation is all<br>
about.<br>
<br>
An Overview of Georgia's Historic Properties<br>
<br>
Buildings<br>
<br>
For many people, buildings are the most familiar type of historic property in Georgia. Certainly<br>
the most obvious, they dominate Georgia's listings in the National Register of Historic Places. <br>
Usually categorized by function, Georgia's historic buildings include a wide variety of houses,<br>
stores and offices, factories and mills, outbuildings on farms and plantations, and community<br>
landmarks.<br>
<br>
Houses are the most prevalent type of historic building in Georgia. They make up approximately<br>
70% of all the Georgia listings in the National Register and nearly 80% of all surveyed properties. <br>
Most historic houses in Georgia are one-story high with wood frames and siding. Others are built<br>
of brick; a few are constructed of stone. The single-family detached house is the most common<br>
house form in the state, although apartment buildings are found in most larger communities and<br>
rowhouses highlight Savannah. <br>
<br>
Approximately one-third of Georgia's historic housing is located in the state's cities and larger<br>
towns; another third is found in smaller towns; and the remaining third is dispersed throughout the<br>
countryside. Three-quarters of all the extant historic houses in Georgia were built between 1890<br>
and World War II. As important as individual buildings, houses with their landscaped yards and<br>
associated domestic archeological resources form a special category of historic property known as<br>
&quot;Georgia's Living Places.&quot; In rural areas, historic houses serve as the centerpieces of farms and<br>
plantations; in communities, houses grouped together form historic neighborhoods.<br>
<br>
Commercial buildings including stores and offices constitute only about 5% of Georgia's historic<br>
buildings, but they are the second most numerous type of historic building in Georgia. <br>
Commercial buildings tend to be concentrated in communities, often forming a cohesive business<br>
district or &quot;downtown,&quot; although some like the country store are found in sparsely settled rural<br>
areas and others like the corner store are situated in residential neighborhoods. In addition to the<br>
country and corner stores, common Georgia examples include the small-town &quot;storefront&quot;<br>
building, the larger city business block, and the urban skyscraper. <br>
<br>
Brick is a common building material, although wood is used in some rural and small-town<br>
commercial buildings; big-city buildings employ steel and concrete. Most extant historic<br>
commercial buildings in Georgia date from the late 19th through the early 20th centuries.<br>
<br>
Industrial buildings in Georgia are not numerous, constituting only about 1% of all surveyed<br>
buildings, yet they represent some of the largest and most economically important historic<br>
buildings in the state. Georgia's industrial buildings include factories, mills, warehouses, gins, and<br>
multi-purpose lofts. They usually are located in or adjacent to communities, often along rivers or<br>
railroads, sometimes grouped in industrial areas or districts. <br>
<br>
A distinct form of self-contained community, the mill village, grew up around some industrial<br>
buildings, usually late 19th or early 20th century textile mills. In contrast, rural grist mills with<br>
their characteristic dams and millponds are located near sources of waterpower, often in isolated<br>
areas. Most rural mills are constructed of wood with heavy mortised-and-tenoned wood frames,<br>
although a few are built of brick or stone. <br>
<br>
Most of the larger urban factories are constructed of brick with &quot;slow burning&quot; heavy timber<br>
frames. Twentieth-century industrial buildings often were constructed with steel or concrete<br>
frames and concrete and brick walls, for durability and to make them relatively fireproof.<br>
<br>
Agricultural buildings are representative of the major role played by agriculture throughout<br>
Georgia's history. Historically, agriculture dominated land use across the state. Agricultural<br>
buildings are found in most rural areas, usually in complexes, along with other structures and<br>
landscape features comprising farmsteads or plantations. The typical historic Georgia farm<br>
consists of a late 19th or early 20th century farmhouse, half a dozen outbuildings, a yard, and<br>
agricultural land. <br>
Approximately 10% of all surveyed houses in the state are associated with farms. Associated<br>
historic agricultural buildings typically include tenant farmhouses, barns, cotton gins, mills, and<br>
offices, although the complete list of Georgia's agricultural outbuildings is seemingly endless.<br>
<br>
Community landmark buildings are a small but diverse group of historic buildings housing<br>
community institutions such as local governments, religious groups, civic organizations, hospitals,<br>
and schools. Although they account for only about 5% of all surveyed buildings, community<br>
landmarks are prominent due to their large size, architectural treatment, and strategic location. <br>
They are focal points, literally and figuratively, for their communities. Common examples include<br>
courthouses, city halls, post offices, churches, lodges and clubhouses, libraries, jails, depots,<br>
theaters, and community centers.<br>
<br>
Structures<br>
<br>
Structures are defined as &quot;functional constructions made usually for purposes other than creating<br>
shelter.&quot; In other words, structures are not primarily places in which to live or work, although<br>
they may be occupied for short periods of time or used in work or other activities. Many<br>
structures resemble buildings and are differentiated from them only by function; other kinds of<br>
structures are fundamentally different than buildings. Many structures are physically or<br>
functionally related to buildings and are sometimes considered subsidiary to them; some are found<br>
in complexes while others stand alone.<br>
<br>
Common kinds of historic structures in Georgia include wells, water towers, agricultural<br>
outbuildings such as corn cribs or implement sheds, military fortifications, bridges, and railroads<br>
(rail beds). Other familiar although less numerous structures include lighthouses, tunnels, dams,<br>
and locomotives. Less familiar types of structures include mines and quarries.<br>
<br>
Structured Environments<br>
<br>
Another kind of historic structure, less commonly recognized, is what might be called a structured<br>
environment: the large-scale, two-dimensional plans or patterns that underlie and shape historic<br>
development. Historic structured environments are found all across Georgia, in cities, towns, and<br>
rural areas. They include city plans, courthouse squares, the layout of parks, gardens, cemeteries,<br>
and yards, agricultural field patterns, and land-lot lines.<br>
<br>
Sites<br>
<br>
A site is defined as &quot;the location of a significant event ... occupation, or activity, or a building or<br>
structure, whether standing, ruined, or vanished, where the location itself possesses historic,<br>
cultural, or archeological value ....&quot; There are several distinct types of sites in Georgia.<br>
<br>
Archeological sites, both historic and prehistoric, are the most numerous if not the most familiar<br>
type of historic property in Georgia. More than 25,000 archeological sites are recorded in the<br>
Georgia Archeological Site File. Approximately 2,000 newly discovered sites are added each<br>
year, yet only a small fraction of the state has been surveyed methodically for archeological<br>
resources.<br>
<br>
A wide variety of archeological sites exists in Georgia. Some sites are complex &quot;stratified&quot; sites,<br>
with various layers representing different periods of occupation and use. Other complex sites are<br>
&quot;multi-component&quot; locations of prehistoric villages. Less complex sites may represent a single<br>
activity or use, such as hunting or fishing, manufacturing or quarrying, or camping. Archeological<br>
sites in Georgia usually contain artifacts made from stone, bone, ceramic, metal, wood, paper, and<br>
glass, even fabric, food remains, and plant matter. Major river valleys, ridge lines, and the Fall<br>
Line have yielded the greatest numbers of archeological sites. A less well-known type of<br>
archeological site, the underwater site, is found on river bottoms, in coastal marshes, and off the<br>
coast on the continental shelf. <br>
<br>
Prehistoric Indians built monumental architecture, in the form of earthen and stone mounds<br>
scattered over the Georgia landscape, since the beginning of the Christian era. They were most<br>
pronounced in the period 1250-1500 A.D. Many still stand.<br>
<br>
Prehistoric archeological sites in Georgia include earthen mounds and platforms, shell middens in<br>
the form of piles and rings, rock quarries, fishing weirs, rock piles, scattered stone chips, and<br>
concentrations of broken pottery. Examples of historic archeological sites include Revolutionary<br>
and Civil War trenches and earthworks, industrial sites, subsurface evidence of former landscape<br>
features, buildings, and structures such as the former Cherokee Nation capitol at New Echota,<br>
and refuse dumps. Underwater archeological sites include submerged ships, piers and wharfs,<br>
building foundations, trash dumps, river crossings, and evidence of former waterfront activities. <br>
Graves also can be considered as archeological sites, although state and federal laws protecting<br>
burial sites severely restrict their archeological investigation.<br>
<br>
Historic sites are places where a significant event or activity took place but where there were no<br>
buildings or structures associated with the event or activity or where the associated buildings or<br>
structures no longer exist. Historic sites are important primarily for the events or activities which<br>
took place there, although significant archeological resources also may be present at the site. <br>
<br>
Historic sites may be characterized by distinctive natural features, like a mountain or cave or tree,<br>
or they may simply be the place where something important happened, like an open field. Good<br>
examples of historic sites in Georgia are the Jeff Davis Capture Site in Irwin County and the<br>
Bloody Marsh battle site in Glynn County. Historic sites are often marked by historic markers or<br>
plaques.<br>
<br>
Traditional cultural properties are a newly recognized type of historic site. This type may be a<br>
distinctive natural place (such as a mountaintop) or historic environment (such as an ethnic<br>
neighborhood), or it may be simply a spatial location, a place, having pronounced historic cultural<br>
value to a living racial, ethnic, or cultural group today. Historical associations with such<br>
properties may be demonstrated through historical documentation, but more likely through<br>
traditional uses or practices, oral history, or common cultural knowledge. Because traditional<br>
cultural properties may be significant for metaphysical reasons, they may be especially difficult to<br>
detect by &quot;outsiders.&quot; Although no traditional cultural properties have been officially recognized<br>
in Georgia, several have been tentatively identified.<br>
<br>
Landscapes<br>
<br>
Landscapes are a special type of historic property combining elements of &quot;sites&quot; and &quot;structures&quot;<br>
and often including buildings as well. Most historic landscapes also contain archeological<br>
resources. Historic landscapes often are overlooked, taken for granted, or misunderstood as<br>
&quot;natural&quot; resources.<br>
<br>
Georgia contains a variety of historic landscapes. They range from small formal gardens to vast<br>
expanses of agricultural countryside and planted woodlands. Typical examples are courthouse<br>
squares (often the largest public landscape space in a community), city parks, streetscapes in<br>
neighborhoods with their street trees and sidewalks, and cemeteries. A well-documented type of<br>
historic landscape in Georgia is the yard; nine major forms of historic domestic landscaping have<br>
been identified through the Georgia's Living Places project.<br>
<br>
Historic Districts<br>
<br>
Historic districts are another special type of historic resource. Defined as &quot;a significant<br>
concentration, linkage, or continuity of sites, buildings, structures, or objects united historically or<br>
aesthetically by plan or physical development,&quot; a historic district contains a combination of the<br>
other types of historic properties--buildings, structures, sites, landscapes, structured<br>
environments--where the overall grouping, the ensemble, takes on an identity and significance<br>
greater than the individual components. <br>
<br>
Historic districts make up about 25% of Georgia's National Register listings, yet they include<br>
more than 95% of all the historic properties listed in the National Register. Because they contain<br>
such a variety of historic properties, in their historic spatial relationships, historic districts best<br>
represent what our historic environments really were like.<br>
<br>
The most common type of historic district in Georgia is the residential neighborhood. Second in<br>
frequency is the downtown central business district. Other important but less numerous types of<br>
historic districts include industrial and warehousing areas, school campuses, military installations,<br>
parks, and waterfronts. Georgia has several extensive archeological districts containing<br>
historically and geographically related sites, such as the Etowah Valley district, and several vast<br>
rural historic districts containing multiple farms, rural communities, and historic rural landscapes,<br>
such as McLemore Cove and the Sautee-Nacoochee Valleys.<br>
<br>
How Many Are There?<br>
<br>
It is estimated that there are about 71,500 historic buildings in Georgia at the present time. Field<br>
survey information on over 26,000 buildings has been entered into the Historic Preservation<br>
Division's computerized database. Previously unsurveyed buildings are being added to the<br>
inventory at the rate of about 5,000 per year.<br>
<br>
Nobody knows exactly how many archeological sites exist in Georgia; because they are mostly<br>
underground (or under water), they are difficult to locate without expert field investigation. At<br>
the present time, more than 25,000 archeological sites have been identified and recorded in the<br>
University of Georgia's Archeological Site File, yet only a small percentage of the state's land area<br>
has been systematically searched for archeological sites. Newly discovered archeological sites are<br>
being reported at the rate of nearly 2,000 per year.<br>
<br>
Why do these numbers keep changing?<br>
<br>
The number of known and estimated historic properties in Georgia changes frequently, with good<br>
reason. On the one hand, known historic properties are lost due to demolition, remodeling, or<br>
destruction every year. A historic building may burn to the ground, or an archeological site may<br>
be bulldozed for a new shopping center. On the other hand, with the passage of time, properties<br>
that formerly were not old enough to be considered historic come of age, so to speak, and the<br>
expanding scope of history and archeology encompass properties not previously recognized as<br>
historic. In addition, continuing and improved field surveys identify more historic properties<br>
every year, and provide a better basis for estimating the total number of historic properties in the<br>
state. So, while the number of historic properties in Georgia at any given point in time is finite, it<br>
will change over time.<br>
<br>
Why are more historic properties being identified?<br>
<br>
The process of identifying and evaluating historic properties lies at the very heart of historic<br>
preservation. By its very nature, it is a continuing, neverending process. Just as time marches on,<br>
so does history, and historic preservation with it. <br>
<br>
The study of history and the practice of archeology, both of which underlie historic preservation,<br>
are dynamic. Both are constantly expanding. For example, historians are now studying what is<br>
called the &quot;recent past&quot;--the period from World War II through the 1960s--while archeologists are<br>
pushing back the dates of human occupation in Georgia to 10,000 years and more. Historians<br>
continue to expand on the achievements of Georgia's African-Americans with special interest in<br>
the 1960s Civil Rights movement, while archeologists and ethnologists are beginning to document<br>
American Indian traditional cultural properties overlooked in previous surveys. If we were to try<br>
to limit our universe of historic properties to only those previously recognized by historians and<br>
archeologists, we would be undermining the very basis of the historic preservation movement.<br>
<br>
Continuing and improving field surveys are identifying more historic properties than ever before<br>
all across the state. For example, a recently completed county survey identified 20 times the<br>
number of historic properties recorded in a 1970s survey of the county. By restricting the number<br>
of historic properties to those previously surveyed, we would be denying the obvious fact that<br>
many more historic properties exist.<br>
<br>
An expanding historic preservation constituency is bringing with it a broader view of historic<br>
properties. For example, increased participation by African-Americans has encouraged the<br>
broader recognition of African-American historic properties from the earliest days of exploration<br>
and settlement to the mid-20th-century Civil Rights movement. Interest on the part of American<br>
Indian groups has led to a heightened sensitivity to many types of prehistoric sites, particularly<br>
burials and traditional cultural properties. The important role played by women in historic<br>
preservation has resulted in new interest in women's history and associated historic properties. If<br>
we were to limit historic properties to those that we know now, many new interest groups would<br>
find their heritage excluded from the historic preservation movement. As more cultural and<br>
interest groups discover their heritage, their desire to preserve the historic places associated with<br>
that heritage grows.<br>
<br>
In short: to limit our universe of historic properties to what is currently known would artificially<br>
constrain historic preservation and directly controvert the intent of the National Historic<br>
Preservation Act which is to preserve properties which represent the &quot;broad patterns&quot; of<br>
American history as we best understand it.<br>
<br>
How many historic properties have been lost?<br>
<br>
No one knows how many archeological sites have been destroyed over the years. But every time<br>
ground-disturbing activity takes place, there is the potential for additional loss.<br>
<br>
It is clear, however, that the vast majority of all the historic buildings and structures that ever<br>
existed in Georgia already have been lost. In just the last 50 years, nearly three-quarters of the<br>
buildings and structures that existed prior to World War II have been lost through destruction or<br>
remodeling. And in some counties, more than one-quarter of the surveyed historic properties that<br>
existed twenty years ago are now gone.<br>
<br>
What kinds of buildings have been lost? Whose heritage has vanished? No detailed study has<br>
been done, but it appears that the greatest losses have been vernacular buildings, modest houses,<br>
tenant farm houses which once dotted every 40 acres or so, many utilitarian structures like mule<br>
barns, liveries, and warehouses, and many homes associated with African-Americans in cities,<br>
towns, and rural areas. Yet virtually every community has lost its share of local landmark<br>
buildings as well--stylish houses, sometimes whole streets of them, grand old hotels, business<br>
blocks, railroad depots, even courthouses.<br>
<br>
What Makes All These Properties &quot;Historic?&quot;<br>
<br>
To be considered &quot;historic,&quot; a property must have three essential attributes: sufficient age, a<br>
relatively high degree of integrity, and significance in history.<br>
<br>
Age<br>
<br>
A historic property must be old enough to be considered &quot;historic.&quot; Historic properties are, by<br>
definition, old, not new. Generally speaking, this means that a property must be at least 50 years<br>
old, although this is just a general rule, not an absolute requirement. Another way of looking at it<br>
is that a property must be old enough to be understood for the role it played in the community,<br>
state or nation so that its place in history is clear.<br>
<br>
Integrity<br>
<br>
In addition to having sufficient age, a property must also have retained what is called its<br>
&quot;integrity&quot; to be considered historic. For a building, structure, landscape feature, historic site, or<br>
historic district, this means that the property must be relatively unchanged. Its essential<br>
character-defining features must still be present. For an archeological site, integrity means that<br>
the site must be relatively undisturbed, with its patterns and layers of artifacts and other<br>
archeological evidence relatively intact. For a traditional cultural property, integrity means that<br>
the site must be recognizable to today's affiliated cultural group, documentable through tradition,<br>
and still used or revered in some way.<br>
<br>
Significance<br>
<br>
Finally, a property must be significant to be considered historic. Significance is generally defined<br>
in three ways: through direct association with individuals, events, activities, or developments that<br>
were important in the past--that shaped our history, or that reflect important aspects of our<br>
history; by embodying the distinctive physical and spatial characteristics of an architectural style<br>
or type of building, structure, landscape, or planned environment, or a method of construction, or<br>
by embodying high artistic values or fine craftsmanship; or by having the potential to yield<br>
information important to our understanding of the past through archeological, architectural, or<br>
other physical investigation and analysis.<br>
<br>
Who Decides What is Historic?<br>
<br>
Each of us may have our own personal opinions about what is historic and what is not. Similarly,<br>
different social and cultural groups of people may have different definitions of &quot;historic.&quot; Other<br>
interest groups in our society may look at historic properties in entirely different ways, or may not<br>
value them at all. An important part of historic preservation is the establishment of public<br>
processes through which consensus can be reached as to what is historic and what is not. Once<br>
this consensus has been reached, it becomes public preservation policy. There are several<br>
established ways in Georgia of publicly determining whether properties are historic and worthy of<br>
being preserved.<br>
<br>
National Register of Historic Places<br>
<br>
One of the most important ways in which we determine which of our properties are historic and<br>
which are not is the National Register of Historic Places. Ever since its creation by Congress<br>
through the National Historic Preservation Act of 1966, the National Register has been one of the<br>
foundations of historic preservation in Georgia and across the country. It provides uniform<br>
standards, a public process, and a national perspective for determining the significance and<br>
preservation worthiness of properties. Although the criteria for determining National Register<br>
eligibility are essentially unchanged since 1966, their interpretation and application to properties<br>
are continuously clarified and updated through published guidance and bulletins. Listing in the<br>
National Register, or determining National Register eligibility, is one of the clearest statements of<br>
public policy about what is historic and worthy of being preserved.<br>
<br>
At the present time there are more than 1,600 official Georgia listings in the National Register<br>
representing more than 38,000 historic properties in the state. Historic properties in Georgia are<br>
being added to the National Register at the rate of approximately 45 listings representing some<br>
1,750 historic properties per year. Georgia ranks about 10th in the nation in the number of<br>
National Register-listed properties.<br>
<br>
Georgia Register of Historic Places<br>
<br>
Established in 1989, the Georgia Register of Historic Places is our state's companion to the<br>
National Register of Historic Places. Modeled closely after the National Register, the Georgia<br>
Register is Georgia's official statewide list of historic properties worthy of being preserved. <br>
Properties listed in the National Register are automatically listed in the Georgia Register.<br>
<br>
Local Designations<br>
<br>
Another important way of determining the significance and preservation worthiness of properties<br>
in Georgia is through local landmark or historic district designation. Under the provisions of the<br>
Georgia Historic Preservation Act of 1980, local governments can pass historic preservation<br>
ordinances which specify procedures for designating historic properties in their jurisdictions. <br>
Local designation provides some level of protection for those properties. Designations may vary<br>
from community to community, reflecting local conditions, needs, goals, and prerogatives. At the<br>
present time, approximately 80 local governments in Georgia have enacted historic preservation<br>
ordinances and appointed preservation commissions.<br>
<br>
Planning<br>
<br>
Yet another way that local communities can define their historic properties is through local<br>
comprehensive plans. As required by the Georgia Planning Act of 1989, local comprehensive<br>
plans must include consideration of historic properties. While this consideration can vary widely<br>
from community to community, and while these plans do not have the force of local designations<br>
under a preservation ordinance, local comprehensive plans can provide an opportunity for<br>
communities to express an opinion about what is locally considered historic and worthy of being<br>
preserved. Other land use planning tools, including zoning ordinances, sign and tree ordinances,<br>
and others can be used to delineate and designate historic places. <br>
<br>
Historical Markers<br>
<br>
The state historical marker program, administered by the Department of Natural Resources, uses<br>
unique criteria and procedures to identify properties of statewide significance. The oldest of the<br>
many ways in which historic properties are identified in Georgia, the marker program dates back<br>
to the early 1950s. Through the marker program, former as well as extant historic properties are<br>
officially recognized. Currently there are nearly 2,000 state historical markers in Georgia. They<br>
are accompanied by uncounted numbers of local and regional historical markers.<br>
<br>
Exactly How Are Properties Determined to be Historic?<br>
<br>
Although there are several different ways of determining whether properties are historic, all of<br>
these processes share certain essential steps. These common steps constitute a fundamental<br>
historic preservation routine, or methodology. <br>
<br>
The first step consists of gathering information about a specific property --the facts, so to<br>
speak--including a physical description and historical documentation. <br>
<br>
The second step involves putting the individual property in its place in history, seeing how it &quot;fits&quot;<br>
into the larger scheme of things, historically speaking. Useful ways of doing this include<br>
comparing and contrasting it to similar properties, to historically related properties, or to other<br>
properties in the same vicinity (see Appendix B for more information). Another useful way is to<br>
determine how the property relates to the &quot;distinctive aspects&quot; of Georgia's history (see sidebar).<br>
<br>
The third step consists of applying criteria for evaluation to the property and what is known about<br>
it--a yardstick for measuring its significance--such as the National Register of Historic Places<br>
&quot;Criteria for Evaluation&quot; or the designation standards found in a local historic preservation<br>
ordinance. Each step of the process involves public input and participation along with appropriate<br>
professional involvement. Taken together, these three steps constitute the basic methodology for<br>
determining the significance of properties.<br>
<br>
Why Preserve Historic Properties?<br>
<br>
Above and beyond their historical significance, why are Georgia's historic properties valuable<br>
resources? Why should they be preserved? The answers are many, and varied.<br>
<br>
Historic properties are tangible evidence of our history. They bring history to life in ways that no<br>
written or even audio-visual materials can do. In doing so, they help us better understand who we<br>
are today, as individuals and as a people, and how things got to be the way they are.<br>
<br>
Historic properties also contribute to a sense of place. They make one place different from<br>
another and make each community unique. They reinforce the lessons of history while<br>
strengthening our identity. They provide a framework for new development; they add variety to<br>
our everyday surroundings.<br>
<br>
Historic properties also represent an enormous investment of time, money, energy, and<br>
materials--resources which, like all other nonrenewable resources, should be used wisely and<br>
conserved. Additionally, historic properties can continue in productive service in everyday life,<br>
either for the use for which they were originally intended, or adapted to new or upgraded uses.<br>
<br>
Historic properties enrich the quality of our lives by presenting for our benefit a variety of<br>
architectural styles, construction materials, and craftsmanship which appears nowhere else in our<br>
physical environment.<br>
<br>
And historic properties literally embody knowledge--about ourselves and our past, as well as<br>
themselves--which can be recovered for the benefit of all through careful archeological or<br>
architectural investigation and conservation.<br>
</p>
<p><a href="newvisio.htm">Table of Contents</a></p>
</body>

