<body>
<p>CHAPTER THREE<br>
<br>
<font size=5><strong>Georgia Now and in the Future</strong></font><br>
</p>
<hr>
<p><br>
As we approach the end of the twentieth century, historic preservation continues to become a<br>
more integral part of the social, economic, and political landscape in the nation as well as in<br>
Georgia. The preservation of historic properties has become one of many quality of life issues<br>
facing our state. Historic resources are affected by many kinds of development, societal and<br>
financial trends. In planning for preservation, it is essential to examine the major trends occurring<br>
in the state and in communities and how those trends affect Georgia's historic resources. <br>
Many Georgians are concerned about the proliferation of unplanned growth that is resulting in<br>
urban sprawl and unsightly development. They look to historic preservation as one method to<br>
help maintain viable communities and improve the quality of life.<br>
<br>
It is important to understand changes that are affecting the state as a whole so that preservation<br>
programs in Georgia can be designed to respond in the most effective manner. In this way,<br>
historic places will more likely help shape Georgia's future.<br>
<br>
Fast-Changing Population <br>
<br>
Statewide Trends<br>
<br>
Population change is transforming Georgia. The major population trends facing Georgia are the<br>
rapid growth taking place in the suburban areas of the state, especially within 100 miles of<br>
Atlanta, and the continued decrease within large cities and rural areas. These diverse directions<br>
in population affect economic activity, existing and planned infrastructure, governmental policies,<br>
and land use decisions, which in turn affect historic resources.<br>
<br>
Georgia is currently the tenth most populated--and one of the fastest growing--states in the<br>
nation, estimated in 1995 to have a population of almost 7.2 million. The 1980s was the first<br>
decade in history that Georgia experienced more population increase from net migration than<br>
from natural increase. Throughout the 1990s and into the new century, Georgia will continue to<br>
grow.<br>
<br>
The age makeup of Georgia is also changing. For the first time, Georgia is in the top ten<br>
nationally in states attracting new elderly residents. Between 1985 and 1990, 44,475 people<br>
sixty-five and older moved into Georgia and more retirees decided to leave Florida for Georgia<br>
than those who went the other way. Notwithstanding the growing elderly population, Georgia's<br>
population is young, with a median age of 31.8 years. The high population of young people can<br>
be directly attributed to the favorable job market created by Georgia's expanding economy. <br>
<br>
Georgia ranks fifth in African-American population nationally, with 1.8 million persons<br>
comprising 27% of the state's population. <br>
<br>
Between 1980 and 1990, 43 Georgia counties lost population, 77 grew at less than the state<br>
average, and 40 grew faster than the state average. By combining these population trends with<br>
urban and rural characteristics, the state can be subdivided into four major population areas. Four<br>
distinct &quot;Georgias&quot; emerge from this classification: suburban, urban, growing rural and declining<br>
rural counties.<br>
<br>
Suburban Georgia<br>
<br>
Riding the crest of population growth is the metropolitan Atlanta area, especially the suburban<br>
and exurban portions within 100 miles of the central city. More than 66% of the total population<br>
of Georgia lives in the Atlanta region. Georgia has three of the top ten fastest growing counties<br>
in the United States. Two of these, Henry and Paulding counties, lie within the metro Atlanta<br>
area. The population of the 14-county metro Atlanta region grew nearly 70% from 1970 to 1990,<br>
exceeding the state growth rate by 25%. During the same time period, Cobb and Gwinnett<br>
counties each increased by more than 250,000 residents, while Fayette County added 50,000 new<br>
residents, growing at an astonishing rate of 550%. Eight of the counties in the region grew at<br>
rates in excess of 200%.<br>
<br>
Urban Georgia<br>
<br>
The population of Georgia's cities as a percentage of the total state population is steadily<br>
decreasing. In 1960, 54% of the state's citizens lived in cities. In 1992, only 39% lived within<br>
city boundaries. Many Georgia cities are becoming a workplace for the middle class, but a home <br>
predominantly to the very wealthy or to minorities and the poor. Growth in the suburbs often<br>
comes at the expense of urbanized areas. Every major Georgia central city is experiencing a<br>
middle-class population decline. <br>
<br>
Rural Areas of Growth<br>
<br>
The rural growth areas of Georgia tend to be located in the northern portion of the state or along<br>
the coast. These counties either possess scenic beauty, and thus attract tourists and retirees, are<br>
located near a military base, or are regional economic centers.<br>
<br>
Rural Areas of Decline<br>
<br>
Rural areas declining in population face the most uncertain future. These areas, concentrated in<br>
the southern half of the state, are characterized by long-term population loss, lack of employment<br>
opportunities and continued high levels of outmigration of working age people, leaving behind a<br>
large number of young and older residents. <br>
<br>
Effects of Population Trends<br>
<br>
The effects of changing population on the historic resources of Georgia vary depending upon the<br>
area of the state. Areas of suburban growth create different concerns and opportunities for<br>
historic property than do areas of rural or urban decline.<br>
<br>
The rapid growth being experienced on the suburban fringe of metropolitan areas creates<br>
widespread change in the landscape and pressure on existing infrastructure and historic resources. <br>
Similar pressures exist in the rural growth areas of the north Georgia mountains and along the<br>
Atlantic coast. In areas of strip developments, residential subdivisions and suburban sprawl,<br>
infrastructure must expand to satisfy a growing population's need for clean water, sewers, roads,<br>
and utilities. These changes often come at the expense of open space, historic landscapes, historic<br>
buildings and archeological sites. <br>
<br>
Anticipating and reacting to rapid growth requires time, effort and planning. Only one-third of<br>
Georgia's 159 counties have enacted any kind of zoning ordinance, although this is slowly<br>
changing. The potential for uncontrolled sprawl is greatest when the local community has not<br>
planned for growth, and has no land use controls in place. In this case,developers often make<br>
more of the decisions about the future of a community than the residents or elected officials. <br>
Georgia has mandated that local governments must produce a comprehensive plan, including an<br>
existing and future land use map, under the Georgia Planning Act of 1989. A required<br>
component of these plans is a section on historic resources and how the community intends to<br>
incorporate these resources into future development.<br>
<br>
Comprehensive planning is a good first step for communities to think about what type of future<br>
they want. Often, however, the plans are not implemented and are not incorporated into local<br>
land use regulations. It is important for local governments to realize that planning is not in<br>
conflict with growth, but is a way to preserve those aspects of a community that are important to<br>
its quality of life, while guiding the growth that will occur. Comprehensive land use planning and<br>
regulation can be an effective tool to achieve growth management and historic preservation goals.<br>
<br>
One method by which planning can promote growth while maintaining a community's character<br>
and quality of life is through a concept called &quot;sustainability.&quot; This approach to community<br>
planning emphasizes long-term planning, rather than meeting only immediate needs, and the<br>
exploration of creative approaches to accomplish change. Sustainable development techniques<br>
include the acknowledgement that factors such as land use, environmental concerns, housing and<br>
transportation systems are overlapping issues that require an integrated strategy, not isolated<br>
solutions. The goal of sustainable development is to create communities of enduring value and<br>
long-term viability. A component of sustainable development is &quot;neo-traditional design,&quot; that is,<br>
using traditional (historic) development patterns in the creation of new urban and suburban<br>
communities. <br>
<br>
The growing interest in sustainable communities among both environmentalists and<br>
preservationists will provide opportunities for conservation and preservation organizations to<br>
work together more in the future. The rapid sprawl that characterizes Georgia's fast-paced<br>
growth adversely affects both natural and historic resources and may become the top issue for<br>
preservationists and conservationists as we approach the year 2000.<br>
<br>
The urban areas of Georgia face some of the same development pressures, especially on their<br>
edges, but they have a much higher concentration of historic resources within their central<br>
business districts and intown neighborhoods. Decaying and outdated infrastructure, underutilized<br>
buildings, vacant lots and a perception of crime and neglect are often seen as roadblocks to<br>
preservation. Here, the threats to historic resources often come from deferred maintenance,<br>
abandonment, disinvestment, or new development at any cost. The prosperity of the suburbs at<br>
the expense of the central city is a shortsighted approach to regional social and economic success. <br>
A strong central city and intown neighborhoods can serve as a solid foundation for sustained,<br>
long-term vitality. Historic preservation can be an effective tool to facilitate the revitalization of<br>
our urban areas. <br>
<br>
Housing rehabilitation programs can provide affordable homes to inner-city residents. <br>
Preservation can also lure middle income residents back into the city. The residential rebirth of<br>
cities is the single most important factor in their revitalization. Facade rehabilitation programs can<br>
act as an incentive for owners of commercial property to improve their buildings, and can work in<br>
conjunction with the federal Investment Tax Credit to provide a stimulus for the revitalization of<br>
commercial areas. <br>
<br>
Rural areas experiencing population decline are perhaps at greatest risk. With little economic<br>
activity, the historic resources in these smaller communities face neglect, high vacancy rates and<br>
abandonment. If any interest is shown in these buildings, it is often for their salvage potential, or<br>
for relocation. In addition, archeological sites in rural areas are threatened by looters, taking<br>
advantage of the growing market for artifacts.<br>
<br>
With a declining population and few employment opportunities for residents in these rural areas,<br>
job creation is a major priority. Many rural communities in Georgia have used historic<br>
preservation as a basis for community and economic revitalization. Using the Main Street<br>
approach of using the existing downtown infrastructure and historic building stock, these<br>
communities have brought businesses, promotions, residents and a sense of community pride back<br>
to declining business districts.<br>
<br>
Historic buildings are sometimes erroneously associated with a community's decline while new<br>
buildings seem to symbolize economic revitalization. The underpinning for any efforts to use<br>
historic preservation is education. Residents need to be made aware that historic resources are<br>
what helps to make their community a special place. They need to know what makes these<br>
buildings, sites and places historically significant, worthy of preservation, and important for the<br>
community's future. <br>
<br>
The large percentage of black Georgians will have an increasing impact on preservation. Interest<br>
in the historic African-American resources of Georgia is increasing at the same time those<br>
resources are rapidly disappearing. More information about the importance of black history and<br>
the places associated with it needs to be made available to a widespread audience. Awareness of<br>
the importance of historic preservation and support for it statewide by the African-American<br>
community will be a significant factor in the ultimate success of preservation in Georgia.<br>
<br>
Housing Trends<br>
<br>
According to 1990 census data, Georgia contains 2.6 million total housing units. Of this total,<br>
10.3% or 271,000 units are vacant. It is estimated that almost 382,000 units or 14.3% of the total<br>
were constructed before 1950.<br>
<br>
The number of persons per household has declined in Georgia by almost 52%, from 4.4 persons in<br>
1930, to 2.6 in 1990. Although household size has decreased, the number of households has<br>
increased dramatically. The population grew by 18.6% in the 1980s, but the number of<br>
households grew by 26.4%. Of all households, 54% contain either one or two persons, and only<br>
10% contain five or more persons.<br>
<br>
Homelessness, housing for people with special needs, and affordability of housing are problems<br>
the state and communities will continue to confront. Historic resources can play a larger role in<br>
providing solutions. Historic hotels and warehouses are being converted to Single Room<br>
Occupancy housing or halfway houses for the homeless, people with AIDS, and the elderly. <br>
Intown historic neighborhoods offer the best chance for creating affordable neighborhoods<br>
through rehabilitation. <br>
<br>
The retention or increase of middle and upper income residents in the central or intown<br>
neighborhoods in order to create viable communities is a growing issue in Georgia's cities. <br>
Recycling of intown historic neighborhoods contributes to downtown revitalization -- by creating<br>
24-hour downtowns -- and to sustainable development for more viable downtowns and intown<br>
neighborhoods.<br>
<br>
Effects of Housing Trends<br>
<br>
The creation of additional housing units increases pressure on the state's historic resources<br>
through the demolition of historic buildings and the destruction of archeological sites. Yet<br>
historic buildings offer exceptional opportunities for creative solutions to many of Georgia's<br>
housing needs.<br>
<br>
Economic Trends<br>
<br>
Economic activity in Georgia has rebounded since the recession of the early 1990s. More new<br>
jobs have been created in Georgia over the past four years than in all but two other states. In<br>
1994, one out of every nine jobs created in the nation was created in Georgia and the 1990 per<br>
capita income of the state was 91% of the national average, up 6% from 1980. In 1994 alone,<br>
132 new manufacturing plants were announced in Georgia, representing a 176% increase in the<br>
value of such investments over 1993. Even without Olympic related construction, which has<br>
accounted for much of the activity, Georgia has enjoyed significant economic growth over the last<br>
ten years. <br>
<br>
From 1984 to 1990, Georgia's total personal income increased by 60.9%, while the national<br>
average grew by only 50.4%. Two factors are primarily responsible for this increase. First, the<br>
growth is related to large numbers of well educated, new residents with high incomes. Second,<br>
Georgia enjoys a diversified economy comprised of manufacturing, agribusiness, the defense<br>
industry, services and tourism. This diversity has enabled the state to weather economic<br>
recessions better than other areas of the country. In the future, Georgia will continue changing<br>
from a manufacturing and natural resource based economy to an information and service-retail<br>
driven one that will require a better educated and highly skilled work force. <br>
<br>
Agriculture<br>
<br>
Agriculture remains the number one economic activity in Georgia. The forestry and timber<br>
industry is the leading agricultural activity, but there has been a significant and long-term decline<br>
both in the total number of farms and in the proportion of the state's land in farms over the last 40<br>
years. The total number of farms has decreased steadily from about 200,000 in 1950 to just over<br>
40,000 in 1992. Likewise, the proportion of the state in farmland has gone from almost 70% in<br>
1950 to 27% in 1992. Through mechanization and higher yields per acre, fewer farmers can<br>
produce more. Land has become valuable in growth areas for residential and commercial<br>
development, tempting farmers to sell their land.<br>
<br>
Effects of Economic Trends<br>
<br>
The effects of economic trends on historic resources closely parallel those of population. With<br>
strong economies in north Georgia, portions of the mountains and along the coast, development<br>
threatens the preservation of historic places. Development changes the landscape in profound and<br>
permanent ways. Construction of new roads, utilities, infrastructure and buildings results in loss<br>
of open space, historic structures, and archeological sites which are gone forever. Creative<br>
planning efforts need to be undertaken to allow for sustainable growth, while at the same time<br>
integrating existing historic and cultural resources. <br>
<br>
The vibrant economy of north Georgia and the coast also presents an opportunity for the<br>
preservation of historic areas. New businesses can be located in historic commercial districts,<br>
unused mill complexes or historic school buildings no longer needed for education. Declining<br>
inner-city neighborhoods can be revitalized with new residents living in historic homes or<br>
compatible infill construction. Developers need to be made aware of the advantages of using<br>
historic buildings for their projects. Information about the cost/benefit ratio of rehabilitating<br>
historic buildings, the available tax benefits, and positive economic effects of preservation on a<br>
community need to be communicated to decision makers and developers.<br>
<br>
The rehabilitation of historic structures is competitive with the cost of comparable new<br>
construction, especially when the available incentives are used for preservation, and when the full<br>
costs of demolition, land development and infrastructure are included in the cost of new<br>
construction. A new building will often be a structure of much lower quality and have a shorter<br>
life expectancy than a rehabilitated historic building. High quality new construction, comparable<br>
to the historic building, will generally cost more. Too often, the cost of rehabilitation is compared<br>
to new construction costs merely on a per-square-foot basis. Such an approach is misleading<br>
because it fails to factor in the savings offered by rehabilitation since demolition, infrastructure<br>
and land preparation costs are often not required for preservation.<br>
<br>
Within the urban core of Georgia's major cities, and in declining rural areas, historic resources are<br>
not threatened with development, but with disinvestment. Underused commercial storefronts,<br>
unused upper floors of downtown buildings, and declining residential neighborhoods are threats to<br>
the future of historic resources of these communities. The utilization of existing infrastructure<br>
and buildings in these areas can be a less costly use of available economic development capital<br>
than the more expensive process of land acquisition, demolition, new construction and the<br>
extension of costly infrastructure and services. Use of existing structures by the private sector<br>
and government can help bring economic vitality back to depressed inner cities and rural<br>
communities.<br>
<br>
Governmental Change<br>
<br>
Since the passage of the National Historic Preservation Act of 1966, the federal government has<br>
provided support for preservation through educational programs, technical assistance, tax<br>
incentives and funding. This support has been critical to preservation efforts throughout Georgia. <br>
Since 1980, however, the financial support received in Georgia from federal sources has been<br>
tenuous. Given the current political climate at the federal level, the trend of uncertain and<br>
probably declining federal appropriations is expected to continue. State government has helped to<br>
respond to the fast growing interest in preservation and the need for technical and financial<br>
assistance in an environment of diminishing federal support. However, state government is also<br>
undergoing cuts, privatization and reorganization. How such change will affect preservation<br>
programs and funding is unclear.<br>
<br>
The major trend in government at all levels is a public perception that there is too much<br>
government, that government is too intrusive. All government activities are coming under<br>
increased scrutiny. The government's role in historic preservation will be questioned.<br>
<br>
Federal Government Influence<br>
<br>
Although its financial support is decreasing, the federal government maintains support for historic<br>
preservation in several ways. Through the investment tax credit and the low-income tax credit<br>
programs, the Internal Revenue Service allows investors to receive a tax credit on the<br>
rehabilitation of historic commercial property and the creation of low-income housing. The<br>
National Park Service provides appropriations for state preservation programs, administers the<br>
National Register of Historic Places, and distributes technical information about preservation<br>
issues. Congress has recently created a National Center for Preservation Technology and<br>
Training to assist in that effort. <br>
<br>
The Department of Housing and Urban Development, through its Community Development<br>
Block Grant, HOME and HOPE programs, provides millions of dollars in funding to Georgia that<br>
can be used for the rehabilitation of substandard historic housing units. The Federal Highway<br>
Administration, through the Intermodal Surface Transportation Efficiency Act of 1991 (ISTEA),<br>
has allowed federal transportation dollars to be used by the Georgia Department of<br>
Transportation for transportation enhancements that can include the acquisition and rehabilitation<br>
of historic properties and the enhancement of historic sites and districts. <br>
<br>
The Department of Defense has instituted the Legacy Program, designed to preserve historic<br>
resources located on military bases. The U.S.D.A. Forest Service has actively surveyed, managed<br>
and interpreted the extensive array of historic and archeological resources on its lands in Georgia<br>
for twenty years. The Advisory Council on Historic Preservation continues to work with all<br>
federal agencies to insure that they meet their responsibilities under Section 106 of the National<br>
Historic Preservation Act to take historic resources into account in their programs and activities.<br>
<br>
Effects of Federal Involvement<br>
<br>
These programs represent a broadening, if not deepening commitment on behalf of the federal<br>
government, to create effective and meaningful stewardship of federally-owned historic property,<br>
as well as conscientious use of federal funds that affect historic resources. <br>
<br>
State Government Influence<br>
<br>
State government support for historic preservation has increased as federal support has<br>
declined. In July 1994, Governor Zell Miller elevated the Historic Preservation Section to<br>
Division status within the Department of Natural Resources. Along with this rise in position in<br>
state government, the Governor recommended and the General Assembly enacted the Heritage<br>
2000 grant program. $270,000 was made available in the form of grants in state fiscal year (SFY)<br>
1996. These grants are designed to provide funds to Georgia communities to rehabilitate their<br>
historic properties. <br>
<br>
State funding continues to support the Regional Historic Preservation Planning Program within 13<br>
of the state's 17 Regional Development Centers, with an allocation of $243,000 for SFY 1996. <br>
An annual $25,000 allocation is provided to the Division for inventory of historic resources. In<br>
addition, State monies are used to support the Georgia Main Street Program, housed in the<br>
Department of Industry, Trade and Tourism. State funds also allow the Historic Preservation<br>
Division to contract with the Georgia Trust for Historic Preservation to carry out the Main Street<br>
Design Assistance Program throughout Georgia. The University of Georgia also receives an<br>
allocation through HPD to provide preservation assistance to local governments through the<br>
Office of Preservation Services. In 1993, the Historic Preservation Division completed a<br>
inventory of all State-owned historic resources as a precursor to future development of a<br>
comprehensive State-owned historic building stewardship program.<br>
<br>
The Department of Community Affairs (DCA) has also assisted communities with numerous<br>
preservation projects through its Local Development Fund, the administration of the Community<br>
Development Block Grant program to non-entitlement communities, and special appropriations.<br>
<br>
In 1989, the General Assembly passed legislation to create an ad valorem tax freeze for owners<br>
rehabilitating historic residential and commercial property. Also in 1989, the State passed the<br>
Georgia Planning Act, mandating that all Georgia communities prepare a comprehensive plan,<br>
including a section acknowledging and planning for the future of historic resources. <br>
<br>
Additional legislation passed by the General Assembly includes the Georgia Environmental Policy<br>
Act of 1991 (GEPA), requiring that historic resources be taken into account for State funded<br>
projects. In 1995, Georgia passed legislation to allow for Judicial In Rem Tax Foreclosure,<br>
facilitating the process by which local governments and nonprofit entities can take tax delinquent<br>
property and make it available for affordable housing and neighborhood redevelopment.<br>
<br>
The Georgia Civil War Commission and the Georgia State Capitol Commission were created by<br>
the General Assembly in 1993, to oversee and promote the preservation of these important and<br>
unique historic resources. In 1995, the Legislature created by resolution the Georgia Future<br>
Communities Commission to examine and make recommendations concerning the governmental,<br>
social, and economic issues confronting local governments.<br>
<br>
Effects of State Involvement<br>
<br>
State initiatives are creating a heightened awareness of the importance of historic resources and<br>
the active preservation of them. New State preservation commissions will generate increased<br>
attention to certain historic resources, as well as a need for close coordination among preservation<br>
partners. Downsizing of government, however, will cause all State agencies, including the<br>
Historic Preservation Division, to re-evaluate priorities and provide services in new ways.<br>
<br>
Transportation Trends<br>
<br>
Georgia is a state that is highly dependent upon its system of interstate highways, expressways,<br>
arterials and collector roads. The Georgia Department of Transportation has aggressively<br>
invested in construction of new roads and bridges, maintenance, rehabilitation and restoration<br>
programs. The road network includes 110,000 miles of public roads, with 18,000 miles classified<br>
as a part of the State Highway System. With the construction of new highways and the expansion<br>
of existing ones, the growth of the state transportation system will have a significant effect on the<br>
historic resources of Georgia.<br>
<br>
Intermodal Surface Transportation Efficiency Act<br>
<br>
The passage of the Intermodal Surface Transportation Efficiency Act (ISTEA) by Congress in<br>
1991 signaled the end of the Interstate era and the beginning of a new approach to transportation<br>
programs. ISTEA set out a new national transportation policy, shifting program emphasis from a<br>
single focus of building highways and bridges, to the creation and management of an integrated,<br>
multimodal transportation network. <br>
<br>
Implementation of this new policy and the eligibility for federal funding is based on compliance<br>
with new planning requirements that include public involvement and an emphasis on local needs to<br>
formulate a Statewide Transportation Improvement Program (STIP, a three-year action plan) and<br>
the Statewide Transportation Plan (a twenty-year policy document identifying projects for the<br>
STIP). In response to these requirements the Georgia Department of Transportation (GDOT)<br>
created the Transportation 2000 Commission, a broad coalition of interested parties, which<br>
developed a new statewide transportation plan. In surveys conducted as part of the Commission's<br>
planning process, 97% of those polled agreed that public involvement in transportation program<br>
decisions should be a continuous process and 83% felt that we must resolve or prevent the<br>
harmful effects of transportation on the natural and built environment. <br>
<br>
The new federal transportation act is having several effects on the preservation of Georgia's<br>
historic resources. The flexible funding provisions of ISTEA allow states to spend money not<br>
only on highways, but on mass transit and commuter rail systems. The Act also requires Georgia<br>
to spend at least 10% of its allocated surface transportation funds on enhancement activities<br>
which can include acquisition and rehabilitation of historic property, preservation and alternative<br>
use of abandoned railway corridors, and acquisition of easements on scenic areas or historic sites. <br>
State transportation plans must include other public policy concerns, and allow for flexible design<br>
standards for projects that affect areas of historic or scenic value.<br>
<br>
Roads and Bridges <br>
<br>
The expansion and maintenance of Georgia's system of highways and bridges continues to be the<br>
single most important element of Georgia's intermodal transportation system. The Georgia DOT's<br>
Developmental Highway System results in the widening of two-lane rural routes to four lanes and<br>
the continuation of these routes into and through many small communities. The proposed Outer<br>
Perimeter around Atlanta would affect fully one-fourth of the state through impacts to traffic, land<br>
use, air and water quality, and community economies. These &quot;improvements&quot; may encourage<br>
sprawl and occur at the expense of archeological resources, rural historic resources, historic<br>
bridges, downtown buildings or the loss of the small town, pedestrian character of communities in<br>
their path. On the other hand, improved roads sometimes allow the communities affected to<br>
recruit new industrial and commercial development and assist tourists and other motorists to more<br>
easily visit their shops and historic places. <br>
<br>
Approximately 1300 bridges still in operation on the public road system in Georgia were built<br>
prior to 1940. Many of the bridges considered eligible for the National Register of Historic<br>
Places have been determined &quot;functionally obsolete,&quot; not meeting current design and safety<br>
standards. These bridges require widening or reconstruction which can result in loss of historic<br>
character.<br>
<br>
It is important that as part of the ISTEA planning process and Section 106 review, communities<br>
make their concerns and objectives known, insuring that the designs for new or widened roads<br>
and replacement bridges take into account issues of historic resources and quality of life.<br>
<br>
Intermodal Transportation<br>
<br>
Public transportation is currently available to nearly 4 million Georgians (67% of the population),<br>
but the majority of use is concentrated in the urban and suburban areas. Survey results from the<br>
Transportation 2000 process show that 75% of those questioned would like to see improvements<br>
in the state's public transit systems. The further development of a statewide intermodal public<br>
transportation system including commuter rail, buses, and rail passenger service can minimize<br>
environmental concerns, reduce sprawl, and serve as an economic development tool. This<br>
approach could reduce the adverse impact of roads on historic resources as well as improve<br>
access to historic communities. <br>
<br>
Railroads<br>
<br>
According to the Georgia Transportation 2000 Commission, people throughout the state<br>
expressed overwhelming support for all types of rail improvements. Results of the GDOT survey<br>
indicate that 81% questioned would like to see improvements to passenger and commuter rail<br>
facilities and over 80% would be willing to pay increased fees, tolls or fares to support the cost of<br>
such improvements. <br>
Rail corridor preservation is another element of the rail improvement program. Preservation of<br>
abandoned rail corridors is critical to protect the rights of way, bridges and depots for future<br>
transportation use, and in the short term they can be utilized for walking paths, bike trails or<br>
greenways. Most of Georgia's rail corridors are historic as significant engineered structures. <br>
Many rail corridors include other historic buildings and structures, such as depots and water<br>
towers. The value of rail corridor protection is especially important in urban areas where the<br>
pressure to develop these areas is most acute. As rail lines continue to be abandoned by the<br>
railroads, and commuter rail perhaps becomes a reality in Georgia, more attention needs to be<br>
paid by the railroads to the preservation of these significant historic resources. <br>
<br>
Airports and Port Facilities<br>
<br>
As Georgia grows, the need for new or expanded ports and airports will also grow. The<br>
construction of new airports and port facilities and expansion of existing ones can have an adverse<br>
effect on historic resources. Construction can affect historic buildings and archeological sites in<br>
the impacted area. Dredging for port access along the coast can destroy underwater archeological<br>
resources or alter currents, leading to coastal erosion. The creation of new airport facilities can<br>
create increased noise and air pollution and an increase in local traffic. When planning these types<br>
of facilities, it is important to look at the possible effects on historic resources early in the<br>
planning process in order to minimize or mitigate them. <br>
<br>
Transportation 2000 Goals<br>
<br>
The goals that emerged from the Transportation 2000 process provide a clear indication of the<br>
attitudes of Georgians toward transportation and historic preservation. These goals include:<br>
preserving the unique character of Georgia's developing small cities and rural areas; supporting a<br>
demonstration program that integrates transportation planning into the community planning<br>
process; providing transportation design that is integrated with architectural and planning design;<br>
providing for the rehabilitation and adaptive use of existing historic buildings and structures; and<br>
encouraging community planning that recognizes the uniqueness and diversity of Georgia's cities<br>
and neighborhoods. <br>
<br>
Effects of Transportation Trends<br>
<br>
Evolving public attitudes, new federal legislation, the development of comprehensive plans in<br>
accordance with the Georgia Planning Act, increasing interest in preservation of historic places<br>
and community character, and increasing public participation in transportation policy will<br>
eventually bring about change in the planning and design of Georgia's transportation system.<br>
<br>
Tourism Trends<br>
<br>
Tourism in Georgia is very big business. After agriculture, tourism ranks as the second largest<br>
industry in the state. The Georgia Department of Industry, Trade and Tourism estimates that in<br>
1994, 39.47 million visitors came to Georgia, spending $12.3 billion, a 25% increase in tourist<br>
expenditures since 1989. The resultant impact of this wave of tourism is 387,659 jobs statewide, <br>
$1.13 billion in State government revenue and $658 million in revenue to local governments. <br>
Much of this tourist activity takes place in Georgia's historic downtowns, at historic sites, or in<br>
historic rural areas, bringing both the opportunity to educate visitors about our historic resources,<br>
and to raise concern over the continued welfare of these resources.<br>
<br>
With the Olympic Games in Atlanta in the summer of 1996, the city and state will be propelled<br>
onto the international stage, with residual effects that could last for years to come. The last<br>
Olympic city, Barcelona, experienced a 43% increase in tourism the year after the games. The<br>
exposure of the Olympics will help to illustrate the diversity of Georgia. The promotion of and<br>
visitation to historic districts and sites will play a major role in visitors' experience of the state. <br>
<br>
Tourism studies show that the profile of the typical tourist is changing. People today take several<br>
short vacations and weekend trips rather than one long vacation each year. They tend to visit<br>
places closer to home. Growing segments of the tourism market are retired people and<br>
professionals with considerable disposable incomes. The African-American tourism market is also<br>
growing rapidly in Georgia.<br>
<br>
Travelers are becoming more interested in looking for experiences off the interstate highways,<br>
traveling on two and four lane secondary roads. Taking advantage of this interest, communities<br>
have worked together to promote a critical mass of attractions such as the Antebellum Trail<br>
through central Georgia. By marketing historic districts, house museums, and landscapes, along<br>
with other attractions, communities can enhance their appeal to tourists. For this to happen,<br>
however, the historic resources must exist, be in good physical shape, be accessible to the public,<br>
and be interpreted accurately. <br>
<br>
For an effective statewide heritage tourism strategy, Georgia must develop better regional and<br>
state heritage tourism marketing strategies, and also improve its &quot;resource base&quot; (i.e. buildings,<br>
sites, etc.). There must be something there and worthwhile for tourism professionals to market. <br>
<br>
Historic properties already play a large role in the tourism economies of Savannah, Atlanta,<br>
coastal Georgia, Macon, Augusta, Columbus and the Georgia mountains. In addition, many<br>
smaller communities in Georgia are capitalizing on their historic appeal and Main Street affiliation,<br>
providing a quality experience for the traveler. <br>
<br>
There has recently been an increase in visitation of sites important to African-American history. <br>
Communities such as Savannah, Augusta, Macon and Atlanta have created walking and driving<br>
tours of historic African-American sites, helping to interpret this important aspect of Georgia's<br>
history. American Indian sites, such as New Echota and Etowah Mounds, continue to attract<br>
tourists. The Department of Natural Resources has taken the lead in managing and interpreting<br>
these sites as part of the state parks and historic sites system.<br>
<br>
Other popular tourist destinations in Georgia are the state's Civil War battlefields and sites. The<br>
National Park Service manages several of these sites such as Andersonville National Historic Site,<br>
Chickamauga National Military Park and Kennesaw Mountain National Battlefield Park. State<br>
and local governments in Georgia are active in preserving, protecting and marketing some lesser<br>
known Civil War sites. Bringing the tourism potential of these sites to fruition can have a<br>
significant effect on local economies. The challenge is to be able to capitalize on these resources,<br>
while at the same time preserving and protecting the sites, vistas and open space that accurately<br>
convey the historic experience.<br>
<br>
Effects of Tourism Trends<br>
<br>
The preservation and promotion of historic sites, &quot;heritage tourism,&quot; is a major component of<br>
tourism activity in Georgia. Up to 38% of visitors surveyed at Georgia Welcome Centers planned<br>
to visit historic or cultural sites during their stay. This percentage would grow significantly if<br>
Georgia were marketed more aggressively as a place to experience history. Currently, only a few<br>
areas are marketed that way, and heritage tourism is a much larger part of those areas' tourism<br>
industry. The popularity of heritage tourism can have a positive effect on the preservation of<br>
historic districts and sites by bringing economic benefits to their communities. In addition, the<br>
attention can raise awareness among local citizens to the importance of the long-term preservation<br>
of their historic resources. <br>
<br>
On the other hand, heavy visitation to a historic site can result in deterioration if not carefully<br>
managed. Wear and tear, parking, insensitive adjacent development and inappropriate<br>
maintenance and repair can have detrimental effects on the integrity of historic property. As<br>
heritage tourism grows, it will become increasingly important for managers of historic sites and<br>
areas to be educated in the appropriate preservation techniques and methods necessary to<br>
maintain, interpret and protect these fragile resources. <br>
<br>
Historic Preservation Trends<br>
<br>
Historic preservation as a profession has broadened its scope in recent years and become more<br>
accepted as a discipline. This has led to the acceptance of professional and technical standards as<br>
well as the use of more sophisticated tools to accomplish preservation goals. <br>
<br>
Education<br>
<br>
Four universities and colleges in Georgia currently offer advanced degree programs in the<br>
preservation field. Historic preservation degrees are offered by Armstrong State College,<br>
Georgia State University, The Savannah College of Art and Design, and the University of<br>
Georgia. Formal training in the documentation, evaluation and protection of historic places can<br>
only increase the effectiveness of preservation programs and projects. Graduates of these<br>
educational programs have helped to raise the level of professional expertise in preservation and<br>
have brought an awareness of the preservation ethic to other fields such as architecture, landscape<br>
architecture, planning, archeology, anthropology, law, and real estate development. More<br>
information about preservation needs to be provided to students pursuing degrees in these and<br>
other fields.<br>
<br>
Even with the commitment by the higher education institutions in the state to the preservation<br>
field, much more education and training needs to be done. Public officials, especially local and<br>
State representatives need to be better informed about the benefits of historic preservation to their<br>
communities and the state. Workshops explaining historic preservation and its potential benefits<br>
need to be made available to developers, planners, government leaders, architects, and other<br>
professionals affecting historic resources. Owners of historic buildings and archeological sites<br>
need to be educated as to the importance of these places and the appropriate techniques to insure<br>
their preservation. <br>
<br>
Most importantly, historic preservation needs to be taught on a widespread basis to school<br>
children throughout the state. Heritage education should include an awareness of historic<br>
buildings, districts and archeological sites as a tangible link to the history of the community, state<br>
and nation. The Georgia Trust for Historic Preservation has sought to assist K through 12<br>
teachers in making better use of their community's historic and cultural resources as a regular part<br>
of the school curriculum. <br>
<br>
Those individuals involved directly in preservation projects such as contractors, craftspeople,<br>
architects and designers need to know not only the skills of their profession, but the overall goals<br>
of a restoration or rehabilitation project and to understand more about the philosophy that<br>
underlies decisions. <br>
<br>
Information about current preservation techniques, materials and methods need to be available to<br>
those individuals making decisions about and directly affecting historic property. <br>
<br>
Technology<br>
<br>
Recent technological advances have also made archeological investigation less expensive and<br>
more accurate. Remote sensing devices have dropped in price and become more powerful,<br>
allowing investigators to locate and map sites without ground disturbance. Unfortunately, the<br>
widespread availability of this type of sophisticated equipment allows looters to locate and<br>
damage these sites as well. Computer-Aided Design (CAD) is also being used much more<br>
frequently to assist with rehabilitation decisions for historic buildings and districts.<br>
<br>
The use of sophisticated mapping techniques such as Geographic Information Systems and Global<br>
Positioning Systems is assisting preservationists with architectural and archeological surveys. <br>
This helps local planning agencies take historic sites into consideration when making land use<br>
decisions. GIS is perhaps the single most important technological improvement revolutionizing<br>
how survey data is stored, manipulated, and made available to others. GIS can speed up decision<br>
making, especially in planning and in Section 106 review, more than any other program<br>
improvement. Historic resource data is, unfortunately, not yet available in GIS format in Georgia<br>
except in a few regional or local planning agencies. <br>
<br>
Current technology can also be used as an effective means of public education. Videotapes and<br>
interactive video conferencing can be low-cost alternatives to visiting individuals and communities<br>
in a state as large and diverse as Georgia. Use of the Internet, the Worldwide Web, image<br>
processing, and other relatively new technologies is just beginning to be used in the preservation<br>
field, but will certainly increase and revolutionize how preservation communication, training and<br>
assistance is done.<br>
<br>
Computer technology is being increasingly used as an information management tool for historic<br>
resource survey data, as well as tracking programs and review projects within state and federal<br>
offices. <br>
<br>
Partnerships<br>
<br>
For preservation to be most effective, there must be a link between the private, public and<br>
nonprofit sectors working toward common preservation goals. Groups such as local historical<br>
societies, museums and preservation commissions need to work closely with the Historic<br>
Preservation Division, the university preservation programs, and statewide organizations like the<br>
Georgia Trust for Historic Preservation, and on the national level with the National Park Service<br>
and the National Trust for Historic Preservation. In addition, these organizations need to find<br>
common ground with organizations that advocate similar goals such as the Trust for Public Land,<br>
the Georgia Conservancy, the Georgia Municipal Association, the Society for Georgia<br>
Archeology, and others.<br>
<br>
Preservationists need to continue to bring their message to nontraditional forums that affect<br>
historic resources. Bankers, state and local officials and planners, educators, realtors and<br>
developers should continue to be informed about the uses and benefits of historic preservation.<br>
<br>
Conclusions<br>
<br>
Georgia is evolving into a very different place than it was fifty, or even twenty, years ago. <br>
Preservation will be more difficult in the future in the face of such change. Yet Georgians will<br>
become more ardent supporters of preservation as a means of retaining the best of our past as we<br>
shape a new future.<br>
<br>
With the rapid increase in population in some areas of the state, preservationists need to<br>
emphasize the education of new residents as well as decision makers to the economic benefits of<br>
preservation and to its use as an effective tool for growth management.<br>
<br>
In areas of little growth, information needs to be distributed that explains how historic resources<br>
can help stimulate economic development through the use of existing infrastructure, downtown<br>
revitalization and the potential for tourism. <br>
<br>
Preservation will be enhanced by the use of new technologies. Computer technology can<br>
accelerate the documentation, identification and location of historic resources, as well as<br>
information management. Public awareness of historic preservation and heritage education can be<br>
enhanced by using new methods of interactive communication.<br>
<br>
<br>
With improved and greater amounts of information about the significance and location of historic<br>
resources, communities can be better informed and take historic places into account when<br>
planning for future growth and land use. New and better development models need to be created<br>
for communities, which emphasize sustainability and reuse of existing historic resources and<br>
infrastructure. Preservation is an important tool that can help citizens and agencies identify and<br>
preserve those aspects of their communities important to their quality of life.<br>
<br>
Preservationists, whether working on the local, regional, state or national level cannot succeed<br>
without assistance from diverse groups and individuals with similar, interconnected goals. <br>
Establishing partnerships and relationships with like-minded organizations will strengthen the<br>
effectiveness of historic preservation, increase its constituency, and continue to solidify its<br>
widespread use and acceptance. <br>
<br>
</p>
<p><a href="newvisio.htm">Table of Contents</a></p>
</body>

