<body>
<p>CHAPTER FOUR </p>
<p><font size=5><strong>Historic Preservation and How It Works</strong></font> </p>
<hr>
<p>Historic preservation is the process of identifying places, sites and resources that have survived from our past; evaluating the 
meaning and value they have for us now; and keeping, using and caring for those significant places, sites and resources so they 
will survive into the future. The preamble of the National Historic Preservation Act, passed by Congress in 1966, best 
expresses the value of historic preservation: &quot;The spirit and direction of the nation are founded upon and reflected in its historic 
heritage; the historical and cultural foundations of the nation should be preserved as a living part of our community life and 
development in order to give a sense of orientation to the American people.&quot; </p>
<p>The preservation process is accomplished in a variety of ways. It may involve survey, evaluation and designation, legal 
protection, planning, archeological research and investigation, rehabilitation, interpretation, acquisition and/or adaptive reuse. </p>
<p>There is a growing desire to preserve Georgia's heritage and historic places as the state continues to change. The preservation 
constituency includes historic property owners and activists, planners and developers, elected officials and professionals, 
African-Americans and American Indians, archeologists and architects, Civil War enthusiasts and Civil Rights activists, 
non-profit organizations and government agencies, academic institutions, environmentalists and downtown business owners, 
farmers and suburban dwellers, open space advocates and economic development specialists, children in classrooms and 
graduate students, the poor in need of housing and museum curators interpreting our history. They support historic 
preservation for different reasons; they see its value from different perspectives. Yet they are all preservationists. </p>
<p>Preservation is no longer just one thing, it is an ever-widening sphere of influence. It includes tourism, economic development, 
open space protection, heritage education, rehabilitation of historic buildings, community conservation, affordable housing, 
neotraditional planning, sustainable development, downtown revitalization, cultural celebration, archeology, design and 
craftsmanship. The challenge for the Historic Preservation Division is to meet the needs and provide services to a diverse 
constituency at a time when the demand for preservation is growing, historic places are disappearing, and the resources to 
meet demands are shrinking. The answer to this challenge lies in strategic planning and forming new partnerships. In the new 
century, preservation will be done by non-preservationists who incorporate the protection and use of historic resources into 
their own goals and activities. </p>
<p>Georgia boasts a strong and well-organized historic preservation network. Preservation of historic places began at the local 
level and continues to occur primarily at the local level through the commitment and actions of local people and organizations. 
Support, training, technical assistance, funding and direction are provided at the state level, with reliance on the federal 
infrastructure of laws, guidelines, criteria and funding. The decision to preserve historic resources is usually made at the local 
level, either by property owners, preservation activists, local organizations, or local government. People at the local level then 
call on statewide agencies, universities, or organizations for help, or they use funds, incentives, or programs offered at the state 
level. Projects are carried out according to federal standards, often using federal dollars or incentives, or relying on federal 
laws and regulations. </p>
<p>Partnerships between different groups --each with unique abilities and resources--have been at the foundation of the 
preservation movement. Such partnerships will be even more important as we move toward the new century. It will not be 
possible for one organization, one level of government, or one group of people to fully represent all of the increasingly 
complex interests in preservation. Each group and organization will find it possible to accomplish their own preservation goals 
only by working in partnership with others. </p>
<p>Preservation at the Local Level </p>
<p>Historic preservation at the local level takes many forms. It ranges from individual preservation of a local landmark, such as a 
county courthouse, to the revitalization of a historic neighborhood or downtown. It could take the form of a preservation 
component in a comprehensive plan or the passage by city council of a historic preservation ordinance and the appointment of 
a preservation commission. All these activities are initiated within the local community, but can be encouraged and assisted by 
regional and state organizations. </p>
<p>Local Historic Preservation Planning </p>
<p>With the passage of the Georgia Planning Act of 1989, communities all over the state have had the opportunity to examine 
where they are, evaluate what they have, and determine where they want to go. The identification and evaluation of historic 
resources is a required component of this planning process. By integrating historic preservation into the overall comprehensive 
planning process, local governments are being asked to consider the relationship between preservation and other aspects of 
community life. Historic preservation should be considered as communities plan for economic development, determine future 
land use, formulate a housing strategy or plan transportation improvements. </p>
<p>The basis of any preservation planning process should be an inventory and evaluation of existing historic resources (see 
Appendix A). From information gathered from comprehensive plans submitted for State review from around Georgia, it is 
evident that some communities do not have adequate inventories on which to base their evaluation. Although a &quot;windshield 
survey&quot; may be a helpful first step in gaining a broad, general impression of what and where a community's historic resources 
are, a detailed survey is needed for serious planning and preservation efforts. The Historic Preservation Division provides 
funding for comprehensive, standardized surveys. Unfortunately, since 1988 only about 24% of the state has been surveyed 
using this program due to the small amount of funds available. A recent analysis of comprehensive plans concluded that almost 
40% do not contain an adequate inventory of existing historic resources. Without a good inventory as a basis for evaluation it 
is difficult for communities to arrive at meaningful goals and implementation strategies relating to their historic resources. Given 
the low funding level available to the Division for historic resource surveys, local governments and preservation organizations 
need to find additional sources of funds for this activity which is the foundation of all preservation efforts. </p>
<p>Analysis of the historic resources component of comprehensive plans revealed that communities with Main Street programs, 
Certified Local Governments, and those that relied on a historic preservation planner at the Regional Development Center 
produced the best historic resource sections of comprehensive plans. This suggests that when trained preservation 
professionals or volunteers are active at the local level, historic resources receive more serious consideration. </p>
<p>Local Historic Preservation Commissions </p>
<p>The number of historic preservation commissions has increased rapidly over the past twenty years. In 1976 there were 492 
historic preservation commissions across the country. By 1993, that number had increased to 1,863. From 1981 to 1992 the 
number of commissions grew by over 200%. The majority of these commissions represent small and mid-sized communities. 
Nationwide, 64% of local preservation commissions function in communities of less than 50,000, and of these, one-third have 
populations under 10,000. The number of commissions in small towns continues to grow. </p>
<p>In Georgia the increase is even more dramatic. Georgia had only seven historic preservation commissions in 1976, but by 
1995 the number had grown to 74, following the passage of the Georgia Historic Preservation Act of 1980. From 1981 
through 1994, the number of commissions grew almost 500%. Along with this phenomenal growth has come increased need 
for training, information and funding. Nationwide and in Georgia, 87% of local preservation commissions receive technical 
assistance and information from the State Historic Preservation Office. </p>
<p>Whatever the motivation, communities are adopting preservation ordinances in Georgia at the rate of about 8 per year. People 
living in historic areas in Georgia are seeking and implementing this type of local regulation and protection. </p>
<p>A 1992 study by the Athens Observer illustrates one of the reasons why communities and neighborhoods are opting for local 
designation. The study looked at the average increase in fair market value for 15 streets or neighborhoods in Athens from 
1986 through 1992. Four of the 15 were in locally designated historic districts, while the other eleven were not. Research 
showed that in the eleven non-designated areas, property values increased by about 30%, but in the four designated historic 
areas the value jumped 130%. A similar study in Macon also found that property values increased significantly more in 
neighborhoods designated as local historic districts than in comparable non-designated neighborhoods. </p>
<p>In addition to enhancing property values, local historic district designation can help attract private investment to downtown 
areas, improve the livability of residential neighborhoods, utilize existing infrastructure, and empower local residents to help 
make decisions about how their community will change and grow. </p>
<p>Certified Local Governments </p>
<p>In 1995, 44 Georgia communities participated in the Certified Local Government (CLG) Program. These communities have 
chosen to enter into a &quot;preservation partnership&quot; with the Historic Preservation Division and the National Park Service. By 
passing a historic preservation ordinance and establishing a local commission that complies with the Georgia Historic 
Preservation Act, these communities have made a commitment to actively protect their historic resources. This partnership 
establishes a relationship between the local government and the state and federal agencies providing historic preservation 
services. CLGs benefit by receiving technical assistance and they are eligible for federal grant funds from the Historic 
Preservation Division. </p>
<p>CLG participation as a percentage of total preservation commissions is significantly higher in Georgia than the national 
average. In Georgia almost 60% of commissions are CLGs while nationwide only 48% of commissions are. </p>
<p>Other Local Preservation Efforts </p>
<p>Non-profit preservation organizations lead local preservation efforts in all of Georgia's major cities. Their functions and 
services vary from one town to another, but all are leaders in advocating for preservation. Main Street programs that promote 
downtown revitalization through economic restructuring, organization, design and preservation, and promotion are bringing 
historic downtowns back to life in 35 cities. Local heritage museums house archival collections and genealogical resources, 
and present exhibits on local history and culture. Countless individuals become active in local issues to protect historic 
resources. Owners of historic property continue to protect and rehabilitate their historic properties, sometimes without even 
realizing that they are the backbone of the historic preservation movement. </p>
<p>Needs at the Local Level </p>
<p>The most requested assistance from the local level is funding for the preservation of specific structures within communities. 
Rehabilitation projects can be expensive, and local governments and non-profit organizations often do not have the means to 
carry out these projects without help. In addition, communities and individuals need technical assistance on current 
preservation techniques, materials and design. </p>
<p>Local governments need more funding to undertake and update comprehensive historic resource surveys to better understand 
their historic resources and how to plan for their future. Historic resource inventories can also serve to educate the community 
and local officials about the location and significance of historic places. </p>
<p>Communities also want assistance with enactment of historic preservation ordinances and creation of historic preservation 
commissions. Those communities that already have commissions are in need of more training for commission members. In a 
recent National Alliance of Preservation Commissions survey, 35% of Georgia's commissions stated that they have had no 
training in the last two years. Few commissions have funds to send their members to training; of the commissions responding, 
79% said they have no budget at all. Local and State officials also need education in the economic, aesthetic and legal aspects 
of historic preservation. </p>
<p>Local governments and commissions need more and flexible tools to implement historic preservation programs. For example, 
many communities outside of Georgia have enacted &quot;Conservation Districts&quot; that allow communities to shape change in areas 
that are special assets but that do not yet qualify as historic. Financial incentives tied to local designation or a tax credit for 
residential rehabilitation would act to stimulate the preservation of resources. </p>
<p>Regional Historic Preservation </p>
<p>Many historic preservation activities span municipal boundaries. Local governments must often work together on a regional 
level to accomplish their preservation goals. In addition, especially in rural areas of the state, local expertise on historic 
preservation is not available. Georgia has in place a network of Regional Development Centers (RDCs) which provide 
planning assistance throughout the state. Since 1978, Regional Preservation Planners have been on staff at most of the RDCs 
to assist local governments, groups and individuals with historic preservation activities. Currently, fourteen of the seventeen 
RDCs employ a Regional Preservation Planner. </p>
<p>This program has been extremely effective in bringing the programs of the Historic Preservation Division and other 
preservation related activities to regional and local constituents. With the passage of the Georgia Planning Act of 1989, the 
state has mandated that all communities create a comprehensive plan. Since RDCs produce many of these plans, the Regional 
Preservation Planners have had the opportunity to integrate the preservation of historic resources into the planning process. </p>
<p>The size of Georgia and the large and growing number of requests for assistance make it virtually impossible for the Historic 
Preservation Division to provide all the assistance, visit all the projects, prepare all the plans, and respond to all the requests 
for help in Georgia. Support for continuation and expansion to all areas of the state of the Regional Preservation Planning 
Program is essential for the future of preservation. </p>
<p>Statewide Preservation Network </p>
<p>One of the hallmarks of preservation in Georgia is the strong statewide network and coordination among the various 
preservation interests throughout the state. Georgia is recognized nationally for the strength, size and accomplishments of its 
many preservation organizations, including the Georgia Trust for Historic Preservation, the Historic Preservation Division, the 
Georgia Alliance of Preservation Commissions, Georgians for Preservation Action, UGA's Office of Preservation Services, 
the Georgia Civil War Commission, the African-American Historic Preservation Network, the Society for Georgia 
Archeology, and the four colleges and universities that offer degrees in historic preservation, among others. With so many 
preservation leaders in Georgia's preservation movement, the challenge becomes coordinating efforts so that all preservation 
organizations communicate one preservation message, avoid duplicating services or activities, and work toward shared goals. </p>
<p>Public funding for preservation activities and projects is provided primarily by the Historic Preservation Division. The Division 
passes a large portion of its state and federal appropriations through to state and local government agencies, non-profit 
organizations, and others in the form of grants and contracts for projects. The Georgia Civil War Commission assists with 
funding for battlefield acquisition and other preservation projects related to Civil War resources. </p>
<p>The majority of preservation services are provided by the Historic Preservation Division, the Georgia Trust, and the Office of 
Preservation Services at the University of Georgia, with much help and cooperation from many others. The Historic 
Preservation Division provides a full range of services, including survey, National and Georgia Register of Historic Places 
nominations, planning assistance, environmental review, funding, information and education services, tax incentives, 
architectural technical assistance, archeology technical assistance, training, advocacy, assistance with local government 
preservation activities and ordinances. The Georgia Trust administers house museums and offers services ranging from 
heritage education, Main Street design assistance, and a statewide revolving fund, to advocacy, scholarships and awards, and 
information and education. The Office of Preservation Services provides hands-on assistance and training to local 
governments, information and education services, community planning and design assistance, and advocacy. Many other 
agencies and organizations provide additional preservation assistance and services. </p>
<p>Advocacy on preservation issues is coordinated by Georgians for Preservation Action and the Georgia Trust. Georgians for 
Preservation Action (GaPA) is a grassroots alliance coordinated by the Georgia Trust that brings together all of the major 
preservation groups, all regions of the state, and diverse perspectives to develop a coordinated approach for advocating the 
protection of historic places and support for preservation programs and funding in Georgia and at the national level. The 
Georgia Trust effectively represents its 9,300 members through advocacy activities at the local, state and national levels. </p>
<p>Historic preservation policy of the State of Georgia is carried out primarily by the Historic Preservation Division. The Division 
implements or monitors laws and regulations pertaining to historic resources, proposes or comments on new legislation that 
would promote preservation goals, prepares the historic preservation plan for Georgia, and provides advice on preservation 
policy to the Governor, the Commissioner of Natural Resources, and other agencies. The Division carries out its duties and 
administers its programs uder legislative authority of federal and state law. </p>
<p>Georgia is fortunate to have so many strong and successful statewide preservation leaders. As the preservation constituency 
continues to broaden; as preservation issues become more complex; as the emphasis for preservation continues to shift to the 
local level; as funding and programs that support preservation shrink; and as change continues to transform Georgia, statewide 
organizations and agencies must double their efforts to coordinate and support one another to provide the most effective 
preservation program possible. </p>
<p>Federal and National Preservation Support </p>
<p>The federal government provides the foundation upon which many local and state historic preservation activities are built. The 
National Historic Preservation Act, passed in 1966 and amended in 1980 and 1992, defined national policy on historic 
preservation, established the National Register of Historic Places, created the Advisory Council on Historic Preservation, and 
created the system of State Historic Preservation Offices through which preservation funds and services are provided. 
Sections 106 and 110 of the Act establish the responsibility of all federal agencies to inventory, designate, and protect historic 
properties which they own, and to take historic resources into account in federally funded, licensed and permitted activities. </p>
<p>The National Park Service (NPS) administers the Historic Preservation Fund, from which annual appropriations are made to 
support the mandated activities of State Historic Preservation Offices. The NPS also administers the National Register of 
Historic Places, and many other programs and activities essential to preservation. The National Register criteria and the 
Secretary of the Interior's Standards have become the benchmarks by which historic resources and preservation activities are 
measured. The NPS also develops preservation technical information and distributes it nationwide. </p>
<p>The National Trust for Historic Preservation is the national non-profit historic preservation organization that was chartered by 
Congress in 1949. The National Trust operates house museums, provides funding for preservation projects, advocates for 
preservation, provides information, provides membership services, and works in cooperation with state and local 
organizations to help preserve historic places. Its regional offices are especially helpful in providing technical assistance and 
funding for preservation projects. </p>
<p>Other national organizations, including the National Conference of State Historic Preservation Officers, Preservation Action, 
the Society for American Archeology, and many more, work to promote the preservation and protection of historic places. </p>
<p>Conclusion </p>
<p>The historic preservation network is growing. As the network grows, it becomes more complex, with more issues to cover 
and more points of view to consider. Yet this network of organizations, agencies, and individuals has developed into an 
effective and committed movement working to shape the future of communities in Georgia and throughout the nation. </p>
<p>&#160;</p>
